        "fledge] This and Q fledge mean the same thing. N.E.D. quotes this line, its earliest example, under Fledge v. 4, “To cover with feathers or down”, and defines Fledge a. 1 as “Of young birds (rarely of the wings): Fit to fly, having the feathers fully developed; fledged”.",
        "I will sooner] ABBOTT (1870, §319): There is a slight meaning of purpose, as though it were, “I will sooner make a beard grow,” derived from the similarity in sound of the common phrase “I will sooner die, starve, than, &c.”—[On the use of will here and of shall in I. 22, see FRANZ (3 ed., 1924) §616.]"
