    "53": {
      "play": "PAGE: He’s gone in Smithfield to buy your Worship a",
      "notes": [
        "gone in Smithfield] SUGDEN (1925): Originally the smethe, i.e. smooth, field. An open space between 5 and 6 acres in extent, lying in the triangle formed by Holborn, Aldersgate St., and Charterhouse St., in London. ... It was the market for horses, cattle, sheep, and hay, from very early times until 1855.—COWL (ed. 1923): The allusions, however, to the horses sold in Smithfield that occur in the drama are not generally flattering."
      ]
