    "87": {
      "play": "Setting my knighthood and my soldiership aside, I",
      "notes": [
        "Setting my knighthood and my soldiership aside] Deighton (ed. 1893): If for a moment I may lay aside my knighthood and my dignity as a soldier.—[Falstaff lays aside his knighthood and his soldiership in order to call himself, hypothetically, a liar, as he would not have dared to do if he had had his knighthood and his soldiership on.—Ed.]—Cf. 1 Henry IV II.iii.iii.120, “setting thy knighthood aside, thou art a knave to call me so”; Wilkins, Miseries of Enforced Marriage (Hazlitt’s Dodsley, 1874, ix. 530), “(Setting thy worship’s knighthood aside) he lies in his throat that says so”, cited by Cowl (ed. 1923); Fletcher, Wit at Several Weapons 11.1 (Works of Beaumont & Fletcher, ed. Glover & Waller, 1905–10, ix. 85), “(Setting his Worship aside) he looks like a fool”."
      ]
    },
    "88": {
      "play": "had lied in my throat if I had said so.",
      "notes": [
        "had lied in my throat] Subjunctive in a main clause with condition attached. See Franz (3 ed., 1924) §639."
      ]
    },
    "89": {
      "play": "SERVANT: I pray you, sir, then set your knighthood and",
      "notes": []
    },
    "90": {
      "play": "your soldiership aside, and give me leave to tell you,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "91": {
      "play": "you lie in your throat if you say I am any other than",
      "notes": [
        "lied in my throat] Miss Porter (ed. 1911): The worst lie and most insulting accusation, guarded here by an if, etc.—N.E.D. (Throat sb. 3c): to lie in one’s throat, to lie foully or infamously."
      ]
    },
    "92": {
      "play": "an honest man.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "93": {
      "play": "FALSTAFF: I give thee leave to tell me so? I lay aside that",
      "notes": []
    },
    "94": {
      "play": "which grows to me? If thou gett’st any leave of me,",
      "notes": [
        "grows to me] N.E.D. (Grow v. 3b): To grow to: to be an organic or integral part of. [Obs. Quotes only this line and a passage in Holland's Pliny (1601) as examples.]—Cf. Sonnet xviii. 12, \"When in eternal lines to time thou grow'st\"."
      ]
    },
    "95": {
      "play": "hang me; if thou tak’st leave, thou wert better be",
      "notes": []
    },
    "96": {
      "play": "hanged. You hunt counter. Hence! Avaunt!",
      "notes": [
        "hunt counter] This is apparently a compound noun, but the reading of Q (see textual notes) may be taken as a verb modified by an adverb. Johnson (ed. 1765), following F, explains the phrase by \"blunderer\" and denies any allusion to the Counter (debtors' prison). In this sense or in that of \"base tyke\", \"worthless dog\" (Ritson, 1783, p. 97), with or without the allusion to the prison contended for by T. Davies (1784, i. 284 f.) and Malone (ed. 1790), it has been understood, I judge, by all the editors who follow F, down to Lobban (1915). But Ritson seems to have had doubts about the phrase as a substantive, and Nares (ed. 1888) rejects it thus: \"It seems to be an error to join the two words into one, as if to make a name, in this passage ... Falstaff means rather to tell the man that he is on a wrong scent: 'You are hunting counter;' that is, the wrong way\". As a hunting term counter is thus defined by Onions (1917): \"following the trail in a direction opposite to that which the game has taken\". Onions and many recent editors recognize a quibble on the name of the prison. Auant] N.E.D. (Avaunt B): Begone! be off! away!"
      ]
    },
    "97": {
      "play": "SERVANT: Sir, my lord would speak with you.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "98": {
      "play": "CHIEF JUSTICE: Sir John Falstaff, a word with you.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "99": {
      "play": "FALSTAFF: My good lord. God give your Lordship good",
      "notes": []
    },
    "100": {
      "play": "time of the day. I am glad to see your Lordship",
      "notes": []
    },
    "101": {
      "play": "abroad. I heard say your Lordship was sick. I hope",
      "notes": [
        "goes abroad by advice] N.E.D. (Abroad adv. 3): Out of one's house or abode; out of doors; out in the open air [quoting this line].—[Cf. iv.v.12.]"
      ]
    },
    "102": {
      "play": "your Lordship goes abroad by advice. Your Lordship,",
      "notes": [
        "by advice] N.E.D. (Advice sb. 5): Opinion given or offered as to action; counsel. spec. medical or legal counsel."
      ]
    },
    "103": {
      "play": "though not clean past your youth, have yet",
      "notes": []
    },
    "104": {
      "play": "some smack of an ague in you, some relish of the",
      "notes": [
        "have yet] The reading of Q, have, may be the second person singular with your Lordship and you. If so, hath is probably an emendation, possibly an unconscious substitution, to bring the clause into conformity with the usual practice of using verbs in the third person with subjects like your Lordship.—Ed. smack] N.E.D. (Smack sb.1 3): A trace, tinge, or suggestion of something specified. age] The sense certainly favors the reading of F against Q an ague, and an ague is no doubt a possible unconscious distortion of age. Likewise the editors who read Time in l. 96 instead of Q time in you must assume that in you is an erroneous repetition of the same words in l. 95."
      ]
    },
    "105": {
      "play": "saltness of time in you, and I most humbly beseech",
      "notes": [
        "saltness of time] SCHMIDT (1875): Taste of salt (opposed to the freshness of youth).—N.E.D. gives no help.—ONIONS (1911): (?) ‘Rankness'.—Schmidt's definition is supported by the passage quoted by COWL (ed. 1923) from Middleton's Spanish Gipsy III.i.41-4: \"Rod. The freshness of the morning be upon you both? San. The saltness of the evening be upon you single!\" Curiously enough, salt is associated with youth in Merry Wives II.iii.43, \"We have some salt of our youth in us\"."
      ]
    },
    "106": {
      "play": "your Lordship to have a reverend care of your",
      "notes": [
        "reverend care] N.E.D. (Reverend a. 5): =Reverent a. 2 [i.e.] deeply respectful."
      ]
    },
    "107": {
      "play": "health.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "108": {
      "play": "CHIEF JUSTICE: Sir John, I sent for you before your",
      "notes": []
    },
    "109": {
      "play": "expedition to Shrewsbury.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "110": {
      "play": "FALSTAFF: An ’t please your Lordship, I hear his Majesty",
      "notes": []
    },
    "111": {
      "play": "is returned with some discomfort from Wales.",
      "notes": [
        "some discomfort from Wales] Schmidt (1874): Uneasiness, sorrow."
      ]
    },
    "112": {
      "play": "CHIEF JUSTICE: I talk not of his Majesty. You would not",
      "notes": []
    },
    "113": {
      "play": "come when I sent for you.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "114": {
      "play": "FALSTAFF: And I hear, moreover, his Highness is fallen",
      "notes": []
    },
    "115": {
      "play": "into this same whoreson apoplexy.",
      "notes": [
        "his Highness is fallen] I.e. the king. According to the N.E.D. (Highness sb. 2b), this title was formerly applied to kings and queens; “Majesty” did not become the official style until the reign of James I.",
        "this same whoreson apoplexy] Deighton (ed. 1893): This abominable apoplexy that you know of so well.—N.E.D. (Same a. 5): Appended redundantly to a demonstrative. Common in 16–17th c.; usually expressing some degree of irritation or contempt, sometimes playful familiarity. Now arch.—[Cf. iii. ii. 267, iv. iii. 90; 1 Henry IV i. ii. 180, “this same fat rogue”; i. iii. 230, “that same sword-and-buckler Prince of Wales”; ii. iv. 325–6, “that same mad fellow of the north, Percy”.] Apoplexie] N.E.D. (Apoplexy 1): A malady, very sudden in its attack, which arrests more or less completely the powers of sense and motion [quoting this line].—O. F. Adams (Irving ed., 1888): Historically this is somewhat out of place in the present connexion. Henry’s illness is chronicled by Otterbourne in 1408. Holinshed first speaks of it in 1412. It was said by some that, at the hour when Archbishop Scrope was put to death, Henry was stricken with leprosy. Hall stigmatizes this statement as a falsehood. He and Holinshed call the king’s ailment an apoplexy.—Zeeveld (E.L.H. iii, 1936, p. 323) [quotes the following marginal gloss from Hall, sig. Evi']: Ingendre᷈d of grose humors whiche fil the vessels of the heade from whence the felyng of the body commeth. And therefore they whiche haue this disease are depriued of felyng, speache & mouyng.—Bucknill (1860, p. 149): Falstaff ... describes [the king’s illness] as an apoplexy, and correctly refers to some of its causes and earlier symptoms, lethargic feelings, tingling sensations, deafness."
      ]
    },
    "116": {
      "play": "CHIEF JUSTICE: Well, God mend him. I pray you let me",
      "notes": [
        "God mend him] ONIONS (1911): Restore to health."
      ]
    },
    "117": {
      "play": "speak with you.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "118": {
      "play": "FALSTAFF: This apoplexy, as I take it, is a kind of",
      "notes": [
        "is, as I take it,] Q as I take it? is, except for the punctuation, is perfectly intelligible, and the transposition is at least as likely to have occurred in copying or setting up F."
      ]
    },
    "119": {
      "play": "lethargy, an ’t please your Lordship, a kind of",
      "notes": [
        "sleeping in the blood] See textual notes.—WHITE (ed. 1859): In my judgement, and without a doubt, [the words wanting in F] were omitted ... by design. It is noticeable as a fine stroke of art that, as Falstaff finds his effrontery ineffectual, his courtesy becomes gradually less over-strained, till finally, in the next speech but one to this, he snaps the Chief Justice up.—[Much more likely, the omission was an accident.—ED.]"
      ]
    },
    "120": {
      "play": "sleeping in the blood, a whoreson tingling.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "121": {
      "play": "CHIEF JUSTICE: What tell you me of it? Be it as it is.",
      "notes": [
        "What tell you me of it?] ABBOTT (1870, §253): “For what,” “why”.—[Cf. II.i.56.] The optative subjunctive. See FRANZ (3 ed., 1924) §637, and cf. IV.i.166, 235, IV.iv.108, IV.v.159, 259, V.v.49, 78, Ep. 8."
      ]
    },
    "122": {
      "play": "FALSTAFF: It hath it original from much grief, from",
      "notes": [
        "hath it original] Possessive, = its. See FRANZ (3 ed., 1924) §320. originally] SCHMIDT (1875): Origin."
      ]
    },
    "123": {
      "play": "study, and perturbation of the brain. I have read the",
      "notes": [
        "perturbation of the brain] Miss ANDERSON (1927, p. 71): In Shakespeare, as in Elizabethan treatises [on physiology and psychology], “perturbation” suggests distress of soul rather than of body. [Cf. IV.v.27, Richard III v.iii.159–61, Much Ado II.i.231–2, Macbeth V.i.9–10: the word occurs only 5 times.]"
      ]
    },
    "124": {
      "play": "cause of his effects in Galen. It is a kind of deafness.",
      "notes": [
        "his effects] The usual possessive of it. See FRANZ (3 ed., 1924) §320. Cf. I.ii.148, 194, I.iii.59, II.iii.68, III.i.45, IV.i.46, IV.iv.102."
      ]
    },
    "125": {
      "play": "CHIEF JUSTICE: I think you are fallen into the disease,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "126": {
      "play": "for you hear not what I say to you.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "127": {
      "play": "FALSTAFF: Very well, my lord, very well. Rather, an ’t",
      "notes": []
    },
    "128": {
      "play": "please you, it is the disease of not listening, the",
      "notes": []
    },
    "129": {
      "play": "malady of not marking, that I am troubled withal.",
      "notes": [
        "troubled withal.] SCHMIDT (1875): = With, as placed at the end of the sentence.— [Cf. iv.ii.104.]"
      ]
    },
    "130": {
      "play": "CHIEF JUSTICE: To punish you by the heels would amend",
      "notes": [
        "punish you by the heels] CAMPBELL (1859, pp. 84 f.): To “lay by the heels” was the technical expression for committing to prison.—SCHMIDT (1874): To set you in the stocks. [So also ONIONS (1911).]—DEIGHTON (ed. 1893): There is, perhaps, as Knight suggests, a further allusion to the baffling of a knight by hanging him or his likeness up head downwards. [I cannot find this suggestion in Knight.—Ed.]—N.E.D. (Heel sb.1 18): Lay, set, clap by the heels. To put in irons or the stocks; to fetter, arrest, or confine; also, fig. to overthrow, disgrace.—[See l. 121, imprisonment.]"
      ]
    },
    "131": {
      "play": "the attention of your ears, and I care not if I do",
      "notes": []
    },
    "132": {
      "play": "become your physician.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "133": {
      "play": "FALSTAFF: I am as poor as Job, my lord, but not so",
      "notes": [
        "FALSTAFF:] See textual notes.—THEOBALD (ed. 1733): [The speech-prefix in Q] almost amounts to a self-evident Proof, of [Falstaff’s first having been called Oldcastle]: and that, the Play being printed from the Stage Manuscript, Oldcastle had been all along alter’d into Falstaff, except in this single Place by an Oversight: of which the Printers not being aware, continued these initial Traces of the Original Name.—STEEVENS (Var. ’78; Malone’s Suppl., 1780; Var. ’85), CAPELL (Notes, 1779, p. 170), and MALONE (ed. 1790) all vigorously combat this inference. Steevens maintains that Old. is the abbreviation of some actor’s name; Capell, that Sh. nodded in writing the play, recalling momentarily the name of a character in The Famous Victories; Malone, that the abbreviation “crept” into the text because Falstaff, behind the scenes, was known by the name of his stage predecessor. For further discussion of this point, see the Variorum i Henry IV, pp. 447 ff.—A second important inference drawn from Q here is that Sh. must have finished this play, or at least this much of it, before 25 February 1598, when 1 Henry IV was entered in the Stationers’ register with Falstaff as the name of the leading comic character. This has likewise been denied as well as affirmed. See the discussion of the date of the play, pp. 516 ff. Very well] VAUGHAN (1878, i. 474): ‘Very well’ does not admit, but contradicts, what the Chief Justice has said. ‘Very well’ imports ‘I hear perfectly what you say.’",
        "poor as Job] The poverty as well as the patience of Job is proverbial. Cf. Merry Wives v.v.149, \"as poor as Job\"."
      ]
    },
    "134": {
      "play": "patient. Your Lordship may minister the potion of",
      "notes": []
    },
    "135": {
      "play": "imprisonment to me in respect of poverty, but how",
      "notes": [
        "in respect of poverty] Rann (ed. 1789): [In respect of] my inability to pay a fine.—Vaughan (1878, i. 474): Why should the potion of imprisonment be ministered to Falstaff in respect of poverty? Perhaps Falstaff alludes here to the penal alternative proposed in the legal maxim 'Luat in persona qui luere non potest in crumena.'—Miss Winstanley (ed. 1918): Falstaff is hinting that the Lord Chief-Justice means to imprison him for debt simply because he is poor."
      ]
    },
    "136": {
      "play": "I should be your patient to follow your prescriptions,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "137": {
      "play": "the wise may make some dram of a scruple,",
      "notes": [
        "make some dram of a scruple] N.E.D. (Scruple sb.^2 2b): To make scruple of: to hesitate to believe or admit. Obs. [Quotes this as its earliest example.]—Cowl (ed. 1923): Dram, 60 gr. in apothecary's weight; hence used fig. for a very small quantity.—[Cf. Twelfth Night III.iv.73-6, \"Why, every thing adheres together, that no dram of a scruple, no scruple of a scruple, no obstacle, no incredulous or unsafe circumstance—What can be said?\"; Cymbeline v.v.182, \"whereat I, wretch, Made scruple of his praise\".]"
      ]
    },
    "138": {
      "play": "or indeed a scruple itself.",
      "notes": [
        "or indeed a scruple itself.] Cowl (ed. 1923): With a play on “scruple,” 20 gr. in apothecary’s weight."
      ]
    },
    "139": {
      "play": "CHIEF JUSTICE: I sent for you, when there were matters",
      "notes": []
    },
    "140": {
      "play": "against you for your life, to come speak with me.",
      "notes": [
        "for your life] Specifies an object risked (N.E.D., For prep. gb)."
      ]
    },
    "141": {
      "play": "FALSTAFF: As I was then advised by my learned counsel",
      "notes": [
        "land-service] Theobald (letter to Warburton, 15 Jany. 1729): With how much Humour does Falstaff play on the Law-phrase, & then archly call his Robbing Land-Service? The same phrase, you remember, he again toys with in Anthony [ii.vi.94] \"You have been a great thief by sea. Men. And you by land. Eno. There I deny my land service.\"—But N.E.D., quoting this line, defines the phrase as \"Service performed on land; military, as opposed to naval, service\", and in this sense, or a sense derived from this, it is used in Winter’s Tale III.iii.92. Accordingly many editors take it as a reference to Falstaff’s military status rather than to the robbery on Gadshill (1 Henry IV)."
      ]
    },
    "142": {
      "play": "in the laws of this land-service, I did not come.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "143": {
      "play": "CHIEF JUSTICE: Well, the truth is, Sir John, you live in",
      "notes": []
    },
    "144": {
      "play": "great infamy.",
      "notes": [
        "great infamy.] DELIUS (ed. 1857): Falstaff purposely misunderstands the meaning of infamy, as if it were a material in which he clothed himself."
      ]
    },
    "145": {
      "play": "FALSTAFF: He that buckles himself in my belt cannot",
      "notes": [
        "buckles himself] Though most editors follow F (see textual notes), it is entirely possible that him is merely a typographical error for himself (Q). See p. 506. The rhythm of the F version is probably superior. Either makes perfectly good sense; on the use of the personal pronoun for the reflexive, see FRANZ (3 ed., 1924) §307."
      ]
    },
    "146": {
      "play": "live in less.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "147": {
      "play": "CHIEF JUSTICE: Your means are very slender, and your",
      "notes": [
        "means are very slender] On the difference between Q and F see p. 506."
      ]
    },
    "148": {
      "play": "waste is great.",
      "notes": [
        "waste is great.] The same pun occurs in Lyly’s Endymion iii.iii (Works, ed. Bond, 1902, iii. 44): “Howe thrifty must she be in whom there is no waste” (cited by WURTH (1895), p. 181), and in Merry Wives I.iii.38–40, “Indeed, I am in the waist two yards about; but I am now about no waste; I am about thrift” (cited by RANN, ed. 1789). slenderer] On the difference between Q and F see p. 505."
      ]
    },
    "149": {
      "play": "FALSTAFF: I would it were otherwise. I would my means",
      "notes": []
    },
    "150": {
      "play": "were greater and my waist slender.",
      "notes": []
    },
