      "play": "FALSTAFF: The young prince hath misled me. I am the",
      "notes": [
        "The young prince hath misled me.] See I Henry IV I.iii.89–90."
      ]
    },
    "153": {
      "play": "fellow with the great belly, and he my dog.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "154": {
      "play": "CHIEF JUSTICE: Well, I am loath to gall a new-healed",
      "notes": []
    },
    "155": {
      "play": "wound. Your day’s service at Shrewsbury hath a",
      "notes": [
        "gilded over your night's exploit] This is the earliest example quoted by N.E.D. (Gild v.¹ 7) of gild over meaning “to cover with gilding, so as to conceal defects; chiefly fig.”"
      ]
    },
    "156": {
      "play": "little gilded over your night’s exploit on Gad’s Hill.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "157": {
      "play": "You may thank th’ unquiet time for your quiet",
      "notes": [
        "th' unquiet time] ZEEVELD (E.L.H. iii, 1936, p. 320) notes that Hall’s title for his account of the reign of Henry IV is “The vnquiete tyme of Kyng Henry the fourthe” (see p. 549)."
      ]
    },
    "158": {
      "play": "o’erposting that action.",
      "notes": [
        "o’erposting that action.] N.E.D. (Overpost v.): Obs. To ‘post’ over; to get over (the ground, or any matter) quickly and easily. [Quotes this line only.]—"
      ]
