    "171": {
      "play": "down like his ill angel.",
      "notes": [
        "ill angel.] THEOBALD (ed. 1733): The Lord Chief Justice calls Falstaff the Prince’s ill Angel, or Genius.—Miss GATCH (P.Q. vii, 1928, p. 40) takes this as a reference to the good and evil angels who were stock figures in the moralities.—Cf. II.iv.338.—[It is hard to say whether Q or F preserves what Sh. wrote here; either ill or evil is a possible copyist’s or compositor’s error for the other. No doubt, as Theobald contends, ill better suits Falstaff’s pun, but Sh. uses “evil angel” in Errors IV.iii.18 and Love’s Labour’s Lost I.ii.163 and “evil spirit” in Caesar IV.iii.280; “ill spirit” in Caesar iv.iii.286 and Tempest I.ii.458. See p. 506.—Ed.]"
      ]
    },
    "172": {
      "play": "FALSTAFF: Not so, my lord. Your ill angel is light, but I",
      "notes": []
    },
    "173": {
      "play": "hope he that looks upon me will take me without",
