      "notes": []
    },
    "244": {
      "play": "PAGE: Sir.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "245": {
      "play": "FALSTAFF: What money is in my purse?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "246": {
      "play": "PAGE: Seven groats and two pence.",
      "notes": [
        "Seven groats] Schmidt (1874): Groat, a piece of money valued at four pence."
      ]
    },
    "247": {
      "play": "FALSTAFF: I can get no remedy against this consumption",
      "notes": []
    },
    "248": {
      "play": "of the purse. Borrowing only lingers and lingers",
      "notes": [
        "lingers and lingers] N.E.D. (Linger v. 6a): quasi-trans. with advb. compl. (forth, on, out): To draw out, prolong, protract by lingering, tarrying, or dallying [quoting this line]."
      ]
    },
    "249": {
      "play": "it out, but the disease is incurable. Giving",
      "notes": []
    },
    "250": {
      "play": "papers to the Page. Go bear this letter to my Lord",
      "notes": []
    },
    "251": {
      "play": "of Lancaster, this to the Prince, this to the Earl",
      "notes": []
    },
    "252": {
      "play": "of Westmoreland, and this to old Mistress Ursula,",
      "notes": [
        "Mistress Ursula] Fleay (Wm. Sh., 1886, p. 201), Miss Porter (ed. 1911), Erler (1913, p. 28), Miss Winstanley (ed. 1918), and A. E. Baker (1930, p. 600) all take this as a reference to Mrs. Quickly, who is named Nell in Henry V ii.i.18 &c. While Sh. may very well have been capable of forgetting that he had dubbed the hostess Ursula between the time that he wrote this"
      ]
    },
    "253": {
      "play": "whom I have weekly sworn to marry since I perceived",
      "notes": []
    },
    "254": {
      "play": "the first white hair of my chin. About it. You",
      "notes": [
        "of my chin] Q on, F of."
      ]
    },
    "255": {
      "play": "know where to find me. Page exits. A pox of this",
      "notes": []
    },
    "256": {
      "play": "gout! Or a gout of this pox, for the one or the other",
      "notes": []
    },
    "257": {
      "play": "plays the rogue with my great toe. ’Tis no matter if I",
      "notes": [
        "do halt.] N.E.D. (Halt v.1 1): To be lame, walk lame, limp. arch."
      ]
    },
    "258": {
      "play": "do halt. I have the wars for my color, and my",
      "notes": [
        "wars for my color] N.E.D. (Colour sb. 12b): Allegeable ground or reason, excuse. Obs.—[Cf. v.v.93, 95.] Pension] MORGANN (1777, p. 56): The mention Falstaff here makes of a pension, has I believe been generally contrued to refer rather to hope than possession, yet I know not why: For the possessive my, my pension (not a pension) requires a different construction."
      ]
    },
    "259": {
      "play": "pension shall seem the more reasonable. A good wit",
      "notes": [
        "good wit] See note on l. 157 above."
      ]
    },
    "260": {
      "play": "will make use of anything. I will turn diseases to",
      "notes": []
    },
    "261": {
      "play": "commodity.",
      "notes": [
        "commodity] STEEVENS (Var. ’78): Profit, self-interest.—ROLFE (ed. 1880) quotes Lear iv.i.22, “our mere defects Prove our commodities”."
      ]
    },
    "262": {
      "play": "[He exits.]",
      "notes": []
    }
  },
  "ACT 1, SCENE 3": {
    "1": {
      "play": "[Enter th’ Archbishop of York, Thomas Mowbray (Earl",
      "notes": []
    },
    "2": {
      "play": "Marshal), the Lord Hastings, and Lord Bardolph.]",
      "notes": []
    },
    "3": {
      "play": "ARCHBISHOP: Thus have you heard our cause and known our",
      "notes": [
        "causes] DELIUS (ed. 1857): Our cause is the same as that which Mowbray later calls the occasion of our arms [l. 8]."
      ]
    },
    "4": {
      "play": "means,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "5": {
      "play": "And, my most noble friends, I pray you all",
      "notes": []
    },
    "6": {
      "play": "Speak plainly your opinions of our hopes.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "7": {
      "play": "And first, Lord Marshal, what say you to it?",
      "notes": [
        "Lord Marshall] ONIONS (1911): Officer charged with the arrangement of ceremonies, esp. with the regulation of combats in the lists.—[See D.P. 12.]"
      ]
    },
    "8": {
      "play": "MOWBRAY: I well allow the occasion of our arms,",
      "notes": [
        "allow] SCHMIDT (1874): Grant, admit.",
        "Armes] N.E.D. (Arm sb.² 6): Fighting, war, active hostilities.—[Cf. I. 92 below, iv.i.77, iv.ii.130.]"
      ]
    },
    "9": {
      "play": "But gladly would be better satisfied",
      "notes": []
    },
    "10": {
      "play": "How in our means we should advance ourselves",
      "notes": [
        "in our Meanes] ROLFE (ed. 1880): With the means we have."
      ]
    },
    "11": {
      "play": "To look with forehead bold and big enough",
      "notes": [
        "big] N.E.D. (Big a. 8b): Haughty, pompous, pretentious, boastful. esp. in the quasi-advb. use, To talk, look big."
      ]
    },
    "12": {
      "play": "Upon the power and puissance of the King.",
      "notes": [
        "puissance] ROLFE (ed. 1880): Used as a dissyllable [as here and in II.iii.57] or trisyllable [as in I. 81 below], according to the measure.",
        "case] Q cause is not certainly erroneous; see N.E.D. (Cause sb. 10, \"the case as it concerns any one\"), which quotes Lucrece 1295, \"The cause craves haste\". But typographical error is quite possible.—ED."
      ]
    },
    "13": {
      "play": "HASTINGS: Our present musters grow upon the file",
      "notes": [
        "File] N.E.D. (File sb.2 3c): A catalogue, list, roll. Obs."
      ]
    },
    "14": {
      "play": "To five-and-twenty thousand men of choice,",
      "notes": [
        "fiue and twenty thousand] AX (1912, p. 63): There were at least twenty thousand, according to the chronicle, whereas the dramatist speaks of “five and twenty thousand men of choice,” which fills the verse better than “twenty thousand” would have done.",
        "of choice] N.E.D. (Choice sb. 3): The ‘pick,’ ‘flower,’ elite. [Quotes R. Hawkins, Observations (1622; ed. Bethune, Hakluyt Society, 1847, p. 191), “our enemies [were] thirteen hundred men and boyes ... and those of the choise of Peru”.]—C. D. STEWART (1914, p. 140): The number of men alone is not good enough for [Hastings]; he must raise their value by looking at them as being more than ordinary men."
      ]
    },
    "15": {
      "play": "And our supplies live largely in the hope",
      "notes": [
        "Supplies] N.E.D. (Supply sb. 5): coll. sing. or pl. An additional body of persons; esp. reinforcements of troops. Obs. [Quotes this line.]—[Cf. I. 32 below, IV.ii.48.]",
        "liue] N.E.D. (Live v.1 1b): fig. of things: To exist, be found. poet.→ [The earliest examples quoted are from Sh.]",
        "largely] ONIONS (1911): Bountifully, copiously, abundantly."
      ]
    },
    "16": {
      "play": "Of great Northumberland, whose bosom burns",
      "notes": [
        "an … Iniuries] WALKER (Crit. Exam., 1860, i. 164): I.e., “a fire incensed of (kindled by) injuries.”"
      ]
    },
    "17": {
      "play": "With an incensèd fire of injuries.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "18": {
      "play": "LORD BARDOLPH: The question, then, Lord Hastings, standeth thus:",
      "notes": [
        "] NOBLE (1935, p. 176): Bardolph touches upon the theme of [the parable of the king making war (Luke xiv. 31)]. It was Shakespeare’s object apparently to represent this group of rebels as active in debate but slow in action."
      ]
    },
    "19": {
      "play": "Whether our present five-and-twenty thousand",
      "notes": []
    },
    "20": {
      "play": "May hold up head without Northumberland.",
      "notes": [
        "May] Can. Cf. III.i.69."
      ]
    },
    "21": {
      "play": "HASTINGS: With him we may.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "22": {
      "play": "LORD BARDOLPH: Yea, marry, there’s the point.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "23": {
      "play": "But if without him we be thought too feeble,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "24": {
      "play": "My judgment is we should not step too far",
      "notes": []
    },
    "25": {
      "play": "Till we had his assistance by the hand.",
      "notes": [
        "had] The temporal subjunctive. See FRANZ (3 ed., 1924) §643. Cf. IV.v.110, v.i.90."
      ]
    },
    "26": {
      "play": "For in a theme so bloody-faced as this,",
      "notes": [
        "Theame] N.E.D. (Theme sb. 1b): A subject treated by action (instead of by discourse, etc.); matter, subject. Obs."
      ]
    },
    "27": {
      "play": "Conjecture, expectation, and surmise",
      "notes": []
    },
    "28": {
      "play": "Of aids incertain should not be admitted.",
      "notes": [
        "incertaine] See ABBOTT (1870) §442, FRANZ (3 ed., 1924) §79."
      ]
    },
    "29": {
      "play": "ARCHBISHOP: ’Tis very true, Lord Bardolph, for indeed",
      "notes": []
    },
    "30": {
      "play": "It was young Hotspur’s cause at Shrewsbury.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "31": {
      "play": "LORD BARDOLPH: It was, my lord; who lined himself with hope,",
      "notes": [
        "lin'd] N.E.D. (Line v.1 2): To strengthen by placing something along the side of; to reinforce, fortify. Also fig. Obs.—DELIUS (ed. 1857) quotes 1 Henry IV II.iii.80, \"hath sent for you To line his enterprize\".—ROLFE (ed. 1880) quotes Henry V II.iv.7, \"To line and new repair our towns of war\"."
      ]
    },
    "32": {
      "play": "Eating the air and promise of supply,",
      "notes": [
        "Eating the ayre] DELIUS (ed. 1857): Percy's \"supply\" existed only in the hope of succor from Northumberland and Glendower, and, since he trusted to such airy promises, he fed himself on air. So in Hamlet (III.ii.92) \"I eat the air, promise-crammed\".—N.E.D. (Eat v. 2b): To eat the air: to be 'fed upon air"
      ]
    },
    "33": {
      "play": "Flatt’ring himself in project of a power",
      "notes": [
        "Project] N.E.D. (Project sb. 2): A mental conception, idea, or notion; speculation. Obs. [The only examples earlier than 1727 quoted by N.E.D. are this line and Much Ado iii.i.55, “She cannot love, Nor take no shape nor project of affection”.]"
      ]
    },
    "34": {
      "play": "Much smaller than the smallest of his thoughts,",
      "notes": [
        "] MUSGRAVE (Var. ’78): I.e. which turned out to be much smaller [&c.].—HERFORD (ed. 1899): Smaller in reality than his least exaggerated estimate of it.—SCHMIDT (1875): Thoughts = expectations."
      ]
    },
    "35": {
      "play": "And so, with great imagination",
      "notes": [
        "] MISS ANDERSON (1927, p. 159): Hotspur is the victim of imagination; and a powerful imagination, according to Elizabethan psychology, is likely to enroll the heart against the reason. ... He goes down in defeat made glorious by his very boldness, but to a defeat imminent at the outset because of his inherent tendency to yield to sensitive faculties. Of this weakness in character his friends have been aware.—COWL (ed. 1923) quotes Dream v.i.7-8, “The lunatic, the lover, and the poet Are of imagination all compact”.",
        "imagination] ROLFE (ed. 1880): Metrically six syllables."
      ]
    },
    "36": {
      "play": "Proper to madmen, led his powers to death",
      "notes": [
        "Proper] SCHMIDT (1875): Peculiar, belonging to.",
        "Powers] See note on I.i.206."
      ]
    },
    "37": {
      "play": "And, winking, leapt into destruction.",
      "notes": [
        "] According to JENTE (1926, No. 203), an allusion to the proverb “Look ere ye leap”.",
        "winking] ROLFE (ed. 1880): Shutting his eyes."
      ]
    },
    "38": {
      "play": "HASTINGS: But, by your leave, it never yet did hurt",
      "notes": []
    },
    "39": {
      "play": "To lay down likelihoods and forms of hope.",
      "notes": [
        "formes of hope] DELIUS (ed. 1857): The images or plans which hope forms.—DEIGHTON (ed. 1893): Formal estimates of what we may hope for.—HERFORD (ed. 1899): Probable issues.—COWL (ed. 1923): The shapes that hope assumes."
      ]
    },
    "40": {
      "play": "LORD BARDOLPH: Yes, if this present quality of war —",
      "notes": []
    },
    "41": {
      "play": "Indeed the instant action, a cause on foot—",
      "notes": [
        "of war, indeed of instant action.] The textual notes will show that the editors who have chosen to emend these lines have seized chiefly on if and indeed as corrupt. As a matter of fact, if is not a likely error for in: f does not look like n and does not lie near it in the compositor’s case. Johnson (ed. 1765), after exclaiming, “I know not what to propose, and am afraid that something is omitted, and that the injury is irremediable”, goes on: “Yet, perhaps, the alteration requisite is no more than this: ‘Yes, in this present quality of war, Indeed of instant action.’ It never, says Hastings, did harm to lay down likelihoods of hope. Yes, says Bardolph, it has done harm in this present quality of war, in a state of things, such as is now before us, of war, indeed of instant action. This is obscure, but Mr. Pope’s reading is still less reasonable.” Malone (ed. 1790), although he believed that “the old reading is the true one, and that a line is lost”, adopted Johnson’s in for if (discarding his of for the and changing the punctuation) “because it makes sense,” explaining this reading thus: “Bardolph, I think, means to say, ‘Indeed the present action, (our cause being now on foot, war being actually levied,) lives,’ &c. otherwise the speaker is made to say, in general, that all causes once on foot afford no hopes that may securely be relied on; which is certainly not true.” This emendation, often with further changes in the punctuation, has been adopted by a large number of editors. All of them except White (ed. 1883) and Kittredge (ed. 1936) put a heavy stop after war. White’s paraphrase of this reading (ed. 1859) is as good as any: “Yes, in this present quality, or function, business, of war, it is harmful to lay down likelihoods, &c. Indeed this very action or affair—a cause on foot—is no more hopeful of fruition than the buds of an unseasonably early spring”. Most of the other editors agree with this interpretation, but Lee (ed. 1908) understands l. 41 to mean “any impending action, when war is once declared, merely relies on hope” &c., just as Kittredge must mean “any cause on foot”. The emendation of indeed began with Pope (ed. 1723), but his impede contradicts what Bardolph is undoubtedly trying to say. Of the many other substitutes proposed, induc’d (Henley, Var. ’85; Mason, 1785, p. 187), although never actually adopted, has met with the most favor. It does not seem a profitable expenditure of space to state in full the reasons advanced by the various critics in favor of their emendations. It has also been proposed to understand indeed as a verb. This idea was put forward by Earle (1871, p. 190) and independently revived, without a reference to Earle, by Mackail (T.L.S. 30 Sept. 1926, p. 654) and, with a reference to Earle, by Cunningham (T.L.S. 13 March 1930, p. 214). “‘Indeed the present [sic] action,’” says Mackail, “means ‘bring the present action into effect’—or, as we should now say, realise it. The formation, though rare and possibly unique, like incorse"
      ]
    },
    "42": {
      "play": "Lives so in hope, as in an early spring",
      "notes": []
    },
    "43": {
      "play": "We see th’ appearing buds, which to prove fruit",
      "notes": [
        "which ... fruite] ABBOTT (1870, §354) explains this as the object of gives. There are other examples of (pro)noun and infinitive used as object, e.g., Winter’s Tale III.ii.213, “I have deserved All tongues to talk their bit- terest”."
      ]
    },
    "44": {
      "play": "Hope gives not so much warrant as despair",
      "notes": []
    },
    "45": {
      "play": "That frosts will bite them. When we mean to build,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "46": {
      "play": "We first survey the plot, then draw the model,",
      "notes": [
        "Modell] N.E.D. (Model sb. 1): An architect’s set of designs for a projected building. [Obs.] [Quotes this line.]"
      ]
    },
    "47": {
      "play": "And when we see the figure of the house,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "48": {
      "play": "Then must we rate the cost of the erection,",
      "notes": [
        "rate] N.E.D. (Rate v.1): To reckon, calculate, estimate, the amount or sum of. Now rare. [Quotes this line as its earliest example.]"
      ]
    },
    "49": {
      "play": "Which if we find outweighs ability,",
      "notes": [
        "] On the construction see FRANZ (3 ed., 1924) §347.",
        "out-weighes] N.E.D. quotes this line as the earliest example of the use of the word in the language (Outweigh v. 1, “to be too heavy or onerous for”)."
      ]
    },
    "50": {
      "play": "What do we then but draw anew the model",
      "notes": []
    },
    "51": {
      "play": "In fewer offices, or at least desist",
      "notes": [
        "offices] N.E.D. (Office sb. 9): pl. The parts of a house, or buildings attached to a house, specially devoted to household work or service.",
        "at least] Clarke (ed. 1865): “Least” has been altered to ‘last’ here; but we think it possible that “at least” is here used in the sense of ‘at worst,’ ‘supposing the least advantageous prospect,’ ‘in case the project wear the aspect least propitious.’—Cowl (ed. 1923): “At least” is, in fact, sometimes used where the sense requires “at most”. Thus in Jonson, The Magnetic Lady v.i [ed. Herford & Simpson, 1925+, vi. 571]: “stay you for us ... wee’ll ... meet you there within this Quarter at least” and Tale of a Tub v.i [op. cit. iii. 79]: “till I come—which shall be Within an houre at least”. Cf. Shakespeare’s use of “less” “with words expressing or implying a negative, where the sense requires ‘more’” (Onions), as in Winter’s Tale iii.ii.54 [“I ne’er heard yet That any of these bolder vices wanted Less impudence to gainsay what they did Than to perform it first”] and Coriolanus i.iv.14 and similarly “lesser” in Troilus and Cressida i.i.28 [“Patience herself ... Doth lesser blench at sufferance than I do”]. “At least” may therefore, perhaps, be construed in the text as “at most, at the utmost, as an extreme measure”."
      ]
    },
    "52": {
      "play": "To build at all? Much more in this great work,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "53": {
      "play": "Which is almost to pluck a kingdom down",
      "notes": []
    },
    "54": {
      "play": "And set another up, should we survey",
      "notes": []
    },
    "55": {
      "play": "The plot of situation and the model,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "56": {
      "play": "Consent upon a sure foundation,",
      "notes": [
        "Consent] Schmidt (1874): Agree or come to an agreement."
      ]
    },
    "57": {
      "play": "Question surveyors, know our own estate,",
      "notes": [
        "Surveyors] N.E.D. (Surveyor 2): A practical architect.",
        "estate] Schmidt (1874): Fortune, property, possessions."
      ]
    },
    "58": {
      "play": "How able such a work to undergo,",
      "notes": [
        "vndertog] Schmidt (1875): To take upon one’s self, to undertake, to perform. [This example of the word is a trifle earlier than the earliest quoted by N.E.D., Caesar i.iii.123.]"
      ]
    },
    "59": {
      "play": "To weigh against his opposite. Or else",
      "notes": [
        "To weigh] The construction here offers some difficulty. Some editors"
      ]
    },
    "60": {
      "play": "We fortify in paper and in figures,",
      "notes": [
        "in] On. See note on I.ii.147.",
        "in Paper, and in Figures] SCHULZE (1908, p. 26): By means of figures on paper [hendiadys]."
      ]
    },
    "61": {
      "play": "Using the names of men instead of men,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "62": {
      "play": "Like one that draws the model of an house",
      "notes": [
        "one ... a] Q on is doubtless a mere typographical error, but Q an, before house, is not in the least surprising. See FRANZ (3 ed., 1924) §270.",
        "that] Who. See note on I.i.114."
      ]
    },
    "63": {
      "play": "Beyond his power to build it, who, half through,",
      "notes": [
        "thorough] As this and Q thorough are synonyms, either could be accidentally substituted for the other. No doubt the editors adopt through because it makes the verse normal, but thorough is also perfectly possible from the metrical point of view.—ED."
      ]
    },
    "64": {
      "play": "Gives o’er and leaves his part-created cost",
      "notes": [
        "Cost] CAPELL (Notes, 1779, p. 171): “Cost” is put figuratively for the building erected by it.—N.E.D. (Cost sb.² 4): That on which money, etc. is expended. Obs. rare. [Quotes this line.]—KEIGHTLEY (Sh.-Expositor, 1867, p. 240) quotes Sonnet lxiv, “When I have seen by Time’s fell hand defaced The rich-proud cost of outworn buried age”.—COWL (ed. 1923): Perhaps an echo of Edward III (1596), I.ii.: “the vpper turfe of earth doth boast His pide perfumes and party colloured cost”."
      ]
    },
    "65": {
      "play": "A naked subject to the weeping clouds",
      "notes": [
        "subiect] N.E.D. (Subject sb. 12c): One who or a thing which is subject to something injurious. Obs. [Quotes only one other example and this line.]",
        "Weeping Clouds] DEIGHTON (ed. 1893) detects here an implication that the clouds, pouring down rain, “seem to bewail the builder’s folly”. This seems to me unnecessary.—ED."
      ]
    },
    "66": {
      "play": "And waste for churlish winter’s tyranny.",
      "notes": [
        "When ... tyranny] Q. D. (1 N. & Q. viii, 22 Oct. 1853, p. 384): “Whiche of you disposed to buylde a towre, sitteth not downe before, and counteth the coste, whether he haue sufficient to perfourme it? Lest at any time after he hath layd the fundation, and is not hable to perfourme it, al that beholde it, beginne to mocke hym, Sayeing: This man beganne to buylde, and was not hable to make an ende.” [Luke xiv. 28-30.]—NOBLE (1935, p. 176): Usually Shakespeare condenses in his paraphrases of Parables. ... Here Lord Bardolph is prolix and repeats himself. The audience familiar with the parable in question could follow each detail with interest, otherwise an argument of such length would have wearied. Possibly on this account it was omitted in the Quarto.—FRIPP (Sh.’s Stratford, 1928, p. 44), Miss SPURGEON (1935, p. 296 n.), and MURRY (1936, pp. 33 f.) all connect this speech with Sh.’s purchase of New Place in 1597 and the presumptive rebuilding of the house, as an echo of personal experience.",
        "waste] N.E.D. (Waste sb. 6c): Something wasted or destroyed. Obs. [A use of the word apparently peculiar to Sh.; N.E.D. quotes only Sonnet xii. 10, \"the wastes of time\", and a passage from Suckling imitating this sonnet.]",
        "churlish] N.E.D. (Churlish a. 2b): Of beasts, natural forces and agents: Violent, rough, etc. (Now only fig.)"
      ]
    },
    "67": {
      "play": "HASTINGS: Grant that our hopes, yet likely of fair birth,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "68": {
      "play": "Should be stillborn and that we now possessed",
      "notes": []
    },
    "69": {
      "play": "The utmost man of expectation,",
      "notes": [
        "a] RIDLEY (ed. 1934): For the sake of a reading that makes sense I have accepted F’s facile emendation of the Q [see textual notes], but the emendation carries singularly little conviction.—[Q so, is undoubtedly an error and F a may be an emendation, facile or otherwise, but it is not impossible that F preserves the reading of Sh.’s MS., misrepresented by Q. But I should not like to be called on to explain how a happened to look like so., See p. 506.—Ed.]"
      ]
    },
    "70": {
      "play": "I think we are a body strong enough,",
      "notes": [
        "Body] The line is the earliest example quoted by N.E.D. of its sense 16, \"An organized collection of fighting men acting together\"."
      ]
    },
    "71": {
      "play": "Even as we are, to equal with the King.",
      "notes": [
        "who] ABBOTT (1870, §263): For \"and he,\" \"for he\" &c.",
        "equall with] N.E.D. (Equal v. 4): To cope on equal terms with (obs. rare) [quoting this line]."
      ]
    },
    "72": {
      "play": "LORD BARDOLPH: What, is the King but five-and-twenty thousand?",
      "notes": [
        "] Ax (1912, p. 63): The royal forces commented upon by the lords are not mentioned in Sh.'s source."
      ]
    },
    "73": {
      "play": "HASTINGS: To us no more, nay, not so much, Lord Bardolph,",
      "notes": [
        "To vs] DEIGHTON (ed. 1893): So far as we are concerned."
      ]
    },
    "74": {
      "play": "For his divisions, as the times do brawl,",
      "notes": [
        "] Ax (1912, p. 63): The rebels’ hope that the King would be forced to divide his troops, is well founded, and the words ll. agree with the chronicle.",
        "as ... braul] COWL (ed. 1923): To correspond to the number of wars that are on foot.",
        "braul] N.E.D. (Brawl v.1): To wrangle, to squabble. (In very early use and in [this line] it was perhaps simply ‘to contend, strive, quarrel.’)"
      ]
    },
    "75": {
      "play": "Are in three heads: one power against the French,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "76": {
      "play": "And one against Glendower; perforce a third",
      "notes": []
    },
    "77": {
      "play": "Must take up us. So is the unfirm king",
      "notes": [
        "take vp] Schmidt (1875): To oppose, to encounter, to cope with. [This line is the earliest example quoted by N.E.D. of this obsolete sense.]—Rolfe (ed. 1880) quotes Coriolanus iii.i.244, “I could myself Take up a brace o’ the best of them”.",
        "vnfirme] Schmidt (1875): Weak.—So also Onions and various editors. The N.E.D., however, gives no example of the word in this sense earlier than 1616."
      ]
    },
    "78": {
      "play": "In three divided, and his coffers sound",
      "notes": [
        "his ... Emptinesse] Ax (1912, p. 64): On almost every page of the chronicle, Sh. could find passages, in which the monarch’s pecuniary embarrassment is spoken of: and the fact that “his coffers sounded with hollow poverty and emptiness”, was certainly for the actual rebels of history also an additional reason for stirring.—Cowl (ed. 1923): Craig refers to the proverb, quoted in Henry V iv.iv.68: “The empty vessel makes the greatest sound”."
      ]
    },
    "79": {
      "play": "With hollow poverty and emptiness.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "80": {
      "play": "ARCHBISHOP: That he should draw his several strengths together",
      "notes": []
    },
    "81": {
      "play": "And come against us in full puissance",
      "notes": []
    },
    "82": {
      "play": "Need not to be dreaded.",
      "notes": [
        "Need] N.E.D. (Need v.²): The irregular form need in the 3rd pers. sing. of the present tense (in place of needs or needeth) becomes fairly common in the 16th c.",
        "be] Q to be. If editors had had only Q to follow they would print to be without hesitation, but since F authorizes them to leave out to they almost unanimously prefer the ten-syllable verse. It is of course perfectly possible for a compositor or copyist to interpolate the sign of the infinitive, but accidental omission is an even more common typographical error.—Ed."
      ]
    },
    "83": {
      "play": "HASTINGS: If he should do so,",
      "notes": [
        "] See textual notes.—Johnson (ed. 1765): These lines, which were evidently printed [in Q] from an interlined copy not understood, are properly regulated in [F], and are here only mentioned to show what errors may be suspected to remain.—Capell (Notes, 1779, p. 171): The casual omission of “To” in the quarto impressions, set at work some amender or other, and produc’d a very different line.—Cowl (ed. 1923): The printer of Q seems to have misread his “copy”; perhaps the words French and Welch were there written in, as a correction, between lines 83 and 84, or in the margin on a level with line 83. The printer attempted to amend the sense by altering the to they (baying).—[That the MS. at this point was difficult for the Q compositor to read seems all the more probable from the fact that he set up the whole speech as prose. Capell is not necessarily right: since F is intelligible it is not unreasonable to assume that it preserves what Sh. wrote. If we assume that Sh. wrote “If he should do so” as a separate line and then, on the next line, “He leaves his backe vnarm’d”, and that “the French, and Welch” is an addition or substitution (perhaps for the they which F omits) written above or beside the line, I think we can understand how the Q compositor might have put the last phrase in the wrong place and how some transcriber whose work sooner or later was incorporated in F may have deciphered the author’s intention more accurately. Some editors, however, prefer emending Q to adopting F.—Ed.]"
      ]
    },
    "84": {
      "play": "He leaves his back unarmed, the French and Welsh",
      "notes": [
        "leaues] Abbott (1870, §371): [In conditional sentences,] sometimes the consequent is put graphically in the present merely for vividness. Cf. iv.i.204, v.ii.75.",
        "Baying] N.E.D. (Bay v.1 5): To pursue with barking like a pack of hounds; to drive to bay with barking [quoting Dream iv.iv.110 and this line as its earliest examples]."
      ]
    },
    "85": {
      "play": "Baying him at the heels. Never fear that.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "86": {
      "play": "LORD BARDOLPH: Who is it like should lead his forces hither?",
      "notes": [
        "] DANIEL (N.S.S. Trans. 1877–9, p. 282): It will be observed that Lord Bardolph is ignorant, until informed by Hastings, that the force directed against them is lead by Prince John; yet in sc. i he was present when Morton informed Northumberland of this fact.—[See notes on I.i.44, 177, III.ii.320.]"
      ]
    },
    "87": {
      "play": "HASTINGS: The Duke of Lancaster and Westmoreland;",
      "notes": [
        "The Duke of Lancaster] See D.P. 7."
      ]
    },
    "88": {
      "play": "Against the Welsh, himself and Harry Monmouth;",
      "notes": [
        "himself ... Monmouth] Ax (1912, p. 64): The conspirators in the play suppose the Prince to be in Wales in his father’s company: and probably Sh. remembers here what the King had said at the end of the first part [v.v.39]: “Myself and you, son Harry, will towards Wales”. We could however not find in the chronicle a definite indication of the Prince’s whereabouts at this time. Perhaps he was in Wales in the early spring of that year , for we read in the poet’s authority, iii. 527–8, “In the meane time, to wit the fifteenth of March at a place in Wales called Huske, in a conflict fought betwixt the Welshmen and certeine of the princes companie, the sonne of Owen Glendouer was taken, and fifteene hundred Welshmen taken and slaine”. He is likely to have joined the King, his father, when the latter abandoned his Welsh expedition in order to push towards the north."
      ]
    },
    "89": {
      "play": "But who is substituted against the French",
      "notes": [
        "substituted] N.E.D. (Substitute v. 1c): To depute, delegate. Obs. [Possibly an innovation of Sh.’s; N.E.D. quotes only one other example, dated 1700.]",
        "'gainst] I suppose most students will agree that Sh. could hardly have written substituted against. If so, Q against is the compositor’s unconscious substitution of the uncontracted for the contracted form and F preserves what Sh. wrote. Curiously enough, the preceding note may be thought to lend some plausibility to Ridley’s emendation.—Ed."
      ]
    },
    "90": {
      "play": "I have no certain notice.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "91": {
      "play": "ARCHBISHOP: Let us on,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "92": {
      "play": "And publish the occasion of our arms.",
      "notes": [
        "our Armes] See note on l. 8 above."
      ]
    },
    "93": {
      "play": "The commonwealth is sick of their own choice.",
      "notes": [
        "] See CLEMEN (1936, pp. 261 ff.) on the use of sickness etc. as an image of political disaffection or civil disorder, very common in the history plays. Cf. iii.1.4 ff., iv.i.63 ff., iv.i.233.",
        "The Common-wealth is ... their] CLARKE (ed. 1865): An instance of Shakespeare's use of a collective noun with a verb in the singular and a pronoun in the plural."
      ]
    },
    "94": {
      "play": "Their over-greedy love hath surfeited.",
      "notes": [
        "surfeited] N.E.D. (Surfeit v. 4): To fall sick in consequence of excess. Now rare or Obs.",
        "] MISS SPURGEON (1935, p. 120): [Sh.’s] disgust at over-eating, which was probably ... common [in his time], is clearly to be seen in his many images from surfeit and its results. [Cf. iv.i.64.]"
      ]
    },
    "95": {
      "play": "An habitation giddy and unsure",
      "notes": [
        "] CARTER (1905, p. 271): Luke vi. 49—\"Is like a man that without fundation built an house vpon the earth: agaynst which the fludde did beate vehemently, and it fel immediately, and the fal of that house was great.\"—NOBLE (1935, p. 176): The Archbishop, like the Bishop of Carlisle in Richard II, had a reputation for learning and piety. Hence in each case Shakespeare's use of Scriptural parallels.",
        "giddy] N.E.D. (Giddy 2): Having a confused sensation of swimming or whirling in the head, with proneness to fall. [Possibly Sh. was thinking more of the idea of \"prone to fall\" than of the rest of the meaning of the word.]"
      ]
    },
    "96": {
      "play": "Hath he that buildeth on the vulgar heart.",
      "notes": [
        "vulgar] ONIONS (1911): Of the common people, plebeian."
      ]
    },
    "97": {
      "play": "O thou fond many, with what loud applause",
      "notes": [
        "fond] SCHMIDT (1874): Foolish.",
        "Many] DOUCE (apud Steevens, ed. 1793): Many or meyny, from the French mesnie, a multitude.—ABBOTT (1870, §87): [Used in the manner of] the old noun \"many,\" \"a many men,\" for \"a many (of) men.\"—N.E.D. (Many sb. 2): Multitude. [Obs.]",
        "] Miss WINSTANLEY (ed. 1918): The scene is described in Richard II v.ii.11 ff."
      ]
    },
    "98": {
      "play": "Didst thou beat heaven with blessing Bolingbroke",
      "notes": [
        "beate ... Bullingbrooke] COWL (ed. 1923): Assail heaven, smite repeatedly the vault of heaven, with prayers."
      ]
    },
    "99": {
      "play": "Before he was what thou wouldst have him be.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "100": {
      "play": "And being now trimmed in thine own desires,",
      "notes": [
        "trimm'd] This figure has drawn murmurs of perplexity from Schmidt and some editors, but is sufficiently explained by the N.E.D. (Trim v. 7), “To array, dress (const. in or with something)”, i.e. “decked out in the blessings which you courted, sc. the accession of Henry to the throne” (DEIGHTON, ed. 1893). VAUGHAN (1886, i. 499) describes the metaphor as “culinary” and Miss PORTER (ed. 1911) as nautical (“in full trim”, said of a ship fully equipped)."
      ]
    },
    "101": {
      "play": "Thou, beastly feeder, art so full of him",
      "notes": []
    },
    "102": {
      "play": "That thou provok’st thyself to cast him up.",
      "notes": [
        "] DEIGHTON (ed. 1893): An allusion to the taking of emetics in order to stir up the stomach to reject food that is obnoxious to it."
      ]
    },
    "103": {
      "play": "So, so, thou common dog, didst thou disgorge",
      "notes": [
        "common Dogge] DEIGHTON (ed. 1893): A low-bred hound that will greedily eat any food; with a play on the word common in reference to the common people, the commonalty."
      ]
    },
    "104": {
      "play": "Thy glutton bosom of the royal Richard,",
      "notes": [
        "bosome] CLARKE (ed. 1865): The word “bosom” is here most comprehensively employed. Shakespeare uses it elsewhere in the sense of ‘cherished desire,’ ‘heartiest wish’; and in the sense of ‘stomach.’ Here, in its application to the metaphor of the “dog,” it bears the latter sense; while in its reference to the popular affection, the general inclination altering towards Bolingbroke and Richard, it includes the former sense."
      ]
    },
    "105": {
      "play": "And now thou wouldst eat thy dead vomit up",
      "notes": [
        "dead vomit] WORDSWORTH (1864, p. 331): The ‘dog returning to his vomit,’ of S. Peter, 2 Ep. ii. 22, and of Proverbs xxvi. 11.—Miss PORTER (ed. 1911) notes that the latter text is quoted in Henry V iii.vii.63-4—in the words of the French Olivetan version, according to NOBLE (1935, p. 177)."
      ]
    },
    "106": {
      "play": "And howl’st to find it. What trust is in these",
      "notes": [
        "trust] N.E.D. (Trust sb. 4): The quality of being trustworthy. Now rare. [Quotes Romeo iii.ii.85, “There’s no trust, No faith, no honesty in men”.]"
      ]
    },
    "107": {
      "play": "times?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "108": {
      "play": "They that, when Richard lived, would have him die",
      "notes": []
    },
    "109": {
      "play": "Are now become enamored on his grave.",
      "notes": [
        "enamour'd on] Cf. 1 Henry IV v.ii.70-1:—On the frequent use of on where of is now usual, see Abbott (1870) §182, who attributes it to the confounding of the two prepositions in the contracted form o’, and Franz (3 ed., 1924) §500. Cf. iii.i.33, iii.i.63 (Q), II.iv.94, iv.iii.50 (Q).",
        "] ROLFE (ed. 1880) quotes Richard II v.ii.30; DEIGHTON (ed. 1893), ib. v.ii.6."
      ]
    },
    "110": {
      "play": "Thou, that threw’st dust upon his goodly head",
      "notes": []
    },
    "111": {
      "play": "When through proud London he came sighing on",
      "notes": []
    },
    "112": {
      "play": "After th’ admirèd heels of Bolingbroke,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "113": {
      "play": "Criest now “O earth, yield us that king again,",
      "notes": [
        "yet] Still (N.E.D., Yet adv. 2)."
      ]
    },
    "114": {
      "play": "And take thou this!” O thoughts of men accursed!",
      "notes": [
        "] COLLIER (ed. 1842): Printed in Italic type, and with inverted commas at the commencement of it, as if to point it out as a quotable axiom, or possibly as if it were itself a quotation."
      ]
    },
    "115": {
      "play": "Past and to come seems best; things present,",
      "notes": [
        "seemes] The third person plural in -s. See ABBOTT (1870) §§333, FRANZ (3 ed., 1924) §§154, 673, 679. Cf. iii.i.54, iv.iii.105, iv.v.90, v.iii.34 (Q), v.v.56 (Q), and note on iv.i.93."
      ]
    },
    "116": {
      "play": "worst.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "117": {
      "play": "MOWBRAY: Shall we go draw our numbers and set on?",
      "notes": [
        "draw] SCHMIDT (1874): To assemble. [Obs.]",
        "numbers] SCHMIDT (1875): Host, army. [N.E.D. does not define the word in this sense, but obviously such is its meaning. Cf. ii.iii.46.]",
        "set on] SCHMIDT (1875): To begin a march or journey or walk.—[Cf. v.v.79.]"
      ]
    },
    "118": {
      "play": "HASTINGS: We are time’s subjects, and time bids begone.",
      "notes": [
        "We … subiects] COWL (ed. 1923) quotes 1 Henry IV v.iv.81, “But thought’s the slave of life, and life time’s fool”."
      ]
    },
    "119": {
      "play": "[They exit.]",
      "notes": []
    },
    "154": {
      "notes": [
        "power] See note on I.i.149."
      ]
    },
    "215": {
      "notes": [
        "] BÜTTNER (1904, p. 83) argues that the archbishop is not justified in the event because of the jubilation in the rebel camp when the truce is announced (iv.ii.94 ff.)."
      ]
    },
    "237": {
      "notes": [
        "] Miss WINSTANLEY (ed. 1918): As many men as we can possibly expect."
      ]
    }
  },
  "ACT 2, SCENE 1": {
    "1": {
      "play": "[Enter Hostess Quickly of the tavern with two Officers,",
      "notes": [
        "Enter ...] On the indefiniteness of the Q stage-direction see p. 491. On the F stage-direction see pp. 512 ff.—Fang's boy was added by CAPELL on the supposition that he is needed to be asked “Sirrah, where’s Snare?” But sirrah might just as well be addressed to Snare; when he doesn’t reply, Fang looks round and asks “Where’s Snare?” I am afraid that the editors have foisted upon Sh. a character whom he never thought of.—ED. 2. Fang, and Snare] COWL (ed. 1923): Fang and Snare are respectively the sergeant and his yeoman. 3. Mr.] COWL (ed. 1923): The Hostess, blunderingly, or from a desire to be on the right side of the two officers, confers on them a title not warranted by their rank. 3. entred the Action] SCHMIDT (1874): Commenced a lawsuit. 5.] MORGAN (1777, pp. 29 f.) takes the fact that the hostess hires two officers to arrest Falstaff as evidence of his valor. 5. Yeoman] N.E.D. (Yeoman 1b): An attendant or assistant to an official, etc. 5. Is it] N.E.D. (It pron. 1b): Used contemptuously or humorously of a person. 6. stand to it] N.E.D. (Stand v. 76c): To stand to it, to fight stoutly. 13. chance] N.E.D. (Chance sb. C): As adv.: By chance, perchance, haply. arch. 15. Alas ... beastly] Furnivall (Old Sp. ed., 1909, p. 102): Should perhaps be set as verse, thus: Alas ... me In ... faith. 15. stabd ... weapon ... foyne] Delius (ed. 1857): To stab is used with the same indecent double meaning as the hostess uses it here in Caesar: \"if Caesar had stabbed their mothers, they would have done no less\".—Wurth (1895, p. 60): The hostess understands to stab, intended in its proper sense, in an obscene sense.—Stoll (M.P. xii, 1914, p. 209) extends the quibble to weapon, foin, and also thrust. 16. and that] On the difference between Q and F see p. 505. 18. foyne] N.E.D. (Foin v. 1): intr. To make a thrust with a pointed weapon. arch. 20. close] N.E.D. (Close v. 13): To come to close quarters or to grips; to engage in hand-to-hand fight, grapple with. 21. nor I neither] See note on 1 Henry IV. 22.] Furnivall (Old Sp. ed., 1909, pp. 102 f.) thinks this may be one line of doggerel verse. 22. fist] Schmidt (1874): To grasp.—N.E.D. (Fist v.1 2): To strike with the fist, beat, punch. 23. Vice] Pope (ed. 1723): Grasp, a metaphor taken from a smith’s vice.—[Q view is obviously a misreading.—Ed.] 24. vndone] Onions (1911): Ruined. 24. with his going] Rann (ed. 1789): If he goes upon this expedition, and leaves my debt unpaid. 24. with] By. See Abbott (1870) §193, Franz (3 ed., 1924) §535. 24. I warrant] N.E.D. (Warrant v. 4a): Often used colloq. as a mere expression of strong belief = ‘I’ll be bound’. 25. infinituie] Delius (ed. 1857): The hostess ... would say infinite.—Miss Hanscom (ed. 1912): It is useless to attempt an explanation of Mistress Quickly’s expressions. It should be noted, however, that her vocabulary is large and far from illiterate. 25. my score] Onions (1911): Account kept by means of tallies or marks on a door, &c. 26. sure] ONIONS (1911): (With the verbs hold, guard) unable to do harm, harmless. 27. continuantly] N.E.D. (Continuantly adv.): A humorous perversion: cf. Continuately.—DELIUS (ed. 1857) and most others take it as a perversion of incontinently. 27. Py-Corner] SUGDEN (1925, p. 411): The corner of Giltspur St. and Cock Lane in W. Smithfield, London. It was so called from the cooks’ shops which stood there. 28. saving your manhoods] SCHMIDT (1875): All due respect shown to, no offence to [your manhoods]. Especially used to apologize for the boldness or impropriety of an expression.—COWL (ed. 1923): The allusion ... is to the native offensiveness of Pie-corner to refined noses and ears. 29. indited] SCHMIDT (1874): Blunderingly for invite[d]. 29. Lubbar's head] JOHNSON (ed. 1765): This is, I suppose, a colloquial corruption of the Libbard’s head.—COWL (ed. 1923): The sign was appropriate to a silkman’s establishment. 29. Lombardstreet] SUGDEN (1925, p. 312): Running from the Mansion House to Gracechurch Street. 32. brought in] COWL (ed. 1923): Sc. into court. 32. to his answer] N.E.D. (To prep. 8): For the purpose of. 33. Mark] See note on I.ii.176. 33. a long one] THEOBALD (letter to Warburton): A long one, [of w]hat? a long Mark? That’s the only antecedent Subst[antive] it can agree with; & com[mon sense] won’t admit of its being coupled to That. I need not to observe to You, how famili[ar it is w]th our Poet to play the Chimes upon Words similar in Sound, & differing in Signifi[cation. I] doubt not, but you’ll read w[ith me—A hundred Marks is a long t]ONE [for a poor lone] woman to bear; [i.e. one hundred marks is a] good round sumie for a poor Widow to venture on Trust. 34. lone woman] STEEVENS (ed. 1793): An unmarried woman.—N.E.D. (Lone a. 2): Unmarried; single or widowed. 35. fub'd off] N.E.D. (Fob v.1 3a): Fob off. To put off deceitfully. 45. whose ... dead?] SCHMIDT (1875): Proverbial phrase = what is the matter? what is amiss? 49. Varlets] SCHMIDT (1875): A term of reproach, = knave, rascal.—COWL (ed. 1923) notes that the word also means sergeant. 49. draw Bardolfe] MORGAN (1777, p. 30): When they lay hold on him he resists to the utmost of his power, and calls upon Bardolph, whose arms are at liberty, to draw. 49. me] See note on l. 38 above. 50. Queane] N.E.D. (Quean 1): A bold, impudent, or ill-behaved woman; a jade, hussy; and spec. a harlot, strumpet. 51. Channel] N.E.D. (Channel sb.1 3a): The watercourse in a street or by a roadway, the gutter. 51. there] On the difference between Q and F see p. 506. 52.] Miss MACKENZIE (1924, p. 105): When the battle is joined she dances round the outskirts of the fray in “a tempest of exclamation”. 53. bastardly] COWL (ed. 1923): A portmanteau word, blending “bastard” and “dastardly”. 54. Hony-suckle ... hony-seed] THEOBALD (ed. 1733): [Hony-seed] instead of homicide.—HANMER (ed. 1743): She means to say, homicidal villain, and homicide rogue. 57. Man-queller] SCHMIDT (1875): Murderer. 59. rescu] N.E.D. (Rescue sb. 2): Law. The forcible taking of a person or goods out of legal custody. 60. bring a rescu] Q bring a reskew or two.—DELIUS (ed. 1857): The hostess understands the cry a rescue as though rescue were the name of a particular person.—DEIGHTON (ed. 1893): The Hostess takes the word to be some weapon that the officer called for. 61. Thou wilt not?] Q wot is a dialectal form of will derived, according to FRANZ (3 ed., 1924, §176), from M.E. wolt. 61. Do, do] SCHMIDT (1874): Used as a term of encouragement (= go on!). 62. Hempseed] DELIUS (ed. 1872): One who ought to be hanged. 63. Page] JOHNSON (ed. 1765): This speech is given to the page in all the editions to the folio of 1664. It is more proper for Falstaff, but that the boy must not stand quite silent and useless on the stage.—CAPELL (Notes, 1779, p. 172): Care, judgment, faithfulness, all the qualities with which an editor ought to be gifted, are display’d in the assignment of this speech by the moderns to Falstaff... 63. Scullion] SCHMIDT (1875): The lowest domestic servant, that washes the kettles and dishes in the kitchen; used as a term of contempt. 63. Rampallian] GENTLEMAN (ed. 1773): A low reptile.—STEEVENS (Var. ’78): May be derived from ramper, Fr. to be low in the world. 64. tucke your Catastrophe] See textual notes; tucke is evidently a misreading or misprint.—Seymour (1805, i. 324): I’ll whip your breech, make your latter-end smart or itch. 65. Enter ...] On the Q stage-direction see p. 491. On the F stage-direction, p. 512. 67. be good to mee] Cowl (ed. 1923): An expression used in appealing for protection or favour to persons in authority. 68. stand to me] N.E.D. (Stand v. 76h): To side with, help, back, support (a person). 69. What] See note on I.ii.109. 73. Stand from him] DEIGHTON (ed. 1893): Let go of him. 73. hang'st vpon] On the difference between Q and F see p. 501. 75. your Grace] Just as the hostess promotes Fang to mastership, she addresses the chief justice by a title usually reserved for royalties, dukes, and archbishops.—Ed. 76. Eastcheap] SUGDEN (1925, p. 165): A street in London running east from the junction of Cannon St. and Gracechurch St. to Great Tower St. The famous Boar’s Head Tavern was at the west end of Eastcheap. 79. all: all] Although I suspect that the editors adopt this rather than Q al because they like it better rather than because of its merits from the strictly textual point of view, the probabilities seem to favor it. 81. substance] N.E.D. (Substance sb. 16): Possessions; means, wealth. arch. 83. o'Nights] On Q a nights=by night, see N.E.D. (A-nights adv. phr.). 83. Mare] Steevens (Var. ’78): The Incubus or Night-Mare.—N.E.D. (Mare sb.2 1) Obs. A kind of goblin supposed to produce nightmare by sitting on the chest of the sleeper. 84. ride the Mare] Steevens (Var. ’78): His allusion, (if it be not a wanton one) is to the Gallows, which was ludicrously called the Timber, or two-legg’d Mare. 85. vantage] N.E.D. (Vantage sb. 3): Position or opportunity likely to give superiority. 85. get vp] N.E.D. (Get v. 72b): To ascend, mount, climb up: esp. to mount on horseback. 86. Fy, what a] On the difference between Q and F see p. 505. 87. temper] Schmidt (1875): Disposition, constitution. 89. exclamation] Rolfe (ed. 1880): Outcry. 91. grosses] N.E.D. (Gross a. 6): Entire, total, whole. 92.] TECK (c. 1794; Das Buck, 1920, p. 233): The citation of these small incidental details is used in a very comical manner in Measure II.i.86 ff., where it again produces extraordinarily rich comic effects.—COLERIDGE (The Friend, 1818; ed. Raysor, 1930, ii. 336): The difference between the products of a well disciplined and those of an uncultivated understanding ... is often and admirably exhibited by our great Dramatist. 94. a parcell gilt Goblet] N.E.D. (Parcel-gilt a.): Partly gilded; esp. of silver ware, as bowls, cups, etc., having the inner surface gilt. 94. Dolphin-chamber] The name of a room in Mrs. Quickly’s tavern. See 1 Henry IV II.iv.26, where another is called the Half-moon. 95. sea-cole] ONIONS (1911): Mineral coal (as distinguished from charcoal). 97. lik'ning him] Q liking means comparing (N.E.D., Like v.2 1b).—Delius (ed. 1857): Perhaps at the behest of the censor, who would permit no ridicule of a reigning king, liking his father was changed to likening him. 97. a singing man of Windsor] Delius (ed. 1857): Falstaff had compared the respectable, perhaps morose, appearance of the king to that of a chorister in the royal chapel at Windsor. 99. my Lady] Cowl (ed. 1923) cites various instances, from the drama, of satire of “the weakness of citizens’ widows for the title ‘lady’”. 100. goodwife] N.E.D. (Goodwife 2): Prefixed to surnames (= Mrs.). Obs. 100. Keech] Steevens (Var. ’78): The fat of an ox rolled up by the butcher into a round lump. 101. gossip] Schmidt (1874): Used as a familiar compellation to a female friend or neighbour. 102. messe] N.E.D. (Mess sb. 1c): A quantity (of meat, fruit, etc.) sufficient to make a dish. (Now dial. and U.S.) 103. whereby] N.E.D. (Whereby adv. 3b): Upon which, whereupon. dial. ?Obs. 105. greene] N.E.D. (Green a. 10): Of a wound: Recent, fresh, unhealed, raw. 105. And ... staires] FURNIVALL (Old Sp. ed., 1909, p. 103): Should perhaps be set as [one line of] verse. 107. familiar] Q familiarity may be something of a stock malapropism; at any rate, it also occurs in Munday's John a Kent (1594). 108. Madam] HARRISON (Description of England, 1577, bk. iii, ch. 4; ed. Furnivall, 1877, i. 115): Howsoever one be dubbed or made Knight, his wyfe is by and by called Madame, or Ladye, so well as the Barons wyfe. 110. Book-oath] SCHMIDT (1874): Oath made on the Bible. 112. My ... her] COWL (ed. 1923): Suggested, perhaps, by ... Lodge and Greene, A Looking-Glass for London: \"Dread Monarch, this is but a lunacie, Which griefe and want hath brought the woman to\". 112. mad] Q made, according to the N.E.D., is a 15th-century variant spelling. 114. in good case] N.E.D. (Case sb.1 5): Well off. 115. distracted] N.E.D. (Distract v. 6): To render insane, drive mad. Obs. in lit. sense. 118.] SQUIRE (1935, p. 176): The Chief Justice [rebukes Falstaff] in set and sonorous phrases that admirably characterize the judge, from the reproving repetition to the lawyer-like termination. ... We can even guess, underneath the lectures of this severe magistrate, the amusement that he 119. true cause] COWL. (ed. 1923): Truth of the matter. 120. It ... consideration] FURNIVALL (Old Sp. ed., 1909, pp. 102 f.): Should perhaps be set [as three lines of] verse. 120. brow] N.E.D. (Brow sb.1 5c): Fronting, aspect, countenance. 121. (more then impudent)] P. SIMPSON (1911, p. 93): Compound nouns or adjectives are enclosed within brackets where we should employ the hyphen if we used any punctuation at all. 122. leuell] SCHMIDT (1874): Equipoised, steady. [Obs.] 123. I know you ha'] The substitution of this for Q you haue as it appeares to me was certainly deliberate, and while it was probably made at the same time that 103 was omitted, the motive for it is not easy to guess. 126.] On the omission of this line from F, see p. 500. 128. peace] SCHMIDT (1875): Be silent. 129. vnpay] DELIUS (ed. 1857): In contrast to to pay.—N.E.D. (Unpay v.²): Obs.¹ To undo, make good. 131. currant] N.E.D. (Current a. 5): Sterling, genuine, authentic: opposed to counterfeit. Obs.—LEE (ed. 1908): The chief justice seems addicted to numismatic punning. 132.] QUILLER-COUCH (Tales, 1900, p. 219): The reply was poor perhaps; but it showed that Falstaff, though careless with the low company of his choice, had shame enough left, being a gentleman himself, to wince under the rebuke of a gentleman. 132. sneape] POPE (ed. 1723): A yorkshire word for rebuke. 134. curt'sie] See textual notes.—N.E.D. (Courtesy sb. 8): The action of inclining, bowing, or lowering the body; usually in phrase to make or do courtesy. Obs. 136. your] On the difference between Q and F see p. 506. 136. [duty] N.E.D. (Duty 1): Due respect, reverence. 137. I desire ... Affaires] KNIGHT (ed. 1839, i. 256): “Falstaff claimed the protection legally called quid protecturus. (See Coke upon Littleton, 130 a.) 137. deliu'rance] N.E.D. (Deliverance 1): Release. 138. hasty] SCHMIDT (1874): Quick, speedy. [Arch.] 139. as hauing] As if you had. 140. in ... Reputation] JOHNSON (ed. 1765): In a manner suitable to your character.—CAPELL (Notes, 1779, p. 172): Suitably to what you know your 144. Enter ...] On the relation of this to the Q stage-direction see pp. 511 ff. 145.] JANSSEN (1897, p. 91): The verse-dialogue between Gower and the chief justice, like that between the prince and Peto in II.iv, introduced into a prose scene, is written in meter, not as Delius says “to emphasize the disparity which separates them from the rest,” but merely because it is concerned with war and therefore has a pathetic interest. 152. of] Concerning. See ABBOTT (1870) §174, FRANZ (3 ed., 1924) §517. 153. Heavenly ground] DELIUS (ed. 1857): She confounds by heaven with another oath, by this ground. 153. must be faine] N.E.D. (Fain a. 2): Const. to with inf. Glad under the circumstances; glad or content to take a certain course as the lesser of two evils. 154. Tapisstry] Wall hangings. See Sh.'s England (1916) ii. 128 ff. 156. Glasses, glasses] STEEVENS (ed. 1793): Mrs. Quickly is here in the same state as the Earl of Shrewsbury, who not having been paid for the diet, &c. of Mary Queen of Scots... 156. oneely] N.E.D. (Only a. 5): Unique in quality, character, rank, etc.; peerless, preëminent. 156. for ... Tapistries] CUST (Sh.'s England, 1916, ii. 4): Elsewhere Shakespeare suggests that tapestry was in his day in process of supersession by the painted cloth. 157. slight] N.E.D. (Slight a. 3): Of light, thin, or poor texture or material. 157. Drollery] STAUNTON (ed. 1858): [One] of those scenes of coarse humor which the painters of the Dutch school introduced, between the end of the sixteenth, and the middle of the seventeenth century. 157. the Storie of the Prodigall] Miss WINSTANLEY (ed. 1918): One of the favorite subjects for \"painted cloths\". 158. the Germane hunting] FARMER (Var. ’73, App. II): I suppose, hunting the wild boar.—STAUNTON (ed. 1858): The words may possibly have reference to the famous German legend of “the Wild Huntsman,” which had, perhaps, found its way to England during the reign of Elizabeth. 158. Waterwork] WARBURTON (ed. 1747): Water-colours. [So also most other editors.]—N.E.D. (Waterwork 4): A kind of imitation tapestry, painted in size or distemper. Obs. 159. Bed-hangings] JOHNSON (ed. 1765): He calls [tapestries] bed-hangings, in contempt, as fitter to make curtains than to hang walls.—Q bed-hangers is not necessarily an error; see N.E.D. (Hanger² 2a, “A piece of tapestry hanging”). If bed-hangers is what Sh. wrote, F Bed-hangings is very likely a modernization or an “improvement”. 160. tenne pound] On the use of the singular form of nouns of measure instead of the plural after numerals, see FRANZ (3 ed., 1924) §190. 161. were ... is] On the discrepancy between these verbs in mood and tense see ABBOTT (1870) §371. 161. humors] N.E.D. (Humour sb. 6c): pl. Moods or fancies exhibited in action; vagaries; fantastic, whimsical, odd, quaint, or humorous traits. 162. Go ... Come] FURNIVALL (Old Sp. ed., 1909, pp. 102 f.): Should perhaps be set as verse. 162. wash thy face] ROLFE (ed. 1880): The poor dame has been crying. 163. draw] MASON (1785, p. 188): Withdraw. 162. thy] If Sh. wrote thy, Q the is an unintentional substitution of a weaker for a stronger word of the same kind. But Q may very well be right and F thy the result of attraction exercised by the previous thy in the same line.—Ed. 163. come ... this] FURNIVALL (Old Sp. ed., 1909, pp. 102 f.): Should perhaps be set as verse: Come, come! ... this! 165. set on] N.E.D. (Set v. 148c): To instigate, incite, urge on (a person) to do something. 167. Nobles] ROLFE (ed. 1880): The noble was a gold coin, worth 6s. 8d. 168. la] N.E.D. (La int.): An exclamation formerly used to introduce or accompany a conventional phrase or an address, or to call attention to an emphatic statement. 169. make ... shift] ONIONS (1911): Manage some other way. 174. Will I liue?] LEE (ed. 1908): As sure as life.—[Cf. Shrew I.ii.193.] 181. bitter newes] See textual notes.—DELIUS (ed. 1857): Better news concerning the king’s health than that given in the paper delivered by Gower.—DEIGHTON (ed. 1893): This is not as good news as it might be.—[On the difference between Q and F see p. 506.] 182. good] On the difference between Q and F see p. 505. 184. lay] N.E.D. (Lie v. 1 5): To dwell or sojourn; esp. to sleep or pass the night (in a place). Now rare or arch. 185. last night] Q to night means the same thing (N.E.D., To-night adv. 3). 186. Basingstoke] SUGDEN (1925, p. 49): A market town in Hants., 46 m. S.W. of London, on the Great Western Road.—AX (1912, p. 65): None of the historical allusions can be supported by an excerpt from the chronicle, neither that to the number of troops destined to join the forces of John of Lancaster, nor those relating to the details of Henry’s stay at Basingstoke. 187.] THEOBALD (ed. 1733): This same Affectation of Inadvertence is again practis’d by our Poet in the 1st Part of Henry VI betwixt Princess Margaret and Suffolk, where He has made her his Prisoner. 190.] AX (1912, p. 65): We are even inclined to see a deviation from Holinshed when, upon the Chief Justice’s question Gower answers... 191. Are march'd] See note on I.i.8. 194.] JANSSEN (1897, p. 91): Falstaff speaks blank verse trying to thrust himself into the conversation between the chief justice and Gower. 196. presently] SCHMIDT (1875): Immediately. 197. go] ABBOTT (1870, §30): “Go” is used where we should say “come”. 198.] QUILLER-COUCH (Tales, 1900, p. 220): Falstaff cleared his throat. 200. entreate you ... to] According to FRANZ (3 ed., 1924, §656), after entreat and similar verbs Sh. sometimes uses to followed by an object where modern idiom requires an infinitive. 202. waite vpon] N.E.D. (Wait v.1 14k): To accompany on one's way (as a mark of respect or to render service or assistance); to escort. Now rare. 204.] COWL (ed. 1923): The dialogue was, perhaps, originally arranged as verse, and retains, in prose, something of the rhythm and diction of verse; e.g. \"in counties as you go.\" 204. being] N.E.D. (Be v. 3): Being that = it being the case that, seeing that, since. 205. take ... vp] N.E.D. (Take v. 90j): To levy, raise, enlist (troops). Obs. 205. Countries] Though this is perfectly intelligible (=counties; see N.E.D., Country 2), I suppose there can be little doubt that it is a typographical error for Q Counties. 206. sup] SCHMIDT (1875): To eat the evening meal [dinner being eaten at noon or earlier]. 207. these manners] Miss PORTER (ed. 1911): As the following lines show, the silly old knight makes a show of several fencing passes to exhibit his dexterity. 211. tap for tap] N.E.D. quotes this line under the sense “A single act of tapping; a light but audible blow or rap”. 211. part faire] N.E.D. (Fair adv. 2b): (To keep, part) fair: i.e. on good terms with. Obs. or arch. 212. lighten] N.E.D. (Lighten v.² 3): To enlighten or illuminate spiritually. arch. [Quotes this line.]—VAUGHAN (1878, i. 489): Possibly the Chief Justice here plays upon the word ‘lighten’ ... He prays that as Falstaff is so ‘great’ a ‘fool’ the Lord will lighten his weight and enlighten his conscience and intellect."
      ]
