      "notes": []
    },
    "94": {
      "play": "parcel-gilt goblet, sitting in my Dolphin chamber at",
      "notes": []
    },
    "95": {
      "play": "the round table by a sea-coal fire, upon Wednesday",
      "notes": []
    },
    "96": {
      "play": "in Wheeson week, when the Prince broke thy head",
      "notes": []
    },
    "97": {
      "play": "for liking his father to a singing-man of Windsor,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "98": {
      "play": "thou didst swear to me then, as I was washing thy",
      "notes": []
    },
    "99": {
      "play": "wound, to marry me and make me my lady thy wife.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "100": {
      "play": "Canst thou deny it? Did not Goodwife Keech, the",
      "notes": []
    },
    "101": {
      "play": "butcher’s wife, come in then and call me Gossip",
      "notes": []
    },
    "102": {
      "play": "Quickly, coming in to borrow a mess of vinegar,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "103": {
      "play": "telling us she had a good dish of prawns, whereby",
      "notes": []
    },
    "104": {
      "play": "thou didst desire to eat some, whereby I told thee",
      "notes": []
    },
    "105": {
      "play": "they were ill for a green wound? And didst thou not,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "106": {
      "play": "when she was gone downstairs, desire me to be no",
      "notes": []
    },
    "107": {
      "play": "more so familiarity with such poor people, saying",
      "notes": []
    },
    "108": {
      "play": "that ere long they should call me madam? And didst",
      "notes": []
    },
    "109": {
      "play": "thou not kiss me and bid me fetch thee thirty",
      "notes": []
    },
    "110": {
      "play": "shillings? I put thee now to thy book-oath. Deny it if",
      "notes": []
    },
    "111": {
      "play": "thou canst.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "112": {
      "play": "FALSTAFF: My lord, this is a poor mad soul, and she says",
      "notes": []
    },
    "113": {
      "play": "up and down the town that her eldest son is like",
      "notes": []
    },
    "114": {
      "play": "you. She hath been in good case, and the truth is,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "115": {
      "play": "poverty hath distracted her. But, for these foolish",
      "notes": []
    },
    "116": {
      "play": "officers, I beseech you I may have redress against",
      "notes": []
    },
    "117": {
      "play": "them.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "118": {
      "play": "CHIEF JUSTICE: Sir John, Sir John, I am well acquainted",
      "notes": []
    },
    "119": {
      "play": "with your manner of wrenching the true cause the",
      "notes": []
    },
    "120": {
      "play": "false way. It is not a confident brow, nor the throng",
      "notes": []
    },
    "121": {
      "play": "of words that come with such more than impudent",
      "notes": []
    },
    "122": {
      "play": "sauciness from you, can thrust me from a level",
      "notes": []
    },
    "123": {
      "play": "consideration. You have, as it appears to me, practiced",
      "notes": []
    },
    "124": {
      "play": "upon the easy-yielding spirit of this woman,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "125": {
      "play": "and made her serve your uses both in purse and in",
      "notes": []
    },
    "126": {
      "play": "person.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "127": {
      "play": "HOSTESS: Yea, in truth, my lord.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "128": {
      "play": "CHIEF JUSTICE: Pray thee, peace.—Pay her the debt you",
      "notes": []
    },
    "129": {
      "play": "owe her, and unpay the villainy you have done with",
      "notes": []
    },
    "130": {
      "play": "her. The one you may do with sterling money, and",
      "notes": []
    },
    "131": {
      "play": "the other with current repentance.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "132": {
      "play": "FALSTAFF: My lord, I will not undergo this sneap without",
      "notes": []
    },
    "133": {
      "play": "reply. You call honorable boldness “impudent",
      "notes": []
    },
    "134": {
      "play": "sauciness.” If a man will make curtsy and say",
      "notes": []
    },
    "135": {
      "play": "nothing, he is virtuous. No, my lord, my humble",
      "notes": []
    },
    "136": {
      "play": "duty remembered, I will not be your suitor. I say to",
      "notes": []
    },
    "137": {
      "play": "you, I do desire deliverance from these officers,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "138": {
      "play": "being upon hasty employment in the King’s affairs.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "139": {
      "play": "CHIEF JUSTICE: You speak as having power to do wrong;",
      "notes": []
    },
    "140": {
      "play": "but answer in th’ effect of your reputation, and",
      "notes": []
    },
    "141": {
      "play": "satisfy the poor woman.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "142": {
      "play": "FALSTAFF: Come hither, hostess.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "143": {
      "play": "[He speaks aside to the Hostess.]",
      "notes": []
    },
    "144": {
      "play": "[Enter a Messenger, Master Gower.]",
      "notes": []
    },
    "145": {
      "play": "CHIEF JUSTICE: Now, Master Gower, what news?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "146": {
      "play": "GOWER: The King, my lord, and Harry Prince of Wales",
      "notes": []
    },
    "147": {
      "play": "Are near at hand. The rest the paper tells.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "148": {
      "play": "He gives the Chief Justice a paper to read.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "149": {
      "play": "FALSTAFF, to the Hostess  As I am a gentleman!",
      "notes": []
    },
    "150": {
      "play": "HOSTESS: Faith, you said so before.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "151": {
      "play": "FALSTAFF: As I am a gentleman. Come. No more words",
      "notes": []
    },
    "152": {
      "play": "of it.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "153": {
      "play": "HOSTESS: By this heavenly ground I tread on, I must be",
      "notes": []
    },
    "154": {
      "play": "fain to pawn both my plate and the tapestry of my",
      "notes": []
    },
    "155": {
      "play": "dining chambers.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "156": {
      "play": "FALSTAFF: Glasses, glasses, is the only drinking. And for",
      "notes": []
    },
    "157": {
      "play": "thy walls, a pretty slight drollery, or the story of the",
      "notes": []
    },
    "158": {
      "play": "Prodigal or the German hunting in waterwork is",
      "notes": []
    },
    "159": {
      "play": "worth a thousand of these bed-hangers and these",
      "notes": []
    },
    "160": {
      "play": "fly-bitten tapestries. Let it be ten pound, if thou",
      "notes": []
    },
    "161": {
      "play": "canst. Come, an ’twere not for thy humors, there’s",
      "notes": []
    },
    "162": {
      "play": "not a better wench in England. Go wash thy face,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "163": {
      "play": "and draw the action. Come, thou must not be in this",
      "notes": []
    },
    "164": {
      "play": "humor with me. Dost not know me? Come, come. I",
      "notes": []
    },
    "165": {
      "play": "know thou wast set on to this.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "166": {
      "play": "HOSTESS: Pray thee, Sir John, let it be but twenty",
      "notes": []
    },
    "167": {
      "play": "nobles. I’ faith, I am loath to pawn my plate, so God",
      "notes": []
    },
    "168": {
      "play": "save me, la.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "169": {
      "play": "FALSTAFF: Let it alone. I’ll make other shift. You’ll be a",
      "notes": []
    },
    "170": {
      "play": "fool still.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "171": {
      "play": "HOSTESS: Well, you shall have it, though I pawn my",
      "notes": []
    },
    "172": {
      "play": "gown. I hope you’ll come to supper. You’ll pay",
      "notes": []
    },
    "173": {
      "play": "me all together?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "174": {
      "play": "FALSTAFF: Will I live? Aside to Bardolph. Go with her,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "175": {
      "play": "with her. Hook on, hook on.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "176": {
      "play": "HOSTESS: Will you have Doll Tearsheet meet you at",
      "notes": []
    },
    "177": {
      "play": "supper?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "178": {
      "play": "FALSTAFF: No more words. Let’s have her.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "179": {
      "play": "Hostess, Fang, Snare, Bardolph, Page,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "180": {
      "play": "[and others exit.]",
      "notes": []
    },
    "181": {
      "play": "CHIEF JUSTICE, to Gower  I have heard better news.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "182": {
      "play": "FALSTAFF, to Chief Justice  What’s the news, my good",
      "notes": []
    },
    "183": {
      "play": "lord?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "184": {
      "play": "CHIEF JUSTICE, to Gower  Where lay the King",
      "notes": []
    },
    "185": {
      "play": "tonight?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "186": {
      "play": "GOWER: At Basingstoke, my lord.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "187": {
      "play": "FALSTAFF, to Chief Justice  I hope, my lord, all’s",
      "notes": []
    },
    "188": {
      "play": "well. What is the news, my lord?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "189": {
      "play": "CHIEF JUSTICE, to Gower  Come all his forces back?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "190": {
      "play": "GOWER: No. Fifteen hundred foot, five hundred horse",
      "notes": []
    },
    "191": {
      "play": "Are marched up to my Lord of Lancaster",
      "notes": []
    },
    "192": {
      "play": "Against Northumberland and the Archbishop.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "193": {
      "play": "FALSTAFF, to Chief Justice",
      "notes": []
    },
    "194": {
      "play": "Comes the King back from Wales, my noble lord?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "195": {
      "play": "CHIEF JUSTICE, to Gower",
      "notes": []
    },
    "196": {
      "play": "You shall have letters of me presently.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "197": {
      "play": "Come. Go along with me, good Master Gower.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "198": {
      "play": "FALSTAFF: My lord!",
      "notes": []
    },
    "199": {
      "play": "CHIEF JUSTICE: What’s the matter?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "200": {
      "play": "FALSTAFF: Master Gower, shall I entreat you with me to",
      "notes": []
    },
    "201": {
      "play": "dinner?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "202": {
      "play": "GOWER: I must wait upon my good lord here. I thank",
      "notes": []
    },
    "203": {
      "play": "you, good Sir John.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "204": {
      "play": "CHIEF JUSTICE: Sir John, you loiter here too long, being",
      "notes": []
    },
    "205": {
      "play": "you are to take soldiers up in counties as you go.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "206": {
      "play": "FALSTAFF: Will you sup with me, Master Gower?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "207": {
      "play": "CHIEF JUSTICE: What foolish master taught you these",
      "notes": []
    },
    "208": {
      "play": "manners, Sir John?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "209": {
      "play": "FALSTAFF: Master Gower, if they become me not, he was",
      "notes": []
    },
    "210": {
      "play": "a fool that taught them me.—This is the right",
      "notes": []
    },
    "211": {
      "play": "fencing grace, my lord: tap for tap, and so part fair.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "212": {
      "play": "CHIEF JUSTICE: Now the Lord lighten thee. Thou art a",
      "notes": []
    },
    "213": {
      "play": "great fool.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "214": {
      "play": "[They separate and exit.]",
      "notes": []
    }
  },
  "ACT 2, SCENE 2": {
    "1": {
      "play": "[Enter the Prince and Poins.]",
      "notes": []
    },
    "2": {
      "play": "PRINCE: Before God, I am exceeding weary.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "3": {
      "play": "POINS: Is ’t come to that? I had thought weariness durst",
      "notes": [
        "had thought] On this use of the subjunctive see FRANZ (3 ed., 1924) §638. Cf. iii.ii.149, iv.i.48, 144, iv.ii.96, iv.v.155.",
        "POINS] THEOBALD (ed. 1733): Tho’ all the Editions concur in giving this Speech to Poins, it seems evident to me, by the Page’s immediate Reply, that"
      ]
    },
    "4": {
      "play": "not have attached one of so high blood.",
      "notes": [
        "attached] N.E.D. (Attach v. 3b): To seize, lay hold of. Said fig. of death, sickness, love, passion, misfortune. Obs.—DELIUS (ed. 1857) quotes Tempest iii.iii.51, “Who am myself attach’d with weariness”."
      ]
    },
    "5": {
      "play": "PRINCE: Faith, it does me, though it discolors the complexion",
      "notes": []
    },
    "6": {
      "play": "of my greatness to acknowledge it. Doth it",
      "notes": []
    },
    "7": {
      "play": "not show vilely in me to desire small beer?",
      "notes": [
        "show] ONIONS (1911): To have (a certain) appearance, appear, seem.—[Cf. iv.i.72, iv.ii.5, iv.iii.51, 54.]",
        "vilely] See note on l. 48 below.",
        "small beer] N.E.D. (Small beer 1): Beer of a weak, poor, or inferior quality."
      ]
    },
    "8": {
      "play": "POINS: Why, a prince should not be so loosely studied",
      "notes": [
        "loosely studied] DELIUS (ed. 1857): Negligent in the pursuit of his studies.—SCHMIDT (1875): Studious, intent, inclined. [So also ONIONS and various editors. If so, loosely means “immorally” (N.E.D., Loosely adv. 3), but N.E.D. does not define studied in the sense inclined.]—DEIGHTON (ed. 1893): A prince’s inclinations ought not to concern themselves with anything of so mean a nature as small beer; with a pun on studied, and on composition in its sense of a literary production.—COWL (ed. 1923): Negligently practised in the part of a prince, or inclined to looseness. Studied, versed [N.E.D., Studied ppl.a. 2], as in Merchant ii.ii.181 [“one well studied in a sad ostent”]."
      ]
    },
    "9": {
      "play": "as to remember so weak a composition.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "10": {
      "play": "PRINCE: Belike then my appetite was not princely got,",
      "notes": [
        "Belike] N.E.D. (Belike A, adv.): Likely, probably; perhaps, possibly.",
        "got] SCHMIDT (1874): Get, to beget.—[Cf. iv.iii.97.]"
      ]
    },
    "11": {
      "play": "for, by my troth, I do now remember the poor",
      "notes": [
        "by my troth] In Q by my troth, another common asseveration, troth = good faith, honesty (N.E.D., Troth sb. 1b); cf. ii.iv.307–8.",
        "good] On the difference between Q and F here and at ll. 93, 96 see p. 505."
      ]
    },
    "12": {
      "play": "creature small beer. But indeed these humble considerations",
      "notes": []
    },
    "13": {
      "play": "make me out of love with my greatness.",
      "notes": [
        "out of love with] N.E.D. (Love sb. 7e): Out of love (with): disgusted (with)."
      ]
    },
    "14": {
      "play": "What a disgrace is it to me to remember thy name,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "15": {
      "play": "or to know thy face tomorrow, or to take note how",
      "notes": []
    },
    "16": {
      "play": "many pair of silk stockings thou hast—with these,",
      "notes": [
        "pair] See note on II.i.131.",
        "with] Q with is explained by WILSON (MS. of Hamlet, 1934, i. 112) as a thz error.—[This mistake has perhaps cast discredit on Q once in the next line, though it is not unintelligible.—Ed.]"
      ]
    },
    "17": {
      "play": "and those that were thy peach-colored ones—or to",
      "notes": [
        "were ... ones] DEIGHTON (ed. 1893): Sc. but which from much wearing and often washing have long since lost their colour.",
        "peach-colored] COWL (ed. 1923): Peach-colour, in the language of colours, signified love (Captain Underwit II.ii [A Collection of Old English Plays, ed. A. H. Bullen, 1883, ii. 345]).—Miss LINTHICUM (1936, p. 40): Allusions to [peach color] in the drama are in connexion with gallants and would-be courtiers. ... If peach-colour had the symbolism which Sicile attributed to it, i.e. diminished riches, lost courage, little nobleness, its occurrence in comic scenes must have provoked laughter."
      ]
    },
    "18": {
      "play": "bear the inventory of thy shirts, as, one for superfluity",
      "notes": [
        "for superfluity] DEIGHTON (ed. 1893): As a change.",
        "out] Steevens (ed. 1793): The same as “out of”.—[See N.E.D. (Out prep. 1) and Franz (3 ed., 1924) §540.]"
      ]
    },
    "19": {
      "play": "and another for use. But that the tennis-court",
      "notes": []
    },
    "20": {
      "play": "keeper knows better than I, for it is a low ebb of",
      "notes": []
    },
    "21": {
      "play": "linen with thee when thou keepest not racket there,",
      "notes": [
        "keepest] N.E.D. (Keep v. 36): To carry on, maintain; to continue to make, cause, or do (an action, war, disturbance, or the like). {Quotes Errors III.i.61, “Who is that at the door that keeps all this noise?” and Twelfth Night I.iii.70, “What a caterwauling do you keep here!”}"
      ]
    },
    "22": {
      "play": "as thou hast not done a great while, because the rest",
      "notes": [
        "a great while] On adverbial phrases of time, place, and manner without preposition, the adverbial accusative, see ABBOTT (1870) §202, FRANZ (3 ed., 1924) §542. Cf. ii.iv.390, iii.ii.34, IV.v.140, 261, V.i.52."
      ]
    },
    "23": {
      "play": "of the low countries have made a shift to eat up thy",
      "notes": [
        "made a shift to] This must have stood in Sh.’s MS. and have been accidentally omitted from Q.—ED."
      ]
    },
    "24": {
      "play": "holland; and God knows whether those that bawl",
      "notes": [
        "bawl] Ridley (ed. 1934): [Bawl is] the usual emendation of Q bal; but no one has made any real sense of the emendation. One wonders whether bat is not possible, in the sense of ‘possing’ clothes (see N.E.D., where ‘battle’ (cf. ‘batler,’ the instrument for beating clothes in the wash) is regarded as possibly a frequentative of ‘bat’). Though this does nothing to explain either the relevance of the allusion to the poor in spirit (unless indeed there is an elaborate pun, involving a misreference, to the peace-(piece-)makers) nor the unexpected appearance of the midwives."
      ]
    },
    "25": {
      "play": "out the ruins of thy linen shall inherit His kingdom;",
      "notes": [
        "shall ... kingdom] Carter (1905, p. 273): Matt. xxv. 34—“Comme ye blessed of my father, inherite the kyngdome, which hath benne prepared for you, from the fundation of the worlde.”—[Ridley’s note on l. 26 alludes to Matthew v. 3, “Blessed are the poore in spirite: for theirs is the kyngdome of heaven”.—Dr. Adams cites Mark x. 14: “Suffer the little children to come unto me, and forbid them not: for of such is the kingdom of God” (A.V.).]"
      ]
    },
    "26": {
      "play": "but the midwives say the children are not in the",
      "notes": []
    },
    "27": {
      "play": "fault, whereupon the world increases and kindreds",
      "notes": [
        "whereupon] N.E.D. (Whereupon 3b): (With clause as antecedent) On which account. Obs."
      ]
    },
    "28": {
      "play": "are mightily strengthened.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "29": {
      "play": "POINS: How ill it follows, after you have labored so",
      "notes": [
        "follows] N.E.D. (Follow v. 16): To result (as an effect from a cause, an inference from premisses); to be, or occur as, a consequent."
      ]
    },
    "30": {
      "play": "hard, you should talk so idly! Tell me, how many",
      "notes": []
    },
    "31": {
      "play": "good young princes would do so, their fathers being",
      "notes": [
        "so ... as] As ... as. See Franz (3 ed., 1924) §580."
      ]
    },
    "32": {
      "play": "so sick as yours at this time is?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "33": {
      "play": "PRINCE: Shall I tell thee one thing, Poins?",
      "notes": [
        "Shall ... thing] Cowl (ed. 1923) quotes Pericles iv.vi.154-5: “Mar. Prithee, tell me one thing first. Boult. Come now, your one thing.”"
      ]
    },
    "34": {
      "play": "POINS: Yes, faith, and let it be an excellent good thing.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "35": {
      "play": "PRINCE: It shall serve among wits of no higher breeding",
      "notes": [
        "wits] Onions (1911): Person[s] of a certain condition or turn of mind (expressed by a qualifying word or phrase).",
        "breeding] Schmidt (1874): Education."
      ]
    },
    "36": {
      "play": "than thine.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "37": {
      "play": "POINS: Go to. I stand the push of your one thing that",
      "notes": [
        "Go to] N.E.D. (Go v. 91b): Go to. Used in imp. to express disapprobation, remonstrance, protest, or derisive incredulity; = Come, come! †Also used to introduce a contemptuous concession.—[Cf. III.ii.121, 276, 298, v.i.58, and see note on III.ii.232.]",
        "stand the push] Rolfe (ed. 1880): Stand the thrust. See 1 Henry IV [III.ii.66, “To laugh at gibing boys, and stand the push Of every beardless vain comparative”].—Miss Hanscom (ed. 1912): Await the encounter."
      ]
    },
    "38": {
      "play": "you will tell.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "39": {
      "play": "PRINCE: Marry, I tell thee it is not meet that I should be",
      "notes": [
        "bear] DEIGHTON (ed. 1893): Sc. in memory, mind.",
        "ass] Cowl (ed. 1923): An allusion to the ass as an emblem of modesty and continence."
      ]
    },
    "40": {
      "play": "sad, now my father is sick—albeit I could tell to",
      "notes": []
    },
    "41": {
      "play": "thee, as to one it pleases me, for fault of a better, to",
      "notes": [
        "for fault of] N.E.D. (Fault sb. 1c): For (the) fault of: in default of; in the absence of; through deficiency or want of. Obs. [Quotes this line.]",
        "for] See note on I.ii.5."
      ]
    },
    "42": {
