    "83": {
      "play": "he had made two holes in the ale-wife’s new",
      "notes": [
        "ale-wife's] According to the N.E.D. (Wife sb.), this form of the possessive is recorded from the 13th through the 17th c.",
        "petticoat] AMNER, i.e. STEEVENS (apud Malone, Suppl., 1780): It should be observed, that the alewife’s petticoat was probably red, a favourite colour of the lower females, and the fittest to represent Bardolph’s face.—[As Dr. ADAMS points out, in The Penniles Parliament of Threed-bare Poets, 1604 (ed. Hindley, Old Book Collector’s Miscellany ii, 1872, pp. 4, 14), red petticoat is used for a woman of ill fame.]"
      ]
    },
