    "103": {
      "play": "POINS: Delivered with good respect. And how doth the",
      "notes": [
        "respect] N.E.D. (Respect sb. 16): Deferential regard or esteem felt or shown towards a person or thing.—Cowl (ed. 1923): An ironical reference to the unceremonious way in which Bardolph delivers the letter."
      ]
    },
    "104": {
      "play": "Martlemas your master?",
      "notes": [
        "Martlemas] Johnson (ed. 1765): That is, the autumn, or rather the latter spring. The old fellow with juvenile passions.—Steevens (Var. ’78): Martlemas is corrupted from Martinmas, the feast of St. Martin, the eleventh of November.—Malone (ed. 1790): In 1 Henry IV [I.ii.152–3] the prince calls Falstaff “thou latter spring! ... All-hallow summer!”—Blakeway (Var.): Martinmas ... was then the chief time of killing hogs: this is therefore only another of the innumerable variations of allusion to Falstaff’s corpulence.—Knight (ed. 1839): Poins calls Falstaff the martlemas, because his year of life is running out.—Clarke (ed. 1865): There are so many allusions to ‘Martlemas beef’ in writers of Shakespeare’s time ... that it is very likely Prince Hal’s [sic] name of “Martlemas” for Sir John may include this meaning also; since he elsewhere calls him “my sweet beef” (1 Henry IV III.iii.176).—Prothero (Sh.’s England, 1916, i. 356): To Shakespeare’s mind the prodigious plenty of Martlemas suggested Falstaff in its proportions.—Miss Winstanley (ed. 1918): Cf. Spenser, Faerie Queene vii. 7.: “Next was November, he full grosse and fat, As fed with lard, and that right well might seeme; For, he had been a fatting hogs of late, That yet his browes with sweat, did reek and steem.”—[The statement of Gluttony in Marlowe’s Dr. Faustus II.ii.153–4 (ed. Boas, 1932, pp. 96 f.) that his godfathers were “Peter Pickled-herring and Martin Martlemas-beef” suggests that Martlemas here stands for glutton.—Ed.]"
      ]
    },
    "105": {
      "play": "BARDOLPH: In bodily health, sir.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "106": {
      "play": "POINS: Marry, the immortal part needs a physician, but",
      "notes": []
    },
    "107": {
      "play": "that moves not him. Though that be sick, it dies not.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "108": {
      "play": "PRINCE: I do allow this wen to be as familiar with me as",
      "notes": [
        "wen] Johnson (ed. 1765): This swoln excrescence of a man.—Becket Ed."
      ]
    },
    "109": {
      "play": "my dog, and he holds his place, for look you how he",
      "notes": [
        "holds his place] N.E.D. (Hold v. 22): To maintain one's position (against an adversary).",
        "fetch] N.E.D. (Fetch v. 6): To draw, derive from a source, esp. from one more or less remote. Const. from or out of. Now rare.—COWL (ed. 1923) quotes Othello I.ii.21, “I fetch my life and being From men of royal siege”."
      ]
    },
    "110": {
      "play": "writes.  He shows the letter to Poins.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "111": {
      "play": "POINS reads the superscription  John Falstaff, knight.",
      "notes": [
        "POINS reads] COWL (ed. 1923): Poins is not, I think, reading from the letter, but referring, with a quibble, to the Prince's words, \"look you how he writes.\" Poins, playing upon the word \"write\" in the sense \"write oneself,\" anticipates that Falstaff will \"write\" or describe himself in (the subscription to) the letter as \"John Falstaff, knight.\" Poins's anticipation—which is based upon the observation: \"every man must know that, as oft as he has occasion to name himself\"—is substantially realized with the reading of the letter which begins at line 115: \"Sir John Falstaff, knight.\" The stage-direction \"Letter\" of F has, I think, been misplaced through the conjectural citation, \"John Falstaff, knight,\" having been taken for a quotation from the letter.—[F Letter is probably a result of the same editorial supervision which directed the printing of the letter in italics.—ED.]"
      ]
    },
    "112": {
      "play": "Every man must know that as oft as he has occasion",
      "notes": []
    },
    "113": {
      "play": "to name himself, even like those that are kin to the",
      "notes": [
        "kin to] N.E.D. (Kin sb.¹ 3d): In predicative use passing into adj.= Related, akin (to) [quoting this line as its earliest example.]"
      ]
    },
    "114": {
      "play": "King, for they never prick their finger but they say",
      "notes": []
    },
    "115": {
      "play": "“There’s some of the King’s blood spilt.” “How",
      "notes": []
    },
    "116": {
      "play": "comes that?” says he that takes upon him not to",
      "notes": [
        "takes upon] N.E.D. (Take v. 16a): To assume the part or character of.—[Cf. iv.i.69.]"
      ]
    },
    "117": {
      "play": "conceive. The answer is as ready as a borrower’s",
      "notes": [
        "conceive] N.E.D. (Conceive v. 9d): To understand, to take the meaning of (a person). Obs. [Quotes this line as its earliest example.]"
      ]
    },
    "118": {
      "play": "cap: “I am the King’s poor cousin, sir.”",
      "notes": []
    },
    "119": {
      "play": "PRINCE: Nay, they will be kin to us, or they will fetch it",
      "notes": [
        "or] Q or. But they will is not unintelligible: it means “even if they must” (N.E.D., But conj. 11a)."
      ]
    },
    "120": {
      "play": "from Japheth. But to the letter: Reads. Sir John",
      "notes": [
        "from Japheth] COWL (ed. 1923): Divines and early ethnologists traced the descent of the peoples of European stock from Japhet. See Genesis x. 5.—Miss WINSTANLEY (ed. 1918): The Prince means that such people will either claim kinship with royalty or else boast of an almost interminable pedigree.—"
      ]
    },
    "121": {
      "play": "Falstaff, knight, to the son of the King nearest his",
      "notes": []
    },
    "122": {
      "play": "father, Harry Prince of Wales, greeting.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "123": {
      "play": "POINS: Why, this is a certificate.",
      "notes": [
        "a certificate] COWL (ed. 1923): I.e. couched in the formal language of a document in which something is certified."
      ]
    },
    "124": {
      "play": "PRINCE: Peace!",
      "notes": [
        "Peace] See note on II.i.105."
      ]
    },
    "125": {
      "play": "Reads. I will imitate the honorable Romans in",
      "notes": [
        "Romans] WARBURTON (apud Theobald, ed. 1733): I don't know, who could furnish Shakespeare with this Account of the Roman Brevity, but Pliny the Younger: B[k]. i, Epist. xi. ... But, after all, should it not be Roman, (in the singular Number) and Brutus be meant? For He was peculiarly Laconick in his Stile.—CAPELL (Notes, 1779, p. 173): [In] the forms of addressing ... the Romans were most concise: many not remote from sir John's \"I commend me to thee,\" &c. are found in all their epistles; and translations might bring the Poet acquainted with them, if we must not grant him originals.—HEATH (1765, pp. 256 f.): I believe Mr. Warburton may be right in his correction ..., but I conceive he is wrong in his application. The poet's representation of Falstaff's character is scarce reconcilable to the supposition, that he had learning enough ever to have heard, that M. Brutus affected great brevity of stile. I suppose by the 'honourable Roman' is intended Julius Cæsar, whose veni, vidi, vici, seems to be alluded to in the beginning of the letter ..."
      ]
    },
    "126": {
      "play": "brevity.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "127": {
      "play": "POINS: He sure means brevity in breath, short-winded.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "128": {
      "play": "PRINCE reads  I commend me to thee, I commend thee,",
      "notes": [
        "I commend me to thee] N.E.D. (Commend v. 5): Now arch. I commend me to you, I present my kind regards or remembrances.—[Cf. i.ii.207, iii.ii.64.]"
      ]
    },
    "129": {
      "play": "and I leave thee. Be not too familiar with Poins, for he",
      "notes": [
        "Be ... Poins] Bulthaupt (2 ed., 1884, p. 78): Falstaff—instinctively and in a humorous way that does not take deep root—feels a kind of jealousy of Poins; he feels that Poins’s better and more noble grain could estrange the prince from him.—Brady (Short Studies, 1929, p. 59): He can imagine no rival influence more dangerous than that of Poins, of whom he is furiously jealous, and whom he tries to discredit."
      ]
    },
    "130": {
      "play": "misuses thy favors so much that he swears thou art to",
      "notes": []
    },
    "131": {
      "play": "marry his sister Nell. Repent at idle times as thou",
      "notes": []
    },
    "132": {
      "play": "mayst, and so farewell.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "133": {
      "play": "Thine by yea and no, which is as much as",
      "notes": [
        "by yea and no] Carter (1905, p. 274): Matt. v. 34—“Sweare not at al.” 37—“But let your communication be yea, yea: nay, nay.”—Cowl (ed. 1923): A Puritan expletive.—[Cf. iii.ii.12.]"
      ]
    },
    "134": {
      "play": "to say, as thou usest him,",
      "notes": [
        "as thou usest him] Sir Andrew Aguecheek, writing a challenge, subscribes himself, “Thy friend, as thou usest him, and thy sworn enemy” (Twelfth Night iii.iv.160–1)."
      ]
    },
    "135": {
      "play": "Jack Falstaff with my familiars,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "136": {
      "play": "John with my brothers and sisters, and",
      "notes": []
    },
    "137": {
      "play": "Sir John with all Europe.",
      "notes": [
        "Sir ... Europe] Miss Winstanley (ed. 1918): Falstaff claims a European reputation and, in the original as Oldcastle, he certainly had some right to it."
      ]
    },
    "138": {
      "play": "POINS: My lord, I’ll steep this letter in sack and make",
      "notes": [
        "being] On the difference between Q and F see p. 506."
      ]
    },
    "139": {
      "play": "him eat it.",
      "notes": [
        "eat it] CowL (ed. 1923) cites three examples from other plays of a person's being actually compelled to eat a letter or other document."
      ]
    },
    "140": {
      "play": "PRINCE: That’s to make him eat twenty of his words.",
      "notes": [
        "twenty ... words] Warburton (ed. 1747): Why just twenty, when the letter contain'd above eight times twenty? We should read plenty; and in this word the joke, as slender as it is, consists.—Heath (1765, p. 257): I think the common reading ... is much more natural [than Warburton's], a certain number for an uncertain.—N.E.D. (Twenty adj. 1d): Used vaguely or hyperbolically for a large number."
      ]
    },
    "141": {
      "play": "But do you use me thus, Ned? Must I marry your",
      "notes": []
    },
    "142": {
      "play": "sister?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "143": {
      "play": "POINS: God send the wench no worse fortune! But I",
      "notes": []
    },
    "144": {
      "play": "never said so.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "145": {
      "play": "PRINCE: Well, thus we play the fools with the time, and",
      "notes": [
        "thus ... time] Does this mean “thus we fool away the time” or “thus we play the fool following the spirit of the times”?"
      ]
    },
    "146": {
      "play": "the spirits of the wise sit in the clouds and mock us.",
      "notes": [
        "the spirits ... us] Theobald (letter to Warburton, 15 Jany. 1729): Do you think our poet might owe ye [foun]dation of this Thought to Lucret[ius]. [liber]. 2. [verses 7-9:] Sed nil dulcius est, bene quàm munita te[nere] Edita doctrina Sapientum templa seren[a,] Despicere unde queas. [“But nothing is more delightful than to possess well fortified sanctuaries serene, built up by the teachings of the wise, whence you may look down from the height” (tr. Rouse, 1924, p. 85).]—Carter (1905, p. 274): Ps. ii. 4—“He that dwelleth in heauen shal laugh them to scorne: the Lorde shal haue them in derision.” Met. Psalm ii, T. S[ternhold]—“But he that in the heauen dwelleth their doynges will deride: And make them all as mocking stockes.”—Cowl (Sources, 1928, p. 29): Shakespeare's image of the spirits of the wise sitting in the clouds would appear to have been suggested by the use in Masques of scenic machinery representing clouds."
      ]
    },
    "147": {
      "play": "To Bardolph. Is your master here in London?",
      "notes": [
        "] Morgann (1777, p. 52): One may infer farther from the Prince's question ..., “Is your master here in London,” that he had likewise a house in the country. [See note on II.i.163-4.]"
      ]
    },
    "148": {
      "play": "BARDOLPH: Yea, my lord.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "149": {
      "play": "PRINCE: Where sups he? Doth the old boar feed in the",
      "notes": []
    },
    "150": {
