    "151": {
      "play": "BARDOLPH: At the old place, my lord, in Eastcheap.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "152": {
      "play": "PRINCE: What company?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "153": {
      "play": "PAGE: Ephesians, my lord, of the old church.",
      "notes": [
        "Ephesians] JOHNSON (ed. 1765): Ephesian ... was, perhaps, a toper. So the Host in the Merry Wives of Windsor [IV.v.15-6]: It is thine host, thine Ephesian, calls.—TIECK (c. 1794; Das Buch, 1920, p. 234): Perhaps whores, lewd people; at least the word Greek had this meaning at that time.—CLARKE (Sh. Key, 1879, p. 42): ‘Jolly companion,’ ‘roystering associate’; the term probably included a mixture of ‘roguery,’ as Ephesus was reputed for its “cozenage” (see the closing speech of act I, Errors [ii. 97 ff.].)—ROLFE (ed. 1880) compares 1 Henry IV II.iv.11, “a Corinthian, a lad of mettle”.—DEIGHTON (ed. 1893): Apparently ... an allusion to the admonishment of St. Paul in his Epistle to the Ephesians against drunkenness.—CARTER (1905, p. 274) recalls the notorious sensuality of the worshippers of “Diana of the Ephesians”.—COWL (ed. 1923) quotes Wever’s Lusty Juvenuts (sig. A.iii.): “Sainct Paul vnto ỳ Ephesians guueth good exhortation Saying, walke circumspectly, redeming the time, That is to spend it well, and not to wickednes enclyne”.",
        "of the old church] DEIGHTON (ed. 1893): Of the old sort, his usual companions. [This is the usual explanation.—Ed.]—COWL (ed. 1923): An irreverent allusion to “the prime church of Ephesus” whose practice in matters of Church government was regarded among Puritans as authoritative (see Middleton, Family of Love I.iii.). For the profane sense in which the expression ... was used by the irreverent, cf. Munday, Drayton, Hathaway and Wilson, Sir John Oldcastle [ed. Simpson, M.S.R., 1908, ll. 1928-31]: “I am neither heretike nor puritane, but of the old church, ile sweare, drinke ale, kisse a wench, go to masse, eate fish all Lent, and fast fridaies with cakes and wine” etc. ... Cf. also the expression “of an ancient house” in Middleton, Blurt, Master Constable III.i.: “ho, a bona-roba; ... a gentlewoman, by my faith, of an ancient house”, and J. Cooke, How a Man May Choose III.ii [Hazlitt’s Dodsley, 1874, ix. 53]: “The gentlewoman of the old house, ... she that is, like homo, common to all men”.—SUGDEN (1925, p. 180): Of the old heathen church before the founding of the Christian church there.—[Cowl bears the palm.]"
      ]
    },
    "154": {
      "play": "PRINCE: Sup any women with him?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "155": {
      "play": "PAGE: None, my lord, but old Mistress Quickly and",
      "notes": []
    },
    "156": {
      "play": "Mistress Doll Tearsheet.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "157": {
      "play": "PRINCE: What pagan may that be?",
      "notes": [
        "pagan] STEEVENS (Var. '78): Prostitute. [Cf. Massinger, The City Madam 11. i (ed. Cunningham, 1897, p. 432): \"in all these places I have had my several pagans billetted\".—COWL (ed. 1923) quotes Fletcher and Massinger, Sir John Van Olden Barnavelt i.i.[206–12]: \"a Cap. ... a kind wench for my young lord his Son ... i Cap. ... if I had thought on't when I left London, I had fitted you for a convenient Pagan\".—[This line is the earliest example of this sense quoted by N.E.D.]]"
      ]
    },
    "158": {
      "play": "PAGE: A proper gentlewoman, sir, and a kinswoman of",
      "notes": [
        "proper] N.E.D. (Proper a. 7b): Of good character or standing; honest, respectable, worthy. Obs. [Quotes this line as its earliest example.]—[Cf. l. 65 above.]"
      ]
    },
    "159": {
      "play": "my master’s.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "160": {
      "play": "PRINCE: Even such kin as the parish heifers are to the",
      "notes": [
        "heifers] COWL (ed. 1923): The c in Heicfors (Q) represents an original h; O.E. heahfore.",
        "town bull] N.E.D. (Town sb. 10): Town-bull, a bull formerly kept in turn by the cow-keepers of a village; hence fig. of a man [quoting this line]."
      ]
    },
    "161": {
      "play": "town bull.—Shall we steal upon them, Ned, at",
      "notes": []
    },
    "162": {
      "play": "supper?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "163": {
      "play": "POINS: I am your shadow, my lord. I’ll follow you.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "164": {
      "play": "PRINCE: Sirrah—you, boy—and Bardolph, no word to",
      "notes": [
        "yet] FRANZ (3 ed., 1924, §423): Already.",
        "to] On the difference between Q and F see p. 506."
      ]
    },
    "165": {
      "play": "your master that I am yet come to town. There’s for",
      "notes": []
    },
    "166": {
      "play": "your silence.  He gives money.",
      "notes": [
        "There's] Sc. something. See FRANZ (3 ed., 1924) §355."
      ]
    },
    "167": {
      "play": "BARDOLPH: I have no tongue, sir.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "168": {
      "play": "PAGE: And for mine, sir, I will govern it.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "169": {
      "play": "PRINCE: Fare you well. Go.    [Bardolph and Page exit.]",
      "notes": []
    },
    "170": {
      "play": "This Doll Tearsheet should be some road.",
      "notes": [
        "road] SKEAT (10 N. & Q. ix, 1908, p. 264): A female who had no reputation to lose was said to be “as common as a cartway.” The expression goes back to the fourteenth century at least. I quote an example from ... Piers the Plowman Passus iii. 127: “Heo [she] is ... As comun as the cart-wei to knaues and to alle”.—[It is to this expression, quoted in full by Poins in the next speech, that the prince alludes.]—SPIELMANN (T.L.S. 9 Jany. 1919, p. 22): According to the Oxford Dictionary, however, “rode” should be taken to mean “a means of communication.” If so, “some” may be regarded as signifying that the disreputable young woman should be a splendid instrument in connexion with Prince Hal’s projected spying upon Falstaff ... Is not this “some” evidence?"
      ]
    },
    "171": {
      "play": "POINS: I warrant you, as common as the way between",
      "notes": []
    },
    "172": {
      "play": "Saint Albans and London.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "173": {
      "play": "PRINCE: How might we see Falstaff bestow himself",
      "notes": [
        "bestow himself] N.E.D. (Bestow v. 5c): refl. To acquit oneself. Obs."
      ]
    },
    "174": {
      "play": "tonight in his true colors, and not ourselves be",
      "notes": []
    },
    "175": {
      "play": "seen?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "176": {
      "play": "POINS: Put on two leathern jerkins and aprons, and",
      "notes": []
    },
    "177": {
      "play": "wait upon him at his table as drawers.",
      "notes": [
        "drawers] N.E.D. (Drawer 1 2): One who draws liquor for customers."
      ]
    },
    "178": {
      "play": "PRINCE: From a god to a bull: a heavy descension. It",
      "notes": [
        "From ... bull] COWL (ed. 1923): An allusion to Jupiter, who, for the love of Europa, transformed himself into a bull. See Ovid, Metamorphoses ii. 846-75.",
        "heavy] T. DAVIES (1784, i. 291): I should imagine Shakspeare wrote heavenly descension, and the words which follow seem to justify this reading, — It was Jove’s case. It was a descent from heaven by Jupiter himself.—N.E.D. (Heavy a. 12): Of great import; weighty, important; serious, grave. Now rare or Obs.",
        "descension] See textual notes.—UPTON (1746, p. 229): It would be more accurate if the words were transposed, and we should read, “From a God to a bull? a heavy transformation; it was Jove’s case. From a prince to a prentice a low declension” [&c.].—WARBURTON (ed. 1747): Descension was preferred with judgment. For descension signifies a voluntary going down; declension, a natural and necessary. [N.E.D., which defines declension as “deviation or declining from a standard”, hardly bears Warburton out.]—ROLFE (ed. 1880) notes that descension is not found elsewhere in Sh.—N.E.D. (Descension 1): Going or coming down, descent (lit. and fig.). Now rare. [Quotes this line.]—[See p. 506.]"
      ]
    },
    "179": {
      "play": "was Jove’s case. From a prince to a ’prentice: a low",
      "notes": []
    },
    "180": {
      "play": "transformation that shall be mine, for in everything",
      "notes": []
    },
    "181": {
      "play": "the purpose must weigh with the folly. Follow me,",
      "notes": [
        "weigh with] SCHMIDT (1875): To have the same weight as, to counterbalance (as the purpose is, such the folly must be; i.e. a foolish purpose requires as foolish a behaviour).—DEIGHTON (ed. 1893): The object in view must be weighed with the folly employed and be an excuse for it."
      ]
    },
    "182": {
      "play": "Ned.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "183": {
      "play": "[They exit.]",
      "notes": []
    },
    "311": {
      "notes": [
        "] AX (1912, p. 65): To judge from Harry’s very first words, he seems to have just arrived from Wales.—[Cf. ii.iv.297.]"
      ]
    },
    "382": {
      "notes": [
        "idly] N.E.D. (Idly adv. 1): Vainly; uselessly; ineffectively."
      ]
    }
  },
  "ACT 2, SCENE 3": {
    "1": {
      "play": "[Enter Northumberland, his wife, and the wife to",
      "notes": []
    },
    "2": {
      "play": "Harry Percy.]",
      "notes": []
    },
    "3": {
      "play": "NORTHUMBERLAND: I pray thee, loving wife and gentle daughter,",
      "notes": [
        "I prethee] Q I pray thee.—Dyce (ed. 1864-7, i. 254): We must suppose (if \"thee\" be not a mistake for \"ye\") that the full construction is, \"I pray thee, loving wife, and thee, gentle daughter,\" &c.—[Perhaps pray thee was such a common formula that the sense of the singular number in thee was lost.—Ed.]"
      ]
    },
    "4": {
      "play": "Give even way unto my rough affairs.",
      "notes": [
        "Giue ... way] N.E.D. (Give v. 49d): Give way. To allow free scope, opportunity, or liberty of action to [quoting v.ii.90, q.v.]."
      ]
    },
    "5": {
      "play": "Put not you on the visage of the times",
      "notes": []
    },
    "6": {
      "play": "And be, like them, to Percy troublesome.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "7": {
      "play": "LADY NORTHUMBERLAND: I have given over. I will speak no more.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "8": {
      "play": "Do what you will; your wisdom be your guide.",
      "notes": [
        "Wisedome,] P. SIMPSON (1911, pp. 26 ff.) quotes this as an example of the “emphasizing comma”, placed after a word to be stressed."
      ]
    },
    "9": {
      "play": "NORTHUMBERLAND: Alas, sweet wife, my honor is at pawn,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "10": {
      "play": "And, but my going, nothing can redeem it.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "11": {
      "play": "LADY PERCY: O yet, for God’s sake, go not to these wars.",
      "notes": [
        "] J. HUNTER (1845, ii. 54 f.): Shakespeare was pleased with his conception of feminine tenderness in the character of the wife of Hotspur, and, therefore, though Hotspur was dead, and the circumstances of the history little called for it, he introduces the lady again, manifesting her strong affection, and engaging the sympathy and best feelings of the audience; or he might wish thus a second time to turn the public sympathy towards the sister of Essex, and wife of the morose Earl of Northumberland. The whole of this speech is singularly beautiful."
      ]
    },
    "12": {
      "play": "The time was, father, that you broke your word",
      "notes": []
    },
    "13": {
      "play": "When you were more endeared to it than now,",
      "notes": [
        "endear’d] N.E.D. (Endear v. 6b): To bind by obligations of gratitude. [This example is a little earlier than the earliest quoted, Timon iii.ii.30.]—[Q endeere is the result of an e:é error.]"
      ]
    },
    "14": {
      "play": "When your own Percy, when my heart’s dear Harry,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "15": {
      "play": "Threw many a northward look to see his father",
      "notes": [
        "Powres] See note on i.i.206."
      ]
    },
    "16": {
      "play": "Bring up his powers; but he did long in vain.",
      "notes": [
        "long] THEOBALD (ed. 1733): Nothing of longing had been express’d before, which makes me suspect this Reading. Shakespeare ... lov’d a Repetition of the same Word: and as it is immediately before said, that Percy threw many a Northward Look, I am perswaded the Poet wrote; ——but he did look in vain!—CAPELL (Notes, 1779, p. 173): The looks that Percy threw northward were longing looks, hence the word in the text."
      ]
    },
    "17": {
      "play": "Who then persuaded you to stay at home?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "18": {
      "play": "There were two honors lost, yours and your son’s.",
      "notes": [
        "two Honors] Miss Winstanley (ed. 1918): Northumberland’s honor was lost because he failed his son and his friends; Hotspur’s was lost because he was conquered in single combat by Prince Hal. Cf. 1 Henry IV v.iv.78-9, “I better brook the loss of brittle life Than those proud titles thou hast won of me”."
      ]
    },
    "19": {
      "play": "For yours, the God of heaven brighten it.",
      "notes": [
        "] Delius (ed. 1857): She suggests that Northumberland had better entrust the restoration of his lost honor to heaven rather than seek it on the field of battle."
      ]
    },
    "20": {
      "play": "For his, it stuck upon him as the sun",
      "notes": [
        "stucke] Apparently the usual word for expressing the fixity and the lustre of a heavenly body in its sphere. Cf. Hamlet v.ii.249, “Your skill shall, like a star i’ the darkest night, Stick fiery off indeed” (quoted by Deighton, ed. 1893); Antony v.ii.79, “His face was as the heavens; and therein stuck A sun and moon, which kept their course and lighted The little O, the earth” (quoted by Struve, 1851, p. 19); Dekker’s Satiromastix (ed. Pearson, 1873, i. 256), “No black-ey’d star must sticke in vertues Spheare”; Chapman’s Byron’s Tragedy [iv.ii.170], “While Lucifer, foreshows Aurora’s springs, And Arctos sticks above the earth unmov’d” (both quoted by Dyce: A Few Notes, 1853, p. 97).",
        "Sunne] Miss Spurgeon (1935, p. 236) [commenting on Sh.’s frequent use of the sun as an image of kingship]: Harry Percy also, in his wife’s eyes, shares some of the attributes of princes.",
        "his] Collins (ed. 1927): Referring to Hotspur rather than to his honour, although it is the honour that is compared with the sun in the previous line. Such slight shifting of the metaphor is characteristically Shakespearian; cp. i.i.137 ff.",
        "moue] Carries on the celestial metaphor. See N.E.D. (Move v. 16b), “To proceed, pass from one place to another: of the heavenly bodies in their regular course”."
      ]
    },
    "21": {
      "play": "In the gray vault of heaven, and by his light",
      "notes": [
        "gray] Delius (ed. 1857): Indicates the light-blue color of the heavens and of the eyes.—Steevens (Var. ’78) quotes Sonnet cxxxii. 6, “And truly not the morning sun of heaven Better becomes the grey cheeks of the east”. Cowl (ed. 1923) quotes Peele’s Old Wife’s Tale (ed. Bullen, 1888, i. 318), “The day is clear, the welkin bright and grey”. Rolfe (ed. 1880) quotes Romeo ii.iii.1, “The grey-eyed morn”."
      ]
    },
    "22": {
      "play": "Did all the chivalry of England move",
      "notes": [
        "Cheualrie] N.E.D. (Chivalry 1e): As a historical term for the medieval men-at-arms. Occasionally applied poetically or idealistically to ‘cavalry’ or ‘horsemen’ in general, esp. when chivalrous gallantry is attributed. [Quotes this line.]"
      ]
    },
    "23": {
      "play": "To do brave acts. He was indeed the glass",
      "notes": []
    },
    "24": {
      "play": "Wherein the noble youth did dress themselves.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "25": {
      "play": "He had no legs that practiced not his gait;",
      "notes": []
    },
    "26": {
      "play": "And speaking thick, which nature made his blemish,",
      "notes": [
        "thicke] STEEVENS (ed. 1793): Fast, crowding one word on another. [The opposite of tardily (l. 29).]—N.E.D. (Thick adv. 4): With confused and indistinct articulation.—Cf. Cymbeline III.ii.55, “say, and speak thick” (quoted by STEEVENS, op. cit.); Lucrece 1784, “Weak words, so thick come in his poor heart’s aid” (quoted by ROLFE, ed. 1880); Cotgrave (Dictionarie, ed. 1632), “Bretonner. To speake thicke and short; or, as wee say, nine words at once” (quoted by COWL, ed. 1923).—AX (1912, p. 67): We could not find in the chronicle of Henry IV’s reign any passage proving that Hotspur spoke “thick” ... Hotspur himself seems to hint at this defect when he says [1 Henry IV V.ii.91–2]: “I thank him, that he cuts me from my tale, For I profess not talking.” But he manifests in [1 Henry IV] I.iii an astonishing eloquence, which even becomes bombastical when he thinks it “an easy leap, To pluck bright honour from the pale-faced moon”."
      ]
    },
    "27": {
      "play": "Became the accents of the valiant;",
      "notes": [
        "Became] MASON (1785, p. 189): Came to be affected and practised by them.",
        "Accents] On this use of the plural see FRANZ (3 ed., 1924) §680. Cf. l. 60 below, IV.i.203, IV.v.209."
      ]
    },
    "28": {
      "play": "For those that could speak low and tardily",
      "notes": [
        "low, and tardily] Miss SPURGEON (1935, p. 73): It is clear that those [Sh.] most admired spoke ‘low and tardily’.",
        "loues] See note on l. 28 above."
      ]
    },
    "29": {
      "play": "Would turn their own perfection to abuse",
      "notes": []
    },
    "30": {
      "play": "To seem like him. So that in speech, in gait,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "31": {
      "play": "In diet, in affections of delight,",
      "notes": [
        "Diet] SCHMIDT (1874): Food, fare.",
        "Affections of delight] Miss WINSTANLEY (ed. 1918): Choice of pleasures."
      ]
    },
    "32": {
      "play": "In military rules, humors of blood,",
      "notes": [
        "Humors of Blood] ROLFE (ed. 1880): Caprices of disposition.—[See note on ii.i.132 and cf. iv.iv.44.]"
      ]
    },
    "33": {
      "play": "He was the mark and glass, copy and book,",
      "notes": [
        "] MALONE (2 App., 1783) compares Lucrece 615: \"For princes are the glass, the school, the book, Where subjects' eyes do learn, do read, do look\".",
        "Marke] ONIONS (1911): Object serving to mark a spot at sea, sea-mark; fig. guiding object, 'example, pattern' (Schmidt).—[Cf. Winter's Tale iv.iv.8, \"Your high self, The gracious mark o' the land\".]",
        "Coppy] N.E.D. (Copy sb. 8c): fig. Pattern, example. Obs."
      ]
    },
    "34": {
      "play": "That fashioned others. And him—O wondrous him!",
      "notes": [
        "him ... him] COWL (ed. 1923): For the objective case in address, cf. Sonnet xxviii. 14, and Jonson, Volpone i.i [ed. Herford & Simpson, 1925 +, v. 34]: \"Happy, happy me!\""
      ]
    },
    "35": {
      "play": "O miracle of men!—him did you leave,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "36": {
      "play": "Second to none, unseconded by you,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "37": {
      "play": "To look upon the hideous god of war",
      "notes": []
    },
    "38": {
      "play": "In disadvantage, to abide a field",
      "notes": [
        "abide] N.E.D. (Abide v. 14): To await defiantly, to face, to encounter, withstand, or sustain.",
        "field] N.E.D. (Field sb. 8): A battle; now rare."
      ]
    },
    "39": {
      "play": "Where nothing but the sound of Hotspur’s name",
      "notes": [
        "defensible] MALONE (Suppl., 1780): Furnishing the means of defence.—[See ABBOTT (1870) §§3, 445.]"
      ]
    },
    "40": {
      "play": "Did seem defensible. So you left him.",
      "notes": [
        "] LETTSOM (apud Dyce, ed. 1866): There is no emphasis on the pronouns, and consequently the line is defective."
      ]
    },
    "41": {
      "play": "Never, O never, do his ghost the wrong",
      "notes": [
        "Ghost] SCHMIDT (1874): The spirit of a deceased person."
      ]
    },
    "42": {
      "play": "To hold your honor more precise and nice",
      "notes": [
        "nice] SCHMIDT (1875): Precise, accurate."
      ]
    },
    "43": {
      "play": "With others than with him. Let them alone.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "44": {
      "play": "The Marshal and the Archbishop are strong.",
      "notes": [
        "Arch-bishop] See note on I.i.205."
      ]
    },
    "45": {
      "play": "Had my sweet Harry had but half their numbers,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "46": {
      "play": "Today might I, hanging on Hotspur’s neck,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "47": {
      "play": "Have talked of Monmouth’s grave.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "48": {
      "play": "NORTHUMBERLAND: Beshrew your",
      "notes": [
        "Beshrew] N.E.D. (Beshrew 3b): Now only in imprecatory expressions: ‘Evil befall, mischief take, devil take, curse, hang!’; also, with weakened force, ‘plague on’, and often humorous or playful. arch.—[Cf. v.iii.53.]"
      ]
    },
    "49": {
      "play": "heart,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "50": {
      "play": "Fair daughter, you do draw my spirits from me",
      "notes": [
        "draw ... me] COWL (ed. 1923): Dispirít me."
      ]
    },
    "51": {
      "play": "With new lamenting ancient oversights.",
      "notes": [
        "ancient] ROLFE (ed. 1880): Former, bygone [arch.]"
      ]
    },
    "52": {
      "play": "But I must go and meet with danger there,",
      "notes": [
        "meet with] N.E.D. (Meet v. 11c): Meet with. To encounter (an enemy). Obs."
      ]
    },
    "53": {
      "play": "Or it will seek me in another place",
      "notes": []
    },
    "54": {
      "play": "And find me worse provided.",
      "notes": [
        "prouided] COWL (ed. 1923): Prepared."
      ]
    },
    "55": {
      "play": "LADY NORTHUMBERLAND: O, fly to Scotland",
      "notes": [
        "that] Conjunctional affix; see ABBOTT (1870) §287, FRANZ (3 ed., 1924) §546. Cf. iii.i.76, iv.i.41, iv.ii.6, iv.iv.46, 145–6, iv.v.148."
      ]
    },
    "56": {
      "play": "Till that the nobles and the armèd commons",
      "notes": []
    },
    "57": {
      "play": "Have of their puissance made a little taste.",
      "notes": [
        "Puissance] See note on i.iiii.12.",
        "taste] N.E.D. (Taste sb1 3c): fig. A slight experience, received or given."
      ]
    },
    "58": {
      "play": "LADY PERCY: If they get ground and vantage of the King,",
      "notes": [
        "get ground ... of] N.E.D. (Get v. 5c): To get ground of: to encroach upon, obtain the mastery of; to draw away from (pursuers) [quoting this line].—COWL (ed. 1923): A metaphor from fencing."
      ]
    },
    "59": {
      "play": "Then join you with them like a rib of steel",
      "notes": [
        "vantage] ONIONS (1911): Superiority.",
        "Ribbe of Steele] Miss SPURGEON (1935, p. 127): The hooping of a barrel with bands of metal is a favourite image with Shakespeare and serves him to express vividly various ideas of binding, strengthening and embracing. [Cf. Hamlet i.iii.63, Much Ado iv.i.151, Antony ii.ii.119.]—[See also iv.iv.49 below.]"
      ]
    },
    "60": {
      "play": "To make strength stronger; but, for all our loves,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "61": {
      "play": "First let them try themselves. So did your son;",
      "notes": [
        "suffer’d] SCHMIDT (1875): Passive = to be allowed to have one's own way, not to be hindered or interfered with."
      ]
    },
    "62": {
      "play": "He was so suffered. So came I a widow,",
      "notes": [
        "came] N.E.D. (Come v. 24a): To become, get to be (in some condition) [quoting this line]."
      ]
    },
    "63": {
      "play": "And never shall have length of life enough",
      "notes": []
    },
