    "52": {
      "play": "help to make the diseases, Doll. We catch of you,",
      "notes": [
        "We catch of you] WURTH (1895, p. 95): We are infected by you.",
        "of] See ABBOTT (1870) §165, FRANZ (3 ed., 1924) §509.",
        "catch] The primary sense of catch is capture, to which Doll probably alludes. Miss WINSTANLEY (ed. 1918) thinks Doll may mean that Falstaff has borrowed from her; COWL (ed. 1923) interprets catch as wheedle, referring to gifts."
