    "91": {
      "play": "HOSTESS: Tilly-vally, Sir John, ne’er tell me. And your",
      "notes": [
        "Tilly-vally] N.E.D. (Tilly-vally int.): Obs. or arch. An exclamation of impatience: Nonsense! fiddlesticks! [quoting this line].—J. Hunter (1845, ii. 55): This foolish interjection ... was a favourite phrase of the wife of Sir Thomas More; and it is remarkable that the Hostess just before is made to use another of the phrases which were favourites of the same lady, “What the good-year, one must bear,” which looks as if Shakespeare might lately have been reading one of the Lives of Sir Thomas, in which there are amusing specimens at once of the philosophy and eloquence of the lady whom he married, when he had lost his first wife.",
