    "156": {
      "play": "mouldy stewed prunes and dried cakes. A captain?",
      "notes": [
        "He lives upon / mouldy stewed prunes and dried cakes.] JOHNSON (ed. 1765): That is, he lives at other mens cost, but is not admitted to their tables, and gets only what is too stale to be eaten in the house.—STEEVENS (Var. ’73): Rather, that he lives on the refuse provisions of bawdy-houses and pastry-cooks shops.—[On the affinity between stewed prunes and bawdy houses, see Variorum 1 Henry IV, p. 235. Though it appears to have had a real basis in the eating of stewed prunes as a preventive against and cure of venereal infection, I suspect that it was magnified by the playwrights because of the pun on stews. Doll may mean simply that Pistol lives on the meanest fare.—ED.]"
      ]
    },
    "157": {
      "play": "God’s light, these villains will make the word as",
      "notes": []
    },
    "158": {
      "play": "odious as the word “occupy,” which was an excellent",
      "notes": [
        "God's light... ill sorted.] On the omission of this passage from F, see p. 500.",
        "occupy] The sense acquired by this word (=fornicate) to which Doll alludes could be abundantly illustrated from contemporary literature, as it has been by the commentators, but the imprint of William Goddard’s Satirycall Dialogue (c. 1616) will serve for example as well as any: “Imprinted in the Lowcountryes for all such gentlewomen as are not altogeather Idle nor yet well Ocupyed”. STEEVENS (Var. ’73) quotes Jonson’s Discoveries (ed. Castelain, 1906, p. 78): “Many out of their owne obscene Apprehensions, refuse proper and fit words; as occupie, nature, and the like”. The same sense of the word",
        "was ill sorted] HERFORD (ed. 1899): Fell into bad company.—LOBBAN (ed. 1915): [Was] fitted with an evil meaning."
      ]
    },
    "159": {
      "play": "good word before it was ill sorted. Therefore",
      "notes": []
    },
    "160": {
      "play": "captains had need look to ’t.",
      "notes": [
        "had need] N.E.D. (Need sb. 6b): In pret. had need to, would require to, ought to."
      ]
    },
    "161": {
      "play": "BARDOLPH, to Pistol  Pray thee go down, good ancient.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "162": {
      "play": "FALSTAFF: Hark thee hither, Mistress Doll.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "163": {
      "play": "PISTOL, to Bardolph  Not I. I tell thee what, Corporal",
      "notes": [
        "Not I] CLARKE (ed. 1865): Said by Pistol in answer to Bardolph’s urging him to “go down” [l. 152]; although it is crossed by Falstaff’s speech to Doll [l. 153]."
      ]
    },
    "164": {
      "play": "Bardolph, I could tear her. I’ll be revenged of her.",
      "notes": [
        "tear] SCHMIDT (1875): To hurt or destroy in a savage manner.—[N.E.D. quotes Romeo v.iii.35, “I will tear thee joint by joint”.]"
      ]
    },
    "165": {
      "play": "PAGE: Pray thee go down.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "166": {
      "play": "PISTOL: I’ll see her damned first to Pluto’s damnèd",
      "notes": [
        "I'll see her damned first...] STEEVENS (Var. ’78): Of absurd and fustian passages from many plays, in which Shakspeare had been a performer, I have always supposed no small part of Pistol’s character to be composed; and the pieces themselves being now irretrievably lost, the humour of his allusion is not a little obscured.—[To elucidate the obscured humor of Pistol’s bombast, the commentators have hunted high and low for the originals, and what they have found is recorded fully in the ensuing notes. Perhaps it should be pointed out that their various suggestions are by no means of equal value. After all, it may well have been a style of dramatic poetry rather than particular passages in par-",
        "Pluto's damned / lake] Miss WINSTANLEY (ed. 1918): Probably the river Lethe, which Pistol has confused with a lake.—COWL (ed. 1923): Cf. Greene, Alphonsus, King of Aragon iii.ii [ed. Greg, M.S.R., 1926, l. 496]: “Plutoes loathsome lake”.—IDEM (T.L.S. 26 March 1925, p. 222): Cf. 2 Tamburlaine iii.v.: “the lake of hell”.—COLLINS (ed. 1927): The Styx, the river of the ancient underworld, of which Pluto was the king.",
        "Erebus] COWL (ed. 1923) quotes Locrine III.vi [ed. McKerrow, M.S.R., 1908, ll. 1345–6]: “lie dragge thy cursed ghoast Through all the riuers of foule Erebus”.—IDEM (T.L.S. 26 March 1925, p. 222): Cf. 1 Tamburlaine v.ii [179–81]: “the fiends infernal view A hell as hopeless and as full of fear As are the blasted banks of Erebus”.—COLLINS (ed. 1927): Usually the name given to the underworld itself; Erebus, as a person, was the son of Chaos and Night.—COWL (Sources, 1928, p. 44) refers to Æneid iv. 510, where Erebus is apparently the name of a god.",
        "tortures vile] COWL (ed. 1923) quotes Locrine v.vi (ed. McKerrow, M.S.R., 1908, ll. 2089–90): “O you iudges of the ninefold Stix, Which with incessant torments racke the ghoasts”.—[On vilde see note on I.ii.18.]"
      ]
    },
    "167": {
      "play": "lake, by this hand, to th’ infernal deep with Erebus",
      "notes": []
    },
    "168": {
      "play": "and tortures vile also. Hold hook and line, say I.",
      "notes": [
        "Hold hook and line] STEEVENS (Var. ’03): In the frontispiece to an ancient black-letter ballad, entitled The Royal Recreation of Joviall Anglers, one of the figures has the following couplet proceeding from his mouth: “Hold hooke and line, Then all is mine.”—STRUVE (1851, p. 16) interprets this quite literally, as “harpoon and cable to kill the monster”.—SCHMIDT (1874): I.e. become an"
      ]
    },
    "169": {
      "play": "Down, down, dogs! Down, Fates! Have we not",
      "notes": [
        "I'll] ONIONS (1911): Will, with negative, to refuse to have, have nothing to do with.",
        "Fates!] Q faters.—N.E.D. (Faitour 1): An impostor, cheat; esp. a vagrant who shams illness or pretends to tell fortunes. [Apparently the word was obsolescent in the time of Spenser, who uses it freely in the sense of traitor].—WHITE (ed. 1859) defends F Fates on the ground that the absurdity of coupling dogs and “the sisters three” is eminently Pistolian.—[See p. 506.]"
      ]
    },
    "170": {
      "play": "Hiren here?    He draws his sword.",
      "notes": [
        "Have we not / Hiren here?] THEOBALD (letter to Warburton, 2 March 1729) states that the sword of Amadis du Gaul was called Hiren.—CAPELL (Notes, 1779, p. 174): “I am a man of honour, a gentleman; this sword denotes me so.”—MALONE (Suppl., 1780): From The Merie Conceited Jests of George Peele, Gentleman, sometime Student in Oxford ... [Works, ed. Bullen, 1888, ii. 394.] it appears, that Peele ... was ... the author of [a play called The Turkish Mahamet and Hyrrin the Fair Greek, which is now lost.] ... Haue we not Hiren here? was, without doubt, a quotation from this play of Peele’s.—[This play has been identified as the Mahomet or as The love of a gresyan lady recorded by Henslowe or as both (GREG, Henslowe’s Diary, 1904–8, ii. 167, 169; CHAMBERS, Elizabethan Stage, 1923, iii. 462). The story is found in Painter’s Palace of"
      ]
    },
    "171": {
      "play": "HOSTESS: Good Captain Peesell, be quiet. ’Tis very late,",
      "notes": [
        "Peesell] COWL (Arden 1 Henry IV, 3 ed., 1925, p. 204): Mrs. Quickly, mispronouncing the name of Captain Pistol, blunders into a form of the word 'pizzle'."
      ]
    },
    "172": {
      "play": "i’ faith. I beseek you now, aggravate your choler.",
      "notes": [
        "beseek] ROLFE (ed. 1880): Intended as a blunder for beseech, though it is really an old [northern and north midland (N.E.D.)] form and pronunciation of that word.",
        "aggravate your choler] Miss WINSTANLEY (ed. 1918): The Hostess means the exact opposite."
      ]
    },
    "173": {
      "play": "PISTOL: These be good humors indeed. Shall pack-horses",
      "notes": [
        "humors] Caprices. See II.iii.33."
      ]
    },
    "174": {
      "play": "and hollow pampered jades of Asia, which",
      "notes": [
        "Shall pack-horses / and hollow pampered jades of Asia, which / cannot go but thirty mile a day] THEOBALD (letter to Warburton, 17 Jany. 1729): Pistol, 'tis certain, does not deliver himself like a Man of this World; but we'll derive one Testimony from hence, yt all his Extravaganza's are not meer [unmea]ning Wildnesses; but thrown in to convey Strokes of Satyre, & expose the Fustian of some Contemporary Pieces; You must know, Dear Sr, there's an old Play, in 2 Parts, call'd Tamburlaine['s Con]quests; Or, the",
        "hollow pampered] COWL (ed. 1923): Hollow is apparently a misquotation of Marlowe’s “Holla”.",
        "go] SCHMIDT (1874): Walk."
      ]
    },
    "175": {
      "play": "cannot go but thirty mile a day, compare with",
      "notes": [
        "cannot go but] See note on 1.i.231."
      ]
    },
    "176": {
      "play": "Caesars and with cannibals and Troyant Greeks?",
      "notes": [
        "compare with] N.E.D. (Compare v.1 4b): To vie with, rival.",
        "cannibals] JOHNSON (ed. 1765): Used by a blunder for Hannibal.—CARTWRIGHT (1866, p. 18): Read Hannibals. It seems utterly impossible Pistol could have made such a blunder; for Gower, speaking of him, says, “Such fellows are perfect in the great commanders’ names: and they will learn you by rote where services were done.”—Henry V iii.vi.68–70.—COWL (ed. 1923): Elbow, on the other hand, makes the blunder of substituting “Hannibal” for “Cannibal”: “O thou wicked Hannibal!” (Measure ii.i.166–7). —IDEM (T.L.S. 26 March 1925, p. 222): It is hard to believe that even an Elizabethan audience can have immediately recognized the name “Hannibal” in Pistol’s perversion of it, “Cannibal,” unless, indeed, it had been previously prepared for the association of the name and the word. Pistol’s blunder would, in fact, have had humorous associations for an audience that had the privilege of being acquainted with this quaint quatrain in Samuel Brandon’s Virtuous Octavia (1598), i.i.119–122, in which “Cannibal” is in apposition to, and rhymes with, “Hannibal”: “His ancient yeares, made craftie Hanniball Adnire the prones, and vallour of his foe: Thrice bitter name, that cursed Canniball, By bloudie treason, made him life forgoe.”"
      ]
    },
    "177": {
      "play": "Nay, rather damn them with King Cerberus, and let",
      "notes": [
        "Troyant Greeks] CARTWRIGHT (1866, p. 18): Pistol in his off-hand manner merely means Greeks before Troy.",
        "damn them with] According to SCHMIDT (1875), the preposition expresses the effect of the action of the verb, “i.e. so that they may be in hell”.",
        "King Cerberus] ROOT (1903, p. 46): ‘King Cerberus’ ... is one of Pistol’s confusions, and has nothing to do with the [many-headed dog].—COWL (ed. 1923): Pistol may have been led by a passage in Kyd’s Spanish Tragedy [iii.xv, Works, ed. Boas, 1901, p. 80] to associate in mind Cerberus with"
      ]
    },
    "178": {
      "play": "the welkin roar. Shall we fall foul for toys?",
      "notes": [
        "let / the welkin roar.] STEEVENS (Var. '85): Part of the words of an old ballad intitled, \"What the father gathereth with the rake, the son doth scatter with the forke\" [Roxburghe Ballads i, Ballad Society, 1869, p. 134]: \"Let the welkin roare, Ile never give o're,\" &c. Again, in another ancient song called, The Man in the Moon drinks Claret [Roxburghe Ballads ii, Ballad Society, 1873, p. 257]: \"Drink wine till the welkin roars.\"—COWL (T.L.S. 26 March 1925, p. 222): Cf. 1 Tamburlaine iv.ii.: \"the welkin crack\".",
        "fall foul] N.E.D. (Fall v. 86b): Fall foul. To clash, come into conflict (with); to quarrel [quoting this line as its earliest example].",
        "toys] ONIONS (1911): Thing[s] of no substance or value, trifling matter[s]."
      ]
    },
    "179": {
      "play": "HOSTESS: By my troth, captain, these are very bitter",
      "notes": []
    },
    "180": {
      "play": "words.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "181": {
      "play": "BARDOLPH: Begone, good ancient. This will grow to a",
      "notes": []
    },
    "182": {
      "play": "brawl anon.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "183": {
      "play": "PISTOL: Die men like dogs! Give crowns like pins! Have",
      "notes": [
        "Die men like dogs!] COWL (T.L.S. 26 March 1925, p. 222): Gives ludicrous expression to the blood-lust of Tamburlaine (cf. 1 Tamburlaine iii.iii.: \"Let thousands die: their slaughtered carcasses,\" &c.).",
        "Give crowns like pins!] Miss WINSTANLEY (ed. 1918): Probably another allusion to Tamburlaine, where the conqueror distributes crowns to his followers (iii.iii.).—COWL (T.L.S. 26 March 1925, p. 222) quotes also 1 Tamburlaine iv.iv., \"take these three crowns, And pledge me, my contributory kings\"; and 2 Tamburlaine I.[vi.23], \"take here thy crown\"."
      ]
    },
    "184": {
      "play": "we not Hiren here?",
      "notes": [
        "Have we not Hiren here?] MALONE (ed. 1790): I see no ground for supposing that the words bear a different meaning here from what they did in a former passage. He is still, I think, merely quoting the same play he had quoted before."
      ]
    },
    "185": {
      "play": "HOSTESS: O’ my word, captain, there’s none such here.",
      "notes": [
        "O' my word, captain, there's none such here.] THEOBALD (ed. 1733): What wonderful Humour is there in the good Hostess so innocently mistaking Pistol's Drift, fancying that he meant to fight for a Whore in the House, and therefore telling him, On my Word, Captain, there's none such here."
      ]
    },
    "186": {
      "play": "What the good-year, do you think I would deny her?",
      "notes": [
        "What the good-year] See note on ll. 59–60 above."
      ]
    },
    "187": {
      "play": "For God’s sake, be quiet.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "188": {
      "play": "PISTOL: Then feed and be fat, my fair Calipolis. Come,",
      "notes": [
        "fat] MASON (1785, p. 189): To grow fat and bloated, is one of the consequences of the venereal disease; and to that Falstaff probably alludes.—[See Doll’s retort.]",
        "Then feed and be fat, my fair Calipolis.] STEEVENS (Var. '73): This is a burlesque on a line in ... The Battle of Alcazar, &c. printed in 1594, in which Muley Mahomet enters to his wife with lyon's flesh on his sword: \"Feede then and faint not faire Calypolis\" [ed. Greg, M.S.R., 1907, I. 596]. And again, in the same play [I. 584], \"Hold thee Calypolis feed and faint no more.\"—IDEM (Var. '78): And again [I. 617–8]: \"Feede and be fat that we may meete the foe With strength and terror to reuenge our wrong.\""
      ]
    },
    "189": {
      "play": "give ’s some sack. Si fortune me tormente, sperato",
      "notes": [
        "Si fortune me tormente, sperato / me contento.] As Pistol's vaunt seems to be a mixture of two or three languages, many editors have tried to correct it (see textual notes), but, as JOHNSON (ed. 1765) says, \"perhaps it was intended that Pistol should corrupt [the original].\"—[See note on I. 160.]—CAMBRIDGE EDITORS (1864): All the editors assume that Italian is the language meant ... If Pistol's sword were a Toledo blade, the motto would be Spanish.—FARMER (Var. '73): Pistol is only a copy of Hannibal Gonsaga, who vaunted on yielding himself a prisoner, as you may read in an old collection of tales, called Wits Fits and Fancies [by Anthony Copley, 1595]. \"Si fortuna me tormenta, Il speranza me contenta.\" [I have not succeeded in locating this passage in Copley's book.—ED.] And Sir Richard Hawkins, in his [Observations, 1622; ed. Bethune, Hakluyt Society, 1847, p. 25], throws out the same gingling distich on the loss of his pinnace.—DOUCE (1807, I. 452 f.): Pistol ... continues to"
      ]
    },
    "190": {
      "play": "me contento. Fear we broadsides? No, let the fiend",
      "notes": [
        "give fire] N.E.D. (Fire sb. 14): Discharge of firearms; also in phrases, to give fire [&c.]"
      ]
    },
    "191": {
      "play": "give fire. Give me some sack, and, sweetheart, lie",
      "notes": [
        "sweetheart, lie / thou there.] See textual notes.—KEIGHTLEY (1867, p. 241): So, Cavalier Shift in Jonson's Every Man out, etc. iii. 1 [ed. Herford & Simpson, 1925+, iii. 510], says to his rapier “no, my deare, I will not bee diuorc’t from thee.”—COWL (ed. 1923): This gesture may have been suggested by a scene in Mucedorus [III.iii.7-4], where Bremo, a wild man, enters, carrying his club: “Bre. No passengers this morning? ... What, not one? then lie thou there, And rest thyselfe til I haue further neede.”—[Cf. Romeo III.i.5-8, “Thou art like one of those fellows that when he enters the confines of a tavern claps me his sword upon the table, and says ‘God send me no need of thee!’ ”]"
      ]
    },
    "192": {
      "play": "thou there. Laying down his sword. Come we to",
      "notes": []
    },
    "193": {
      "play": "full points here? And are etceteras nothings?",
      "notes": [
        "points] FORTESCUE (Sh.’s England, 1916, i. 129): The defences for the arms were either attached to the gorget and so carried like a milkman’s yoke, or the rerebraces were fastened to the stout fustian or leather garment by ‘points’ which, passing through two holes in the top of the rerebrace, were then tied in a bow knot. ... These points were also the mark of a soldier.—[And not, therefore, of Pistol’s commission, as JOHNSON and many others say.—ED.]",
        "Come we to / full points here? And are etceteras nothings?] JOHNSON (ed. 1765): That is, shall we stop here, shall we have no further entertainment.—CLARKE (ed. 1865): There is a play on the words “full points,” in the double sense of ‘weapon edges’ and ‘grammatical stops’ ... It is as if he had said, ‘Are we to come to a dead stop here, and is there to be no fighting fun?’—N.E.D. (Point sb. A29): A conclusion, completion, culmination, end, ‘period.’ Also full point. Obs.",
        "nothings] There is at least as much likelihood that Q no things is right as that the F reading is. See p. 506."
      ]
    },
    "194": {
      "play": "FALSTAFF: Pistol, I would be quiet.",
      "notes": [
        "be quiet] This must refer to some superfluous thrashing about by Falstaff after Pistol has gone.—ED."
      ]
    },
    "195": {
      "play": "PISTOL: Sweet knight, I kiss thy neaf. What, we have",
      "notes": [
        "neaf] POPE (ed. 1723): From nativa, i.e. a woman slave that is born in one's house.—IDEM (ed. 1728): He would kiss Dol.—THEOBALD (Sh. Restored, 1726, p. 146): I should very little expect that these Parties, in such a Ferment, should come to kissing ... I wonder Mr. Pope did not remember ... the same Word ... had past him in ... the Midsummer Night’s Dream [IV.i.18]. “Bot. Give me your neaf, Mounsieur Mustardseed;—”"
      ]
    },
    "196": {
      "play": "seen the seven stars.",
      "notes": [
        "the seven stars] ONIONS (1911): Pleiades. Also an Elizabethan name for the Great Bear, which may be meant in some of the Shn. instances."
      ]
    },
    "197": {
      "play": "DOLL: For God’s sake, thrust him downstairs. I cannot",
      "notes": []
    },
    "198": {
      "play": "endure such a fustian rascal.",
      "notes": [
        "fustian] N.E.D. (Fustian adj. 3): Worthless, sorry, pretentious [quoting this line].—Miss LINTHICUM (1936, pp. 108 f.): From its substitution for silk materials, grew the figurative meaning of falseness, pretence, or bombast."
      ]
    },
    "199": {
      "play": "PISTOL: “Thrust him downstairs”? Know we not Galloway",
      "notes": [
        "Thrust] N.E.D. (Thrust v. 1): To push, shove, drive. Chiefly with adverb or advb. phr. (Now chiefly literary.) [Quotes this line.]",
        "Galloway / nags] JOHNSON (ed. 1765): Common hackneys.—N.E.D. (Galloway 1): One of a small but strong breed of horses peculiar to Galloway [quoting this line].—SUGDEN (1925, p. 213): He means that Doll is like a Galloway nag, because anyone may ride her."
      ]
    },
    "200": {
      "play": "nags?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "201": {
      "play": "FALSTAFF: Quoit him down, Bardolph, like a shove-groat",
      "notes": [
        "Quoit] N.E.D. (Quoit v. 2): To throw like a quoit [quoting this line as its earliest example].",
        "shove-groat / shilling] ONIONS (1911): Shilling coined in the reign of Edward VI commonly used in the game of shove-groat.—SIEVEKING (Sh.'s England, 1916, ii. 467 f.): The popular amusement of Shovel-board or Shuffle-board consisted in driving a coin or disk by a blow with the hand along a highly polished board into compartments marked out at one end of it. It was also known by many synonyms—Shove-board, Shove-groat, Slide-groat, Slide-thrift, and Slip-groat. The coin most commonly used was a shilling ... The ease with which the coin slid along the smooth board is well illustrated by Ben Jonson in Every Man in his Humour [ed. Herford & Simpson, 1925+, iii. 353]: “(They) made it runne as smooth, of the tongue, as a shoue-groat shilling”."
      ]
    },
    "202": {
      "play": "shilling. Nay, an he do nothing but speak",
      "notes": []
    },
    "203": {
      "play": "nothing, he shall be nothing here.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "204": {
      "play": "BARDOLPH: Come, get you downstairs.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "205": {
      "play": "PISTOL, taking up his sword  What, shall we have",
      "notes": []
    },
    "206": {
      "play": "incision? Shall we imbrue? Then death rock me",
      "notes": [
        "incision] COWL (ed. 1923): Bloodshed.",
        "imbrue] ONIONS (1911): (Of a person) absol. to commit bloodshed. [The line is the earlier of the two examples quoted by N.E.D.]—HERFORD (ed. 1928): A word of melodramatic flavour, used by Thisbe, Dream v.i.335."
      ]
    },
    "207": {
      "play": "asleep, abridge my doleful days. Why then, let",
      "notes": [
        "death rock me / asleep... Come, Atropos, I say.] DOUCE (1807, i. 456): This is manifestly in ridicule of Sackville’s Complaynt of Henry duke of Buckingham, in The mirour for magistrates: “where eke my graūdsyer duke of Buckingham was wounded sore, and hardly skapte wntane. But what may boot to stay the sisters three? When Atropos perforce will cut the threde: The doleful day was come when you might see Northampt̄on fyeld with armed men orespred” [ed. Campbell, 1938, p. 319].",
        "death rock me / asleep] STEEVENS (Var. ’78): This is a fragment of an ancient song supposed to have been written by Anne Boleyn: “O death rock me on slepe, Bring me on quiet rest, &c.”—CHAPPELL (1855, i. 238) prints the words and music from a MS. belonging to E. F. Rimbault; this is also the source of the text in Flügel’s Neuenenglisches Lesebuch (1895, i. 37). Chappell says that there is another copy, with an accompaniment for the lute, in Add. MS. 4900 (British Museum). F. M. PADELFORD (Early 16th Century Lyrics, 1907, p. 103) prints a text from Add. MS. 15,117, from which Chappell (ed. Wooldridge, 1893, i. 111) quotes another setting. Miss E. M. BROUGHAM (Corn from Olde Fieldes, 1918, pp. 211 ff.) prints another version from Add. MS. 26,737."
      ]
    },
    "208": {
      "play": "grievous, ghastly, gaping wounds untwind the Sisters",
      "notes": [
        "abridge my doleful days] COWL (ed. 1923): Burlesquing, perhaps, Sabren’s last speech in Locrine [ed. McKerrow, M.S.R., 1908, II. 2244-51]: “I my selfe ... Meane to abridge my former destenies”. Cf. Kyd, Soliman and Perseda II.iii.: “Death. ... I abridgde his life”.—IDEM (T.L.S. 26 March 1925, p. 222): Cf. 1 Tamburlaine v.[ii.223]: “abridge thy baneful days”.—[“O dolefull day” occurs in Preston’s Cambises, ed. Farmer (S.F.E., 1910), sig. C2v.]",
        "grievous, ghastly, gaping wounds] COWL (T.L.S. 26 March 1925, p. 222): Cf. 1 Tamburlaine II.vii.: “now doth ghastly death With greedy talents gripe my bleeding heart, And like a harpy tires on my life”, and 2 Tamburlaine III.ii.: “a gaping wound”."
      ]
    },
    "209": {
      "play": "Three. Come, Atropos, I say.",
      "notes": [
        "untwind the Sisters / Three] ROLFE (ed. 1880) quotes Thisbe's apostrophe to the fates in Dream v.1.327 ff.—Miss WINSTANLEY (ed. 1918): Pistol, as usual, hopelessly confuses his classical allusions and speaks as if the Three Sisters or Fates were twined or bound together.—COWL (Sources, 1928, p. 24) suggests that Sh. is burlesquing the invocation to the fates in Richard Edwards's Damon and Pythias (Dramatic Writings, ed. Farmer, 1906, p. 30): \"Gripe me, you greedy grief And present pangs of death, You sisters three, with cruel hands With speed now stop my breath\".",
        "untwind] Q untwinde, according to N.E.D., is a rare equivalent of untwine. It quotes Wyatt's version of Psalm xxxvii. 104 [Poems, ed. Foxwell, 1913, i. 202], Wyrley's True Use of Armorie (1592, p. 34), and Machin's Dumb Knight, sig. D2v.",
        "Come, Atropos, I say.] STEEVENS (ed. 1793): Perhaps Pistol alludes to a poem printed in A Gorgeous Gallery of gallant Inuentions, &c. 4to. 1578. \"The Louer complayneth of his Ladie's Inconstancy\" ...: \"I hate this lothsome life O Atropos draw nie, Vntwist yᵉ thred of mortall strife Send death and let mee die.\"—COWL (ed. 1923): Again, perhaps, burlesquing Locrine [ed. McKerrow, M.S.R., 1908, I. 228], where ... Sabren apostrophises Atropos: \"Sweet Atropos, cut off my fatall thred\"."
      ]
    },
    "210": {
      "play": "HOSTESS: Here’s goodly stuff toward!",
      "notes": [
        "Here's goodly stuff toward!] COWL (ed. 1923): Here's a nice \"to-do\" ... Mrs. Quickly may, however, be alluding to Atropos as \"goodly stuff\"; cf. \"good stuff,\" the usual English translation of It[alian] bona-roba [see iii.ii.26].",
        "toward] ONIONS (1911): In preparation, about to take place, forthcoming."
      ]
    },
    "211": {
      "play": "FALSTAFF: Give me my rapier, boy.",
      "notes": [
        "Give me my rapier, boy.] GRAF (1892, p. 42): In the tavern scene, where he encounters Pistol, Falstaff's wit, otherwise so abundantly sparkling, seems to have dried up. He must even shake off his imperturbable phlegm to throw out the swashbuckler and for a long time afterwards he cannot overcome his anger."
      ]
    },
