        "rogue] This line is the earliest example quoted by N.E.D. (Rogue sb. 3, “One who is of a mischievous disposition. Common as a playful term of reproof or reproach, and freq. used as a term of endearment by 17th c. dramatists.”)",
        "toss the rogue in a / blanket] Cowl (ed. 1923): A punishment inflicted in contempt upon cowards."
