      "play": "FALSTAFF: He a good wit? Hang him, baboon. His wit’s",
      "notes": []
    },
    "257": {
      "play": "as thick as Tewkesbury mustard. There’s no more",
      "notes": [
        "Tewkesbury mustard] GREY (1754, i. 353): Tewksbury is a fair market town in the county of Gloucester, noted for the mustard balls made there, and sent into other parts."
      ]
    },
    "258": {
      "play": "conceit in him than is in a mallet.",
      "notes": [
        "conceit] N.E.D. (Conceit sb. 8d): Gaiety of imagination, wit [quoting this line].",
        "mallet] Usually taken as meaning a wooden hammer, but KNIGHT (ed. 1839) and DELIUS (ed. 1857) explain it as mallard, i.e. the male wild duck, of which mallet is a 17th-century spelling. I do not know of any association of the mallard and stupidity.—Ed."
      ]
    },
    "259": {
      "play": "DOLL: Why does the Prince love him so then?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "260": {
      "play": "FALSTAFF: Because their legs are both of a bigness, and",
      "notes": []
    },
    "261": {
      "play": "he plays at quoits well, and eats conger and fennel,",
      "notes": [
        "conger and fennel] On conger see note on l. 55 above. Fennel is, according to ONIONS (1911), a \"fragrant yellow-flowered perennial, Faeniculum vulgare, used in fish-sauces\", and according to both him and Schmidt, considered an emblem of flattery.—STEEVENS (Var. '73): Conger with fennel was formerly regarded as a provocative.—IDEM (Var. '78) refers to Philaster II.ii (Works of Beaumont & Fletcher, ed. Glover & Waller, 1905-10, i. 93): \"your Grace must flie Phlebotomie, fresh Pork, Conger, and clarified Whay; They are all dullers of the vital spirits.\"—NARES (ed. 1859): Therefore, to eat conger and fennel, was to eat two high and hot things together, which was esteemed an act of libertinism.—WHITE (ed. 1859): The explanation universally given since Steevens’ note, that conger and fennel were considered provocatives, is not sustained by contemporary authority; and in the very passage in Philaster II.ii to which he refers, \"the wanton Spanish prince\" is advised to abstain from this article of luxury because it is a \"duller of the vital spirits\".—BESLY (1864, p. 158): [Fennel] was used as a sauce with fish hard of digestion.—COWL (ed. 1923): I.e. has a good digestion and a dull wit. The conger is described by writers on gastronomy as having remarkably firm and hard \"flesh\" which needs much stewing to render it digestible. ... [The warning against conger &c. given Pharamond in Philaster means] they will make you grow stupid and fat."
      ]
    },
    "262": {
      "play": "and drinks off candles’ ends for flap-dragons, and",
      "notes": [
        "drinks off candles' ends for flap-dragons] STEELE (Tatler No. 85, 25 Oct. 1709): There is a play, Jenny, I have formerly been at when I was a student: we got into a dark corner with a porringer of brandy, and threw raisins into it, then set it on fire. My chamber-fellow and I diverted ourselves with the sport of venturing our fingers for the raisins; and the wantonness of the thing was to see each other look like a dæmon, as we burnt ourselves, and snatched out the fruit. This fantastical mirth was called Snap-Dragon.—JOHNSON (Var. '73):"
      ]
    },
    "263": {
      "play": "rides the wild mare with the boys, and jumps upon",
      "notes": [
        "boys] Delius (ed. 1857): Servants or waiters.—Cowl (ed. 1923): Youngsters.",
        "joint stools] N.E.D. (Joint-stool 1): A stool made by a joiner, as distinguished from one of more clumsy workmanship. Obs."
      ]
    },
    "264": {
      "play": "joint stools, and swears with a good grace, and",
      "notes": [
        "with a good grace] N.E.D. (Grace sb. 1c): (With a mixture of branch 11 [=favor]), with a good grace, with a show of willingness, as though pleased to do so.—[Or perhaps Falstaff means merely very well.—Ed.]"
      ]
    },
    "265": {
      "play": "wears his boots very smooth like unto the sign of",
      "notes": [
        "wears his boots very smooth] Cowl (ed. 1923): Poins, having a good leg, wore well-fitting boots. Those, on the contrary, whose legs were indifferent, would wear ruffled boots.",
        "the sign of / the Leg] Rolfe (ed. 1880): A sign over the shop-door of a boot-maker (Hunter)."
      ]
    },
    "266": {
      "play": "the Leg, and breeds no bate with telling of discreet",
      "notes": [
        "bate] N.E.D. (Bate sb.1): Discord. Obs.",
        "with telling of discreet / stories] Steevens (Var. ’78): I suppose by discreet stories, is meant what suspicious masters and mistresses of families would call prudential information; i.e. what ought to be known, and yet is disgraceful to the teller.—Douce (1807, i. 458): [Falstaff means that] he excites no censure for telling them modest stories; or in plain English, he tells them nothing but immodest ones.—Lee (ed. 1908): In other words, his indecencies satisfy all demands.—Collins (ed. 1927): Probably “slanderous stories told in confidence”."
      ]
    },
    "267": {
      "play": "stories, and such other gambol faculties he has that",
      "notes": [
        "gambol] N.E.D. (Gambol sb. 4): attrib. (quasi-adj.) Sportive, playful. Obs. [Quotes this line as its earliest example.]"
      ]
    },
    "268": {
      "play": "show a weak mind and an able body, for the which",
      "notes": []
    },
    "269": {
      "play": "the Prince admits him; for the Prince himself is",
      "notes": [
        "admits] N.E.D. (Admit v. 1d): To allow to enter, let in, receive into the number or fellowship of. Obs."
      ]
    },
    "270": {
      "play": "such another. The weight of a hair will turn the",
      "notes": [
        "turn the / scales] As the omission of the article in a phrase like this seems exceptional (see FRANZ, 3 ed., 1924, §267), perhaps Q turne scales is a typographical error."
      ]
