    "291": {
      "play": "FALSTAFF: What stuff wilt thou have a kirtle of? I shall",
      "notes": [
        "kirtle] The early commentators carried on a long controversy over the meaning of this word, which may be read in Var. and in Gifford’s ed. of Jonson (1816), ii. 260.—Miss Linthicum (1936, p. 185 f.): Used over petticoats and farthingale as an outside dress, but a gown or cloak was worn over it. It consisted of a separable bodice, called a ‘pair of bodies’, and a skirt. … The kirtle was open in front from neck to feet, the stomacher filling in the opening of the bodice."
      ]
