    "317": {
      "play": "and turn all to a merriment if you take not the heat.",
      "notes": [
        "merriment] N.E.D. (Merriment 1): Something that contributes to mirth; a jest; ‘a piece of fooling’; spec. a brief comic dramatic entertainment. Obs. [Quotes this line.]",
        "take the heat] STEEVENS (ed. 1793): Alluding, I suppose, to the proverb, “Strike while the iron is hot.” So again, in King Lear [I.i.306]: “We must do something, and i’ the heat.”—CLARKE (ed. 1865): Do not get the start of him.—Miss WINSTANLEY (ed. 1918): Unless you at once grow angry.—COWL (ed. 1923): Act promptly; a metaphor, Craig thinks, from the smith’s forge. ... The sense may be “catch fire,” “warm to the encounter.”"
      ]
