        "Didst thou hear me?] C. F. T. BROOKE (Yale Review vii, 1918, p. 353): [Falstaff has a] trick of mischievously teasing the complaining victim, drawing him on from irritation to positive anger for sheer pride of intellectual superiority; allowing half-derisive confessions of abuse to accumulate till the victim is ready to strike, and then by a dexterous turn of phrase leaping clear away and leaving the dazed antagonist more firmly in his power than before."
