      "notes": []
    },
    "380": {
      "play": "Bareheaded, sweating, knocking at the taverns",
      "notes": []
    },
    "381": {
      "play": "And asking everyone for Sir John Falstaff.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "382": {
      "play": "PRINCE: By heaven, Poins, I feel me much to blame",
      "notes": [
        "By heaven, Poins, I feel me much to blame...] CSERNYINKA (Jahrbuch xxxiii, 1897, p. 69): We should ill understand the poet’s intentions if we did not already infer from the prince’s words to Poins ... a complete break with Falstaff.",
        "to blame] Q too blame.—N.E.D. (Blame v. 6): The dat. infin. to blame is much used as the predicate after be. In the 16–17th c. the to was misunderstood as too, and blame taken as adj. = blameworthy, culpable."
      ]
    },
    "383": {
      "play": "So idly to profane the precious time",
      "notes": []
    },
    "384": {
      "play": "When tempest of commotion, like the south",
      "notes": [
        "commotion] N.E.D. (Commotion 4): Public disturbance or disorder; tumult, sedition, insurrection.—[Cf. IV.i.45, 102.]",
        "the south] ROLFE (ed. 1880): The south wind. See As You Like It [III.v.50, “Like foggy south, puffing with wind and rain”].—DYER (1884, p. 94): A popular saying ... tells us that: “When the wind is in the south, It is in the rain’s mouth.” Again, in days gone by, the southerly winds were generally supposed to be bearers of noxious fogs and vapors. [Cf. Cymbeline III.iii.131, 1 Henry IV V.i.3–6.]",
        "Borne] CLARKE (Sh. Key, 1879, p. 534): ‘Laden,’ ‘charged,’ ‘freighted.’—[It is hard to imagine what else the word could mean here, but N.E.D. does not define the word in this sense.]"
      ]
    },
    "385": {
      "play": "Borne with black vapor, doth begin to melt",
      "notes": []
    },
    "386": {
      "play": "And drop upon our bare unarmèd heads.—",
      "notes": []
    },
    "387": {
      "play": "Give me my sword and cloak.—Falstaff, good",
      "notes": [
        "Give me my sword and cloak.—Falstaff, good / night.] RITSON (apud Steevens, ed. 1793, viii. 595): “Give me my sword and cloak; good night, Oldcastle”. [See note on l. 365 above.]"
      ]
    },
    "388": {
      "play": "[night.   Prince, Peto, and Poins exit.]",
      "notes": [
        "Falstaff, good night.] A. E. MORGAN (1924, p. 40): [The division of this line in F] may indicate that ‘Falstaffe, good night’ was an addition made to stop a gap caused by cutting, but it is not quite clear at what point in the history of the MS. it could have been inserted, as it occurs in Q.—[See p. 495.]",
        "Prince, Peto, and Poins exit.] Miss PORTER (ed. 1911) protests against Capell’s removing Bardolph from the stage along with the prince and Poins; she argues that Bardolph could receive the message which he imparts to Falstaff (ll. 377–8) at the door. Capell’s arrangement probably shows a sounder instinct for effective stage business, whatever else may be said about it.—ED."
      ]
    },
    "389": {
      "play": "FALSTAFF: Now comes in the sweetest morsel of the",
      "notes": [
        "the sweetest morsel of the / night] ROLFE (ed. 1880): Cf. v.iii.47–8."
      ]
    },
    "390": {
      "play": "night, and we must hence and leave it unpicked.",
      "notes": [
        "must hence] On the suppression of a verb of motion following will, shall, must, &c., and preceding an adverb or a prepositional phrase, see ABBOTT (1870) §405, FRANZ (3 ed., 1924) §621. Cf. I. 377 below, iii.i.114, iii.ii.16, 223, 283, 291, 296, iv.iii.130, v.i.4, v.ii.48.",
        "unpicked] SCHMIDT (1875): Unplucked, ungathered, unenjoyed.—[N.E.D. quotes only one other (later) example of this sense.]"
      ]
    },
    "391": {
      "play": "(Knocking. Bardolph exits.) More knocking at the",
      "notes": []
    },
    "392": {
      "play": "[door? (Bardolph returns.) How now, what’s the]",
      "notes": []
    },
    "393": {
      "play": "matter?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "394": {
      "play": "BARDOLPH: You must away to court, sir, presently.",
      "notes": [
        "presently] See note on II.i.159."
      ]
    },
    "395": {
      "play": "A dozen captains stay at door for you.",
      "notes": [
        "A dozen captains stay at door for you.] MORGAN (1777, p. 36): What are we to infer from Falstaff’s being sent for to Court on this ill news, but that his opinion was to be asked, as a Military man of skill and experience, concerning the defences necessary to be taken.",
        "A dozen] STOLL (M.P. xii, 1914, p. 214): A ballad-like exaggeration ... Like Capulet’s “twenty cunning cooks” they “stay at door”.",
        "stay] ONIONS (1911): Wait for."
      ]
    },
    "396": {
      "play": "FALSTAFF, to Page  Pay the musicians, sirrah.—",
      "notes": [
        "Pay the musicians] LOBBAN (ed. 1915): An astonishing first thought to come from Falstaff. But he delegates the duty.—COWL (ed. 1923): The Page carried Falstaff’s purse (II.ii.215), and it was the duty of a page to make incidental payments in behalf of his master."
      ]
    },
    "397": {
      "play": "Farewell, hostess.—Farewell, Doll. You see, my",
      "notes": []
    },
    "398": {
      "play": "good wenches, how men of merit are sought after.",
      "notes": [
        "how men of merit are sought after. / The undeserver may sleep when the man of action / is called on.] MORGAN (1777, pp. 36 f.): Nor is Shakespeare content, here, with leaving us to gather up Falstaff’s better Character from inference and deduction: He comments on the fact by making Falstaff observe that “Men of merit” [&c.]"
      ]
    },
    "399": {
      "play": "The undeserver may sleep when the man of action",
      "notes": []
    },
    "400": {
      "play": "is called on. Farewell, good wenches. If I be not sent",
      "notes": []
    },
    "401": {
      "play": "away post, I will see you again ere I go.",
      "notes": [
        "post] SCHMIDT (1875): Adverbially=in haste."
      ]
    },
    "402": {
      "play": "DOLL: I cannot speak. If my heart be not ready to",
      "notes": []
    },
    "403": {
      "play": "burst—well, sweet Jack, have a care of thyself.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "404": {
      "play": "FALSTAFF: Farewell, farewell.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "405": {
      "play": "He exits with Bardolph, Page, and Musicians.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "406": {
      "play": "HOSTESS: Well, fare thee well. I have known thee these",
      "notes": [
        "Well, fare thee well. I have known thee...] HUDSON (ed. 1852, v. 298 f.): She plainly wants to say some good of him, which she cannot quite say, it is so glaringly untrue: the only instance, by the way, of her being checked by any scruples on that score. [This is quite wrong: the hostess chokes up with genuine emotion.—Ed.]—CLARKE (ed. 1865): These valedictory words (printed also in the Folio with a dash, to indicate a broken speech, as if unfinished from incapacity to express all she feels of admiration), uttered by Hostess Quickly after nearly thirty years of experience of Sir John’s honesty and truth, serve better than pages of commentary upon his powers of fascination, to show how strong is the spell he exercises upon the judgment and affections of those with whom he associates. The hostess’s blind idolatry, Bardolph’s toughly worshipping attachment (as seen in Henry V) form the handsomest excuse for the bewitchment with which the prince seeks his society.—PRIESTLEY (1925, p. 80): Falstaff is neither honest nor true-hearted, as she has known to her cost, but he has her admiration and affection, and so she uses the words of praise that come most easily to her tongue.—STOLL (Sh. Studies, 1927, p. 486): Mrs Quickly even momentarily [attributes] to him that one thing which (none should know so well as she) he lacketh ... What a testimony and tribute, entirely fallacious!"
      ]
    },
    "407": {
      "play": "twenty-nine years, come peasecod time, but an",
      "notes": []
    },
    "408": {
      "play": "honester and truer-hearted man—well, fare thee",
      "notes": []
    },
    "409": {
      "play": "well.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "410": {
      "play": "BARDOLPH, within  Mistress Tearsheet!",
      "notes": []
    },
    "411": {
      "play": "HOSTESS: What’s the matter?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "412": {
      "play": "BARDOLPH, within  Bid Mistress Tearsheet come to my",
      "notes": []
    },
    "413": {
      "play": "master.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "414": {
      "play": "HOSTESS: O, run, Doll, run, run, good Doll. Come.—",
      "notes": []
    },
    "415": {
      "play": "She comes blubbered.—Yea! Will you come, Doll?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "416": {
      "play": "[They exit.]",
      "notes": []
