    "123": {
      "play": "MOULDY: I was pricked well enough before, an you",
      "notes": [
        "I was pricked well enough before] DEIGHTON (ed. 1893): I have always had plenty of pricking, goading, by my wife. [See next note.]—O. F. ADAMS (Irving ed., 1888) compares Sonnet xx. 13, “But since she prick’d thee out for women’s pleasure”, and LEE (ed. 1908) calls this “unedifying quibbling”.",
        "pricked] N.E.D. (Prick v. 20): To attire (a person) with clothes and ornaments. Now dial."
      ]
    },
    "124": {
      "play": "could have let me alone. My old dame will be",
      "notes": [
