    "276": {
      "play": "choose a man? Care I for the limb, the thews, the",
      "notes": [
        "Care I for the limb... Give me the spirit] CARTER (1905, p. 277): 1 Sam. xvi. 7—“But the Lorde said unto Samuel, Looke not on his fashion, or on the heigth of his stature, because I haue refused hym: For God seeth not as man seeth. For man looketh on the outwarde appearance, but the Lorde beholdeth the hart.”—STOLL (M.P. xii, 1914, p. 229): He cries, “Give me the spirit, Master Shallow,” meaning, “give me the crowns and shillings, Mouldy and Bullcalf.”",
        "thews] N.E.D. (Thew sb.^1 3b): pl. The bodily powers or forces of a man (L. vires), might, strength, vigour; in Sh., bodily proportions, lineaments, or parts, as indicating physical strength [quoting this line]."
      ]
    },
    "277": {
      "play": "stature, bulk and big assemblance of a man? Give",
      "notes": [
        "bulk] COWL’s explanation (ed. 1923), trunk (see N.E.D., Bulk sb.^1 2), does not seem to me to go so well with the other nouns of the sentence as does the sense magnitude.—ED.",
        "assemblance] N.E.D. (Assemblance^2): Obs. Semblance, appearance, show [quoting this line].—So also SCHMIDT. ONIONS marks this definition disputed. ROLFE (ed. 1880) and COWL (ed. 1923) gloss the word tout ensemble."
      ]
    },
    "278": {
      "play": "me the spirit, Master Shallow. Here’s Wart. You see",
      "notes": [
        "it is] See note on II.i.5."
      ]
    },
    "279": {
      "play": "what a ragged appearance it is. He shall charge you",
      "notes": []
    },
    "280": {
      "play": "and discharge you with the motion of a pewterer’s",
      "notes": [
        "charge you and discharge you] I.e. load and fire (his musket). See notes on II.iv.113, 114."
      ]
    },
    "281": {
      "play": "hammer, come off and on swifter than he that",
      "notes": [
        "with the motion of a pewterer's hammer] COWL quotes Cooke’s Greene’s Tu Quoque (Hazlitt’s Dodsley, 1874, xi. 236): “as a drummer,—or a pewterer ... one beats on a drum, t’other a platter”.",
        "come off and on] DEIGHTON (ed. 1893): Retreat and advance.—[See note on II.iv.51.]"
      ]
    },
    "282": {
      "play": "gibbets on the brewer’s bucket. And this same half-faced",
      "notes": [
        "gibbets on the brewer's bucket] JOHNSON (ed. 1765): Swifter than he that carries beer from the vat to the barrel, in buckets hung upon a gibbet or beam crossing his shoulders.—MASON (1785, p. 192): The carrying beer from the vat to the barrel, must be a matter that requires more labour than swiftness. Falstaff seems to mean, “swifter than he that puts the buckets on the gibbet;” for as the buckets at each end of the gibbet must be put on at the same instant, it necessarily requires a quick motion.—N.E.D. (Gibbet v. 1.): intr. To hang as on a gibbet. Obs. [Quotes this line only.] (Bucket sb.2): A beam or yoke on which anything may be hung or carried [quoting this line].—[Johnson must be wrong, then, in equating gibbet and yoke.]"
      ]
    },
    "283": {
      "play": "fellow, Shadow, give me this man. He presents",
      "notes": [
        "half-faced] N.E.D. (Half-faced a. 1): Presenting a half-face or profile. Of a coin: having a profile stamped upon it; hence, of persons, having a thin, pinched face. [Quotes this line.]"
      ]
    },
    "284": {
      "play": "no mark to the enemy. The foeman may with",
      "notes": []
    },
    "285": {
      "play": "as great aim level at the edge of a penknife. And for",
      "notes": [
        "as great aim] COWL (ed. 1923): As large a target or mark [N.E.D., Aim sb. 6]."
      ]
    },
    "286": {
      "play": "a retreat, how swiftly will this Feeble, the woman’s",
      "notes": [
        "retreat] A common 16th-century form, but, according to ONIONS (1911), occurring in Sh. only here."
      ]
