    "13": {
      "play": "Their cold intent, tenor, and substance, thus:",
      "notes": []
    },
    "14": {
      "play": "Here doth he wish his person, with such powers",
      "notes": [
        "COURTENAY (1840, i. 128): Shakspeare's archbishop imputes to [Northumberland] irresolution, if not perfidy. The Chronicles rather impute \"too much haste\" to the archbishop. [See p. 537.] cold] N.E.D. (Cold a. 10): Chilling, the reverse of encouraging. intent] N.E.D. (Intent sb. 5): Meaning; import; purport. Obs. tenure] A spelling of tenor recorded by N.E.D. from the 14th through the 18th century. Cf. v.v.79.",
        "Powers] See note on I.i.206."
      ]
    },
    "15": {
      "play": "As might hold sortance with his quality,",
      "notes": [
        "hold sortance] ROLFE (ed. 1880): Be in accordance.—N.E.D. defines sortance as \"agreement, correspondence\", quotes only this line, and indicates that there is no other recorded use of the word. Qualitie] SCHMIDT (1875): Rank."
      ]
    },
    "16": {
      "play": "The which he could not levy; whereupon",
      "notes": []
    },
    "17": {
      "play": "He is retired, to ripe his growing fortunes,",
      "notes": [
        "is retyr’d] See note on I.i.8. ripe] SCHMIDT (1875): To make ripe, to mature."
      ]
    },
    "18": {
      "play": "To Scotland, and concludes in hearty prayers",
      "notes": []
    },
    "19": {
      "play": "That your attempts may overlive the hazard",
      "notes": [
        "Attempts] N.E.D. (Attempt sb. 3a): A warlike enterprise; an attack, assault, onset. Obs. or arch. ouer-liue] N.E.D. (Overlive v.): To survive, outlive.—ROLFE (ed. 1880): Used by Sh. only here."
      ]
    },
    "20": {
      "play": "And fearful meeting of their opposite.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "21": {
      "play": "MOWBRAY: Thus do the hopes we have in him touch ground",
      "notes": [
        "ground] N.E.D. (Ground sb. 2b): The bottom [of the sea] at a point where the water becomes too shallow for a vessel, etc. to float [quoting this line as its earliest example]."
      ]
    },
    "22": {
      "play": "And dash themselves to pieces.",
      "notes": []
    },
