    },
    "25": {
      "play": "MESSENGER: West of this forest, scarcely off a mile,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "26": {
      "play": "In goodly form comes on the enemy,",
      "notes": [
        "forme] N.E.D. (Form sb. 8): Regularity, good order; also, military formation [quoting this line]."
      ]
    },
    "27": {
      "play": "And, by the ground they hide, I judge their number",
      "notes": []
    },
    "28": {
      "play": "Upon or near the rate of thirty thousand.",
      "notes": [
        "Vpon] N.E.D. (Upon prep. 3b): About; near; close on (a specified number, etc.). Obs. rate] N.E.D. (Rate sb.^1 1): The (total) computed or estimated quantity, amount, or sum of anything. Obs. [Quotes this line as its last example.]"
      ]
    },
    "29": {
      "play": "MOWBRAY: The just proportion that we gave them out.",
      "notes": [
        "iust] N.E.D. (Just a. 9): Exact, as opposed to approximate. Obs. proportion] N.E.D. (Proportion sb. 5): Size or extent, relatively to some standard.",
        "iust] SCHMIDT (1874): Exact, precise."
      ]
    },
    "30": {
      "play": "Let us sway on and face them in the field.",
      "notes": [
        "sway-on] Heath (1765, p. 259): [Expresses] the fluctuating march of an army.—Johnson (ed. 1765): Intended to express the uniform and forcible motion of a compact body.—N.E.D. (Sway v. 4b): To have a certain direction in movement; to move. Obs. [Quotes this line as its earliest example, two others from Sh. (Twelfth Night II.iv.30, Macbeth V.iii.9), and one more dated 1650.]"
      ]
    },
