    "124": {
      "play": "That need to be revived and breathed in me?",
      "notes": [
        "need] See note on I.iii.82. breath’d] SCHMIDT (1874): Adj., endowed with breath."
      ]
    },
    "125": {
      "play": "The King that loved him, as the state stood then,",
      "notes": [
        "as ... then] DEIGHTON (ed. 1893): I.e. when Richard was king.",
        "] Miss WINSTANLEY (ed. 1918) quotes Richard II I.iii.148–9: “Norfolk, for thee remains a heavier doom, Which I with some unwillingness pronounce”. 126 ff.] This episode is dramatized in Richard II I.iii."
      ]
    },
    "126": {
      "play": "Was force perforce compelled to banish him,",
      "notes": [
        "forc’d, perforce] See textual notes.—SCHMIDT (1874): Force perforce, by violence, against one’s will.—[Cf. IV.iv.52.]"
      ]
    },
    "127": {
      "play": "And then that Henry Bolingbroke and he,",
      "notes": [
        "then, that] ABBOTT (1870, §284): Apparently “then when”.—N.E.D. (Then adv. 6) explains that then was used as a relative or conjunctive adverb of time=when, though it quotes no example later than a 1440, and that that was added to the demonstrative adverbs then, there, etc., when used as relatives, though it gives no example of the combination then that (That conj. 6)."
      ]
    },
    "128": {
      "play": "Being mounted and both rousèd in their seats,",
      "notes": [
        "rowsed] N.E.D. (Rouse v. 3b): To raise or lift up. Obs. [Quotes this line as its earliest example.]"
      ]
    },
    "129": {
      "play": "Their neighing coursers daring of the spur,",
      "notes": [
        "daring ... Spurre] SCHMIDT (1874): Probably=their coursers, by neighing, challenging the spur to give the signal of setting off.—ONIONS (1911) repeats Schmidt’s explanation, but marks it disputed."
      ]
    },
    "130": {
      "play": "Their armèd staves in charge, their beavers down,",
      "notes": [
        "Staues] N.E.D. (Staff sb.1 3b): A spear, lance, or similar armed weapon [quoting this line]. charge] N.E.D. (Charge sb. 17): The position of a weapon ready for action [quoting this line as its earliest example]. Beuaers] N.E.D. (Beaver2): Obs. ‘The lower portion of the face-guard of a helmet, when worn with a visor; but occasionally serving the purposes of both.’—FORTESCUE (Sh.’s England, 1916, i. 130): Sometimes used for the visor, as [here]."
      ]
    },
    "131": {
      "play": "Their eyes of fire sparkling through sights of steel,",
      "notes": [
        "sights] N.E.D. (Sight sb.1 13b): A visor. Obs. [Quotes this line.]"
      ]
    },
    "132": {
      "play": "And the loud trumpet blowing them together,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "133": {
      "play": "Then, then, when there was nothing could have",
      "notes": []
    },
    "134": {
      "play": "stayed",
      "notes": []
    },
    "135": {
      "play": "My father from the breast of Bolingbroke,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "136": {
      "play": "O, when the King did throw his warder down—",
      "notes": [
        "Warder] ONIONS (1911): Staff or mace held by one presiding over a combat."
      ]
    },
    "137": {
      "play": "His own life hung upon the staff he threw—",
      "notes": []
    },
    "138": {
      "play": "Then threw he down himself and all their lives",
      "notes": [
        "all their Liues] The lives of all those. On this construction see ABBOTT (1870) §218, FRANZ (3 ed., 1924) §321."
      ]
    },
    "139": {
      "play": "That by indictment and by dint of sword",
      "notes": []
    },
    "140": {
      "play": "Have since miscarried under Bolingbroke.",
      "notes": [
        "dint of Sword] N.E.D. (Dint sb. 2b): phr. By dint of sword: by force of arms. Obs.",
        "mis-carryed] N.E.D. (Miscarry v. 1): To come to harm, misfortune, or destruction; to perish; (of a person) to meet with one’s death."
      ]
    },
    "141": {
      "play": "WESTMORELAND: You speak, Lord Mowbray, now you know not what.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "142": {
      "play": "The Earl of Hereford was reputed then",
      "notes": [
        "Earle] CAPELL (Notes, 1779, p. 178): (Whether a slip of the poet himself, or of his printer) [this] ought to have been corrected, his style being “duke” at this time. Hereford] WALKER (Sh.'s Versification, 1854, p. 1): A dissyllable."
      ]
    },
    "143": {
      "play": "In England the most valiant gentleman.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "144": {
      "play": "Who knows on whom fortune would then have",
      "notes": []
    },
    "145": {
      "play": "smiled?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "146": {
      "play": "But if your father had been victor there,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "147": {
      "play": "He ne’er had borne it out of Coventry;",
      "notes": [
        "had borne] See note on II.ii.5. borne it] N.E.D. (Bear v.1 3f): To bear it: to carry off as a prize, to ‘carry’ by assault, carry the day. Obs. Couentry] DELIUS (ed. 1857): The place where the combat was held."
      ]
    },
    "148": {
      "play": "For all the country in a general voice",
      "notes": [
        "voyce] N.E.D. (Voice sb. 3): The expressed opinion, judgement, will, or wish of the people, etc."
      ]
    },
    "149": {
      "play": "Cried hate upon him; and all their prayers and",
      "notes": [
        "Cry’d ... vpon] N.E.D. (Cry v. 17): To invoke or bring by outcry (fame, honor, hate, etc.) on or upon. [Quotes Twelfth Night v.i.53, \"Cried fame and honour on him\".]"
      ]
    },
    "150": {
      "play": "love",
      "notes": [
        "and did] Thirlby’s emendation is almost universally adopted, but perhaps the conjectures recorded in the textual notes testify to some uneasiness about it. Perring (ii N. & Q. ii, 1910, p. 164) defends did, explaining it as=did for. So does Miss Porter (ed. 1911). Furnivall (Old Sp. ed., 1909) adopts Delius’s bid, which he takes to mean “prayd for”."
      ]
    },
    "151": {
      "play": "Were set on Hereford, whom they doted on",
      "notes": []
    },
    "152": {
      "play": "And blessed and graced, indeed more than the",
      "notes": []
    },
    "153": {
      "play": "King.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "154": {
      "play": "But this is mere digression from my purpose.",
      "notes": [
        "meere] Schmidt (1875): Only; simply that which is designated, and nothing else."
      ]
    },
    "155": {
      "play": "Here come I from our princely general",
      "notes": []
    },
    "156": {
      "play": "To know your griefs, to tell you from his Grace",
      "notes": []
    },
    "157": {
      "play": "That he will give you audience; and wherein",
      "notes": []
    },
    "158": {
      "play": "It shall appear that your demands are just,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "159": {
      "play": "You shall enjoy them, everything set off",
      "notes": [
        "euery thing set off] Clarke (ed. 1865): This phrase is so ambiguous in expression, that it is capable of several interpretations; and therein precisely serves the purpose of the speaker. It may mean ‘everything set apart, cast out, thrown forth, acquitted, excluded, or excepted;’ or may mean ‘everything counterbalanced, rendered account for, or yielded retribution for.’ [Though quoted by various editors, probably a supersubtle interpretation; N.E.D. does not support the sense “rendered account for”. This line is the only example which it quotes of the sense “take away, remove” (Set v. 147a).—Ed.]"
      ]
    },
    "160": {
      "play": "That might so much as think you enemies.",
      "notes": [
        "thinke] N.E.D. (Think v. 10): With complement (with or more often without inf.): To believe, consider, or suppose (to be ...); to look upon as. [Quotes Tempest iv.i.120, “May I be bold To think these spirits?”]"
      ]
    },
    "161": {
      "play": "MOWBRAY: But he hath forced us to compel this offer,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "162": {
      "play": "And it proceeds from policy, not love.",
      "notes": [
        "Policy] N.E.D. (Policy sb.1 4): Sagacity, shrewdness, artfulness; in bad sense, cunning, craftiness, dissimulation."
      ]
    },
    "163": {
      "play": "WESTMORELAND: Mowbray, you overween to take it so.",
      "notes": [
        "ouer-weene] N.E.D. (Overween v. 1): To be conceited, arrogant, presumptuous, or too self-confident [quoting this line]."
      ]
    },
    "164": {
      "play": "This offer comes from mercy, not from fear.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "165": {
      "play": "For, lo, within a ken our army lies,",
      "notes": [
        "Ken] N.E.D. (Ken sb.1 1): = Kenning vb. sb.1 4b [i.e. “The distance that bounds the range of ordinary vision, esp. at sea; hence, a marine measure of about 20 or 21 miles”]. Obs."
      ]
    },
    "166": {
      "play": "Upon mine honor, all too confident",
      "notes": []
    },
    "167": {
      "play": "To give admittance to a thought of fear.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "168": {
      "play": "Our battle is more full of names than yours,",
      "notes": [
        "Battailes] See note on III.ii.161-2. Names] DELIUS (ed. 1857): Men whose names have a great reputation [for valor].",
        "Battailels] See note on III.ii.161–2."
      ]
    },
    "169": {
      "play": "Our men more perfect in the use of arms,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "170": {
      "play": "Our armor all as strong, our cause the best.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "171": {
      "play": "Then reason will our hearts should be as good.",
      "notes": [
        "Reason will] N.E.D. (Reason sb.1 12a): In verbal phrases denoting the conformity of something to the dictates of reason: Reason will or would. Obs. [Quotes this line as its last example.]"
      ]
    },
    "172": {
      "play": "Say you not then our offer is compelled.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "173": {
      "play": "MOWBRAY: Well, by my will, we shall admit no parley.",
      "notes": [
        "by my will] ONIONS (1911): With my consent."
      ]
    },
    "174": {
      "play": "WESTMORELAND: That argues but the shame of your offense.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "175": {
      "play": "A rotten case abides no handling.",
      "notes": [
        "] Proverbial; see JENTE (1926), No. 50. rotten] N.E.D. (Rotten a. 8): Weak, unsound [quoting as its earliest example Coriolanus i.x.231]. handling] CAPELL (Notes, 1779, ii. 228) first noted that the word is a trisyllable. See ABBOTT (1870) §477."
      ]
    },
    "176": {
      "play": "HASTINGS: Hath the Prince John a full commission,",
      "notes": [
        "Commission] Four syllables.",
        "Hast.] Q Prince is certainly wrong according to ll. 100–6, but how Prince came to stand in place of Hast. or how Hast. came to be read as Prince I am at a loss to explain.—Ed."
      ]
    },
    "177": {
      "play": "In very ample virtue of his father,",
      "notes": [
        "In ... vertue of] ONIONS (1911): By the full authority of. 173-4. determine Of] N.E.D. (Determine v. 5): To give a decision; to decide. Const. of (on) [obs.].—COWL (ed. 1923): “Hear” and “determine” are technical terms in legal procedure."
      ]
    },
    "178": {
      "play": "To hear and absolutely to determine",
      "notes": [
        "] On this characteristic Tudor doctrine, see HART, Sh. and the Homilies (1934). Substitute] ONIONS (1911): Deputy.—[Cf. I.iii.89, IV.iv.8.]"
      ]
    },
    "179": {
      "play": "Of what conditions we shall stand upon?",
      "notes": [
        "Conditions ... vpon] N.E.D. (Stand v. 78f): To stand upon conditions, to insist upon conditions."
      ]
    },
    "180": {
      "play": "WESTMORELAND: That is intended in the General’s name.",
      "notes": [
        "intended] N.E.D. (Intend v. 20b): Of words, etc.: To mean, to signify; to indicate. Obs. [Rather than implied, as the editors explain.]"
      ]
    },
    "181": {
      "play": "I muse you make so slight a question.",
      "notes": [
        "muse] SCHMIDT (1875): Wonder. make ... Question] N.E.D. (Question sb. 1): To make question, to raise discussion or talk, to express or entertain doubt. Obs."
      ]
    },
    "182": {
      "play": "ARCHBISHOP, giving Westmoreland a paper",
      "notes": []
    },
    "183": {
      "play": "Then take, my Lord of Westmoreland, this schedule,",
      "notes": [
        "Schedule] SCHMIDT (1875): A piece of paper written on.—[This word, which is not in Holinshed, who speaks of a scroll (see p. 535), appears in Stow (Annales, 1592, p. 542): “[The archbishop] shewed a Scedule, in which the Articles were contayned, which when the Earle of Westmerland had read, hee with word and countenance praised the Bishops holy and vertuous intent’”. 179–84.] Miss HANSCOM (ed. 1912): The participial clauses are conditional or temporal in effect."
      ]
    },
    "184": {
      "play": "For this contains our general grievances.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "185": {
      "play": "Each several article herein redressed,",
      "notes": [
        "Each seuerall] SCHMIDT (1875): Every single, every particular."
      ]
    },
    "186": {
      "play": "All members of our cause, both here and hence",
      "notes": []
    },
    "187": {
      "play": "That are insinewed to this action,",
      "notes": [
        "] On the rhythm see p. 509. insinewed] SCHMIDT (1874): Joining one’s sinews to those of another,"
      ]
    },
    "188": {
      "play": "Acquitted by a true substantial form",
      "notes": [
        "substantial form] JOHNSON (ed. 1765): A pardon of due form and legal validity.—N.E.D. defines Form sb. 13 as “a formal agreement, settlement, or arrangement between parties”, but gives no example later than 1411."
      ]
    },
    "189": {
      "play": "And present execution of our wills",
      "notes": [
        "present] SCHMIDT (1875): Instant, immediate.—[Cf. iv.iii.76.]"
      ]
    },
    "190": {
      "play": "To us and to our purposes confined,",
      "notes": [
        "] The textual notes will show that this line has displeased many editors and has been frequently emended. I shall omit the various editors’ explanations of their emendations and deal only with the attempts to explain it as it stands.—ED.—HEATH (1765, p. 260): In truth nothing else is meant by that word {purposes} but the proposals contained in the schedule.—MASON (1785, p. 194): What they demand is a speedy execution of their wills, so far as they relate to themselves, and to the grievances which they purposed to redress.—COLLIER (ed. 1842): “The execution of our wills being confined, or restricted, to us and to our purposes”.—FIELD (Sh. Soc.’s Papers iii, 1847, pp. 139-40) construes the line closely with our wills: “we of our free wills (confined to ourselves and our own purposes) will come” &c.—SCHMIDT (1874): Confine, to state with precision, to limit exactly. [N.E.D. does not bear this out.]—LEE (ed. 1908): Limited to, or defined by, our explicit demands.—Miss HANSCOM (ed. 1912): Pertaining to ourselves and our plans.—LOBBAN (ed. 1915): Which refer only to ourselves and our proposals.—COWL (ed. 1923): Such redress to be confined to ourselves and not to exceed our actual demands. The Archbishop with propriety affirms that the redress sought is not intended to go beyond the several articles contained in the schedule. to] The meter, if nothing else, makes it certain that this word was omitted from Q by accident.—ED."
      ]
    },
    "191": {
      "play": "We come within our awful banks again",
      "notes": [
        "] The metaphor implies a stream that has overflowed its banks. Awful, however, has puzzled many.—JOHNSON (ed. 1765): Awful banks are the proper"
      ]
    },
    "192": {
      "play": "And knit our powers to the arm of peace.",
      "notes": [
        "] The very characteristic metaphor of knitting, used by Sh. to express a variety of close relationships, is not worked out very clearly here, but perhaps arm was suggested to his mind by the word powers and so he plays with two meanings of the former.—ED. Powers] See note on I.i.206.",
        "] The very characteristic metaphor of knitting, used by Sh. to express a variety of close relationships, is not worked out very clearly here, but perhaps arm was suggested to his mind by the word powers and so he plays with two meanings of the former.—Ed. Powers] See note on I.i.206."
      ]
    },
    "193": {
      "play": "WESTMORELAND: This will I show the General. Please you, lords,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "194": {
      "play": "In sight of both our battles we may meet,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "195": {
      "play": "And either end in peace, which God so frame,",
      "notes": [
        "At] See p. 509. frame] N.E.D. (Frame v. 8d): To cause, produce, bring to pass. Obs. [Quotes this line.] 193–4.] Ax (1912, p. 76): Mowbray’s warning words in the drama … evidently are founded on the passage: “the archbishop … gaue credit to the earle, and persuaded the earle marshall (against his will as it were) to go with him to a place appointed” (Holinshed iii. 530 [p. 535 below]).—Miss WINSTANLEY (ed. 1918) notes that Sh. often gives premonitions to men about to die, and indeed Mowbray’s misgivings make his ultimate fate ironical."
      ]
    },
    "196": {
      "play": "Or to the place of difference call the swords",
      "notes": []
    },
    "197": {
      "play": "Which must decide it.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "198": {
      "play": "ARCHBISHOP: My lord, we will do so.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "199": {
      "play": "[Westmoreland exits.]",
      "notes": []
    },
    "200": {
      "play": "MOWBRAY: There is a thing within my bosom tells me",
      "notes": [
        "a thing] N.E.D. (Thing sb.1 6): a thing, in indefinite sense: =anything, something.—[Cf. II.ii.34. See ABBOTT (1870) §81.] tells] Which tells. See note on II.iv.68–9."
      ]
    },
    "201": {
      "play": "That no conditions of our peace can stand.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "202": {
      "play": "HASTINGS: Fear you not that. If we can make our peace",
      "notes": [
        "not, that] See p. 509."
      ]
    },
    "203": {
      "play": "Upon such large terms and so absolute",
      "notes": []
    },
    "204": {
      "play": "As our conditions shall consist upon,",
      "notes": [
        "consist upon] N.E.D. (Consist v. 4c): Consist on or upon. To stand or insist upon, on. Obs. [Quotes this line and Pericles I.iv.83 only.]"
      ]
    },
    "205": {
      "play": "Our peace shall stand as firm as rocky mountains.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "206": {
      "play": "MOWBRAY: Yea, but our valuation shall be such",
      "notes": [
        "valuation] ROLFE (ed. 1880): The king’s estimate or opinion of us. See ABBOTT (1870) §219."
      ]
    },
    "207": {
      "play": "That every slight and false-derivèd cause,",
      "notes": [
        "false-derived] COWL (ed. 1923): Resting upon false grounds."
      ]
    },
    "208": {
      "play": "Yea, every idle, nice, and wanton reason,",
      "notes": [
        "nice] SCHMIDT (1875): Petty, insignificant, trifling. wanton] ONIONS (1911): Capricious, frivolous."
      ]
    },
    "209": {
      "play": "Shall to the King taste of this action,",
      "notes": [
        "Action] ROLFE (ed. 1880): A trisyllable.—[See note on I.ii.194.]"
      ]
    },
    "210": {
      "play": "That, were our royal faiths martyrs in love,",
      "notes": [
        "That] So that. See note on I.i.198. were ... Loue] Miss WINSTANLEY (ed. 1918): Even if we were faithful to the king to the point of martyrdom. Royal faiths] CAPELL (Notes, 1779, p. 178): “Royal faith” is—the faith, i.e. faithfulness, shew’d to royalty.—MALONE (apud Steevens, ed. 1793): So, in Henry VIII [iv.i.8]: “The citizens ... have shown at full their royal minds;” i.e. their minds well affected to the king. Wolsey, ... when he discovers the king in masquerade, says, “here I’ll make My royal choice” [I.iv.86], i.e. not such a choice as a king would make, but such a choice as has a king for its object. So royal faith, the faith which is due to a king; which has the sovereign for its object.—N.E.D.: In a number of Shaksperian passages the adj. [royal] has a purely contextual meaning, the precise force of which is not always clear.—[See note on II.iii.28.]"
      ]
    },
    "211": {
      "play": "We shall be winnowed with so rough a wind",
      "notes": [
        "] NOBLE (1935, p. 179): For the figure of being winnowed cf. Luke xxii. 31: “Satan hath desired you, to winow you, as wheate” (Genevan version). The winnowing of the disciples may have been in mind.—Cf. Edward III I.i.96–7: “From whence wele shake him with so rough a storme, As others shalbe warned by his harme”. shall be] On the tense see note on I.iii.84."
      ]
    },
    "212": {
      "play": "That even our corn shall seem as light as chaff,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "213": {
      "play": "And good from bad find no partition.",
      "notes": [
        "partition] SCHMIDT (1875): Distinction."
      ]
    },
    "214": {
      "play": "ARCHBISHOP: No, no, my lord. Note this: the King is weary",
      "notes": []
    },
    "215": {
      "play": "Of dainty and such picking grievances,",
      "notes": [
        "daintie] N.E.D. (Dainty sb. 4): Daintiness; fastidiousness [quoting this line and Faery Queen I.ii.27, “so dainty they say maketh derth”].—[The editors uniformly take dainty as an adjective = fastidious, coordinate with picking and likewise modified by such.—Ed.] picking] N.E.D. (Picking ppl.a. 2): Dainty; fastidious; trifling, nice. Obs. [Quotes this line.]"
      ]
    },
    "216": {
      "play": "For he hath found to end one doubt by death",
      "notes": [
        "doubt] N.E.D. (Doubt sb.1 3b): A thing to be dreaded; danger, risk. Obs."
      ]
    },
    "217": {
      "play": "Revives two greater in the heirs of life;",
      "notes": [
        "Heires of Life] Those who survive."
      ]
    },
    "218": {
      "play": "And therefore will he wipe his tables clean",
      "notes": [
        "wipe ... cleane] See note on II.iv.269-70. Cf. the current metaphor “to wipe the slate clean”."
      ]
    },
    "219": {
      "play": "And keep no telltale to his memory",
      "notes": []
    },
    "220": {
      "play": "That may repeat and history his loss",
      "notes": [
        "Historie] SCHMIDT (1874): Record.—ROLFE (ed. 1880): The only instance of the verb in Sh. losse] This, I suppose, refers to the hypothetical concessions that the king is to make.—Ed."
      ]
    },
    "221": {
      "play": "To new remembrance. For full well he knows",
      "notes": []
    },
    "222": {
      "play": "He cannot so precisely weed this land",
      "notes": [
        "precisely] N.E.D. (Precisely adv. 1): Definitely; entirely, absolutely. Obs."
      ]
    },
    "223": {
      "play": "As his misdoubts present occasion;",
      "notes": [
        "mis-doubts] SCHMIDT (1875): Suspicion[s], apprehension[s]. 217-9.] WORDSWORTH (1864, p. 330): [The] parable of the wheat and the tares, Matt. xiii. 29 [“Nay: lest whyle ye geather vp the tares, ye roote vp also the wheate with them”], appears to have suggested to our poet the metaphorical language which he uses.",
        "doubt] N.E.D. (Doubt v. 6b): To suspect. arch."
      ]
    },
    "224": {
      "play": "His foes are so enrooted with his friends",
      "notes": [
        "en-rooted] N.E.D. (Enroot v. 2): To entangle root with root [quoting this line as its only example]."
      ]
    },
    "225": {
      "play": "That, plucking to unfix an enemy,",
      "notes": [
        "plucking] N.E.D. (Pluck v. 4b): To pull sharply or forcibly, to tug (at something); to snatch at [quoting this line]."
      ]
    },
    "226": {
      "play": "He doth unfasten so and shake a friend;",
      "notes": []
    },
    "227": {
      "play": "So that this land, like an offensive wife",
      "notes": []
    },
    "228": {
      "play": "That hath enraged him on to offer strokes,",
      "notes": [
        "so] DEIGHTON (ed. 1893): In this way, by this action. 220-4.] MURRY (1936, p. 32): When I read [these lines] I personally am persuaded that Shakespeare did not observe that happening as a detached third-party. He was involved in it. There is something in the image which betrays intimate experience.—See Miss SPURGEON (1935, pp. 138 f.) on “Shakespeare's intimate knowledge of mother and babe”—COWL (ed. 1923): Simile and metaphor are curiously interwoven in these lines.—COLLINS (ed. 1927): The simile is continued in the main sentence (lines 222-4), and as a metaphor, in the usual Shakespearean style; in this case the confusion between metaphor and simile extends to the simile itself, in [l. 221].",
        "enrag'd ... on] N.E.D. (Enrage v. 5): To throw into a rage; to make furious, exasperate; also with on, and absol. [quoting this line]. him] CLARKE (ed. 1865): The husband who is implied in the word \"wife,\" and the king who was mentioned at the beginning of the speech. offer] N.E.D. (Offer v. 5): To make an attempt to inflict, deal, or bring to bear (violence, or injury of any kind); to put forth one's effort to make (attack) [quoting this line].—[Cf. l. 229 below.]"
      ]
    },
    "229": {
      "play": "As he is striking holds his infant up",
      "notes": []
    },
    "230": {
      "play": "And hangs resolved correction in the arm",
      "notes": [
        "hangs] SCHMIDT (1874): Hang, to make hover and impend, and hence to make linger.—ROLFE (ed. 1880) quotes Troilus IV.v.188, “When thou hast hung thy advanced sword i' the air”. resolu'd] N.E.D. (Resolved ppl.a. 3b): Of actions, states of mind, etc.: Fully determined upon, deliberate."
      ]
    },
    "231": {
      "play": "That was upreared to execution.",
      "notes": [
        "execution] Five syllables."
      ]
    },
    "232": {
      "play": "HASTINGS: Besides, the King hath wasted all his rods",
      "notes": [
        "wasted] SCHMIDT (1875): Waste, to consume, to spend. Rods] NOBLE (1935, p. 179): Reminiscent of Ps. lxxxix. 32: \"I wyl visite their offenses with the rodde\"."
      ]
    },
    "233": {
      "play": "On late offenders, that he now doth lack",
      "notes": []
    },
    "234": {
      "play": "The very instruments of chastisement,",
      "notes": [
        "] BUCKNILL (1860, p. 154) says this is a “surgical fact”. for] Because of, in consequence of. See ABBOTT (1870) §150; FRANZ (3 ed., 1924) §479."
      ]
    },
    "235": {
      "play": "So that his power, like to a fangless lion,",
      "notes": [
        "that] So that. See note on i.i.198.",
        "like to] Like. See FRANZ (3 ed., 1924) §532.",
        "] The mislineation in Q which attaches this to the next line is probably no more than a compositor’s error. See note on l. iii.—ED."
      ]
    },
    "236": {
      "play": "May offer but not hold.",
      "notes": [
        "offer] See note on l. 221 above. hold] SCHMIDT (1874): To keep or take a thing in one’s grasp.—DEIGHTON (ed. 1893): Be able to keep its hold.—COWL (ed. 1923) Hold out in its purpose. ... Cf. Job xli. 26: “The sword of him that layeth at him cannot hold” [Authorized version]."
      ]
    },
    "237": {
      "play": "ARCHBISHOP: ’Tis very true,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "238": {
      "play": "And therefore be assured, my good Lord Marshal,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "239": {
      "play": "If we do now make our atonement well,",
      "notes": [
        "attonement] N.E.D. (Atonement 2a): Reconciliation. Obs."
      ]
    },
    "240": {
      "play": "Our peace will, like a broken limb united,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "241": {
      "play": "Grow stronger for the breaking.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "242": {
      "play": "MOWBRAY: Be it so.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "243": {
      "play": "Here is returned my Lord of Westmoreland.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "244": {
      "play": "[Enter Westmoreland.]",
      "notes": []
    },
    "245": {
      "play": "WESTMORELAND, to the Archbishop",
      "notes": []
    },
    "246": {
      "play": "The Prince is here at hand. Pleaseth your Lordship",
      "notes": [
        "pleaseth] N.E.D. (Please v. 3) describes this as a corrupt form of please it you (see note on I.i.9); SCHMIDT (1875) and ABBOTT (1870, §361), apparently erroneously, take it as the indicative for the subjunctive. Cf. IV.ii.56.",
        "Pleaseth] See note on iv.i.238."
      ]
    },
    "247": {
      "play": "To meet his Grace just distance ’tween our armies.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "248": {
      "play": "[Enter Prince John and his army.]",
      "notes": []
    },
    "249": {
      "play": "MOWBRAY, to the Archbishop",
      "notes": []
    },
    "250": {
      "play": "Your Grace of York, in God’s name then set",
      "notes": []
    },
    "251": {
      "play": "forward.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "252": {
      "play": "ARCHBISHOP: Before, and greet his Grace.—My lord, we come.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "253": {
      "play": "All move forward.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "254": {
      "play": "JOHN OF LANCASTER: You are well encountered here, my cousin",
      "notes": [
        "wel encountered] Well met, a conventional greeting, as in Love’s Labour’s Lost v.i.31, Cymbeline iii.vi.65. cosin] SCHMIDT (1874): A title given by princes to other princes and noblemen.—[Cf. II. 85, 90, 109 below, iv.iii.27, 82, vii.28, 29.]"
      ]
    },
    "255": {
      "play": "Mowbray.—",
      "notes": []
    },
    "256": {
      "play": "Good day to you, gentle Lord Archbishop,—",
      "notes": [
        "gentle ... Archbishop] See note on I.i.205."
      ]
    },
    "257": {
      "play": "And so to you, Lord Hastings, and to all.—",
      "notes": []
    },
    "258": {
      "play": "My Lord of York, it better showed with you",
      "notes": [
        "shew’d] See note on II.ii.8."
      ]
    },
    "259": {
      "play": "When that your flock, assembled by the bell,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "260": {
      "play": "Encircled you to hear with reverence",
      "notes": []
    },
    "261": {
      "play": "Your exposition on the holy text",
      "notes": []
    },
    "262": {
      "play": "Than now to see you here, an iron man talking,",
      "notes": [
        "Iron man] STEEVENS (Var. ’78): Holinshed says of the archbishop, that “comming foorth amongst them clad in armor, [he] incouraged, exhorted, and (by all meanes he could) pricked them foorth to take the enterprise in hand” [iii. 529; p. 535 below].—RIDLEY (ed. 1934): F not unnaturally omits talking [see textual notes], which is both weak and hypermetric. But it must represent something in the copy (? an alternative for cheering)."
      ]
    },
    "263": {
      "play": "Cheering a rout of rebels with your drum,",
      "notes": [
        "rowt] See note on iv.i.42."
      ]
    },
    "264": {
      "play": "Turning the word to sword, and life to death.",
      "notes": [
        "the Word, to Sword] SCHMIDT (1875): Word, the Scripture, or any part"
      ]
    },
    "265": {
      "play": "That man that sits within a monarch’s heart",
      "notes": []
    },
    "266": {
      "play": "And ripens in the sunshine of his favor,",
      "notes": [
        "] An alexandrine? shadow] ONIONS (1911): Shelter, protection. [With an allusion to Sunne-shine (l. 13).—ED.]—[On the omission of the article, see FRANZ (3 ed., 1924) §267.]"
      ]
    },
    "267": {
      "play": "Would he abuse the countenance of the King,",
      "notes": [
        "Countenance] N.E.D. (Countenance sb. 8): ‘Patronage; appearance of favour’; moral support.—[Cf. l. 25 below, v.i.50.]"
      ]
    },
    "268": {
      "play": "Alack, what mischiefs might he set abroach",
      "notes": [
        "set abroach] N.E.D. (Abroach adv.); prop. phrase. To set abroach: to broach, to set a-foot, to publish or diffuse."
      ]
    },
    "269": {
      "play": "In shadow of such greatness! With you, Lord",
      "notes": []
    },
    "270": {
      "play": "Bishop,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "271": {
      "play": "It is even so. Who hath not heard it spoken",
      "notes": []
    },
    "272": {
      "play": "How deep you were within the books of God,",
      "notes": [
        "] DELIUS (ed. 1857): How deeply you had penetrated into the understanding of the Bible.—SCHMIDT (1874): Deep, proficient, versed.—ONIONS (1911): Deep: Profound in knowledge, learning, or insight.—TIESSEN (E.S. ii, 1879, p. 447): How well you were reputed by God. Cf. Much Ado [i.i.64]: “I see, lady, the gentleman is not in your books”.—COWL (ed. 1923): [How deep you were] in the good graces [of God].—[Tiessen and Cowl are right, I think. If so, deep means simply far, utterly. Cf. II.ii.45.—ED.]"
      ]
    },
    "273": {
      "play": "To us the speaker in His parliament,",
      "notes": [
        "Speaker] White (ed. 1859) quotes Sir Thomas Smith’s De Republica Anglorum II. ii (ed. Alston, 1906, p. 51): “In this meane time the knights of the shires and burgesses of the parliament … are called by such as it pleaseth the prince to appoint, into an other great house or chamber by name, to which they answere …: then they are willed to choose an able and discrete man to be as it were the mouth of them all, and to speake for and in the name of them,” i.e. to the prince and the lords.—C. Clark (Sh. and the Supernatural, 1931, p. 257): The Church is recognized as the channel of communication between God and man."
      ]
    },
    "274": {
      "play": "To us th’ imagined voice of God Himself,",
      "notes": [
        "imagine] Malone (Suppl., 1780): An apparent error of the press.—[See p. 509.]"
      ]
    },
    "275": {
      "play": "The very opener and intelligencer",
      "notes": [
        "Opener] Schmidt (1875): One who reveals. [So also Onions (1911), Cowl (ed. 1923). Some editors gloss as explainer, interpreter.] Intelligencer] Schmidt (1874): Agent, mediator.—N.E.D. (Intelligencer b): A bringer of news; messenger [quoting no example before 1632]."
      ]
    },
    "276": {
      "play": "Between the grace, the sanctities, of heaven,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "277": {
      "play": "And our dull workings? O, who shall believe",
      "notes": []
    },
    "278": {
      "play": "But you misuse the reverence of your place,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "279": {
      "play": "Employ the countenance and grace of heaven",
      "notes": [
        "Grace] Schmidt (1874): Divine favour. Sanctities] N.E.D. (Sanctity 1b): Holiness of life, saintliness. pl. [quoting this line as its only example before 1820].—Thaler (1929, p. 178) suggests that the word may be used concretely as in Paradise Lost iii. 60, “About him all the Sanctities of Heaven Stood thick as Starrs”.",
        "Countenance, and Grace] Schulze (1908, p. 17): Gracious countenance [hendiadys]."
      ]
    },
    "280": {
      "play": "As a false favorite doth his prince’s name,",
      "notes": [
        "workings] Steevens (ed. 1793): I.e. labours of thought.—Schmidt (1874): Affections.—Onions (1911): Effort[s], endeavour[s] [disputed].—N.E.D. (Working vbl.sb. 5d): Action, operation. Of the mind, conscience, etc. Often pl. [Quotes 1 Henry VI v.v. 86, “I am sick with working of my thoughts”; Hamlet II.ii.547, “That from her [the soul’s] working all his visage wann’d”; Sonnet xciii, “Whate’er thy thoughts or thy heart’s workings be”.]"
      ]
    },
    "281": {
      "play": "In deeds dishonorable? You have ta’en up,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "282": {
      "play": "Under the counterfeited zeal of God,",
      "notes": [
        "Zeale of Heauen] CLARKE (ed. 1865): Devotion to God's cause.—HERFORD (ed. 1899): Perhaps with a play on ‘seal.’—ONIONS (1911): Construed with of (instead of the usual to).—NOBLE (1935, p. 179) quotes Romans x. 2, “they haue a zeale of God”."
      ]
    },
    "283": {
      "play": "The subjects of His substitute, my father,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "284": {
      "play": "And both against the peace of heaven and him",
      "notes": [
        "the Peace ... him] COWL (ed. 1923) quotes Sir Thomas Smith's De Republica Anglorum III. iii [ed. Alston, 1906, p. 113]: “The Prince ... must see justice executed against all malefactors and offenders against the peace, which is called Gods and his”. Cf. III.45-6."
      ]
    },
    "285": {
      "play": "Have here up-swarmed them.",
      "notes": [
        "vp-swarmed] SCHMIDT (1875): Raise[d] in swarms.—[N.E.D. quotes no other example.] 35-44.] HART (1934, p. 64): The homilist comments caustically on the catch-word, ‘reformation,’ so popular in his day. “Surely that which they falsely call reformation is indeed not only a defacing or a deformation, but also an utter destruction of all Common-wealth, as would well appear, might the Rebels have their wills; and doth right well, and too well, appear by their doing in such places of the Country where Rebels do rout, where though they tarry but a very little while, they make such reformation, that they destroy"
      ]
    },
    "286": {
      "play": "ARCHBISHOP: Good my Lord of",
      "notes": []
    },
    "287": {
      "play": "Lancaster,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "288": {
      "play": "I am not here against your father’s peace,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "289": {
      "play": "But, as I told my Lord of Westmoreland,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "290": {
      "play": "The time misordered doth, in common sense,",
      "notes": [
        "mis-order'd] N.E.D. (Misorder v.1): Obs. To confuse, disturb [quoting this line].—ROLFE (ed. 1880): Used by Sh. nowhere else. common sense] HEATH (1765, p. 260): The feeling we have of the common and national grievances.—JOHNSON (ed. 1765): The general sense of general danger.—MASON (Var. '03): The dictates of reason.—DELlUS (ed. 1857): Naturally.—HUDSON (ed. 1880): The feeling, which we all have in common, of the public grievances.—N.E.D. (Common sense 3): The general sense, feeling, or judgement of mankind, or of a community.—HERFORD (ed. 1899): Mere ordinary perception and understanding. York urges that his extraordinary action (in leading a revolt) springs from the normal instinct of self-defence.—ONIONS (1911): Ordinary or untutored perception [N.E.D., Common sense 2c]."
      ]
    },
    "291": {
      "play": "Crowd us and crush us to this monstrous form",
      "notes": [
        "Crowd] N.E.D. (Crowd v.1 6d): To compress, crush. Also fig. Obs. [Quotes this line as its earliest example.] monstrous] N.E.D. (Monstrous a. 1b): Of persons: Strange and unnatural in conduct or disposition. Obs."
      ]
    },
    "292": {
      "play": "To hold our safety up. I sent your Grace",
      "notes": []
    },
    "293": {
      "play": "The parcels and particulars of our grief,",
      "notes": [
        "parcels] N.E.D. (Parcel sb. 3): An item, detail, particular, point; esp. an item of an account. Obs. Grief] See note on iv.i.78."
      ]
    },
    "294": {
      "play": "The which hath been with scorn shoved from the",
      "notes": [
        "hath] See note on iv.i.93 and FRANZ (3 ed., 1924) §673."
      ]
    },
    "295": {
      "play": "court,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "296": {
      "play": "Whereon this Hydra son of war is born,",
      "notes": [
        "] HERFORD (ed. 1928): It was the rejection of the claim for redress of grievances that gave birth to this armed rising; as the Hydra heads only multiplied by being cut off. this Hydra-Sonne of Warre] SCHMIDT (1874): War, this son of Hydra.—ONIONS (1911): Hydra: Used attrib. = difficult to kill like the many-headed snake of Lerna, whose heads grew as fast as they were cut off.—ROOT (1903, p. 72): The Hydra is described in [Ovid's] Met[amorphoses] ix. 70 seq."
      ]
    },
    "297": {
      "play": "Whose dangerous eyes may well be charmed asleep",
      "notes": [
        "] STEEVENS (ed. 1793): Alluding to the dragon charmed to rest by the spells of Medea.—ROOT (1903, p. 40): By a strange confusion with the Hydra, the charming asleep of Argus' eyes [by Mercury's music, Metamorphoses i. 622 ff.] is mentioned in connection with Hydra."
      ]
    },
    "298": {
      "play": "With grant of our most just and right desires,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "299": {
      "play": "And true obedience, of this madness cured,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "300": {
      "play": "Stoop tamely to the foot of majesty.",
      "notes": [
        "Stoope] N.E.D. (Stoop v.¹ 2a): To 'bow' to superior power or authority; to yield obedience. Now somewhat rare."
      ]
    },
    "301": {
      "play": "MOWBRAY: If not, we ready are to try our fortunes",
      "notes": []
    },
    "302": {
      "play": "To the last man.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "303": {
      "play": "HASTINGS: And though we here fall down,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "304": {
      "play": "We have supplies to second our attempt;",
      "notes": [
        "Supplyes] See note on I.iii.15. second] N.E.D. (Second v.¹ 2c): To take the place of, succeed (a combatant who is hors de combat). Obs. [Quotes this line.]"
      ]
    },
    "305": {
      "play": "If they miscarry, theirs shall second them,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "306": {
      "play": "And so success of mischief shall be born,",
      "notes": [
        "successe] HANMER (ed. 1743): Succession. Mischief] N.E.D. (Mischief sb. 1): Misfortune; trouble, distress. Obs."
      ]
    },
    "307": {
      "play": "And heir from heir shall hold his quarrel up",
      "notes": [
        "hold ... vp] N.E.D. (Hold v. 44b): Hold up. fig. To support, sustain, maintain, keep up. this] Q his makes a kind of sense, but F this is so much better that it is reasonably safe to assume that t was omitted from Q by accident.—ED."
      ]
    },
    "308": {
      "play": "Whiles England shall have generation.",
      "notes": [
        "Whiles] See note on Ind. 16. generation] N.E.D. (Generation 3): Offspring, progeny. Obs.—[Five syllables.] 53–5.] CLEMEN (1936, pp. 92 f.): The images are formed, as it were, while Sh. is in the act of writing them; one word begets the other, one imaginative expression awakens a related image. ... Shallow, i.e. stupid, superficial in character, here recalls to Sh. its typical concrete meaning and so calls up the unexpressed picture of the deep sea, whose bottom Hastings cannot sound. 56–7.] CAPELL (Notes, 1779, p. 179): [Westmoreland] puts him upon an in-"
      ]
    },
    "309": {
      "play": "JOHN OF LANCASTER: You are too shallow, Hastings, much too shallow",
      "notes": []
    },
    "310": {
      "play": "To sound the bottom of the after-times.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "311": {
      "play": "WESTMORELAND: Pleaseth your Grace to answer them directly",
      "notes": []
    },
    "312": {
      "play": "How far forth you do like their articles.",
      "notes": [
        "farre-forth] SCHMIDT (1874). [Forth is used] redundantly after far.—[See FRANZ (3 ed., 1924) §429.] 58–69.] STEEVENS (Var. ’78): It was Westmoreland who made this deceitful proposal, as appears from Holinshed: “The earle of Westmerland vsing more policie than the rest: Well (said he) then our trauell is come to the wished end: and where our people haue beene long in armour, let them depart home to their woonted trades and occupations: in the meane time let vs drinke togither in signe of agreement, that the people on both sides maie see it, and know that it is true, that we be light at a point” [iii. 530; p. 536 below]."
      ]
    },
    "313": {
      "play": "JOHN OF LANCASTER: I like them all, and do allow them well,",
      "notes": [
        "allow] MALONE (ed. 1790): Approve."
      ]
    },
    "314": {
      "play": "And swear here by the honor of my blood",
      "notes": []
    },
    "315": {
      "play": "My father’s purposes have been mistook,",
      "notes": [
        "mistooke] See note on i.i.147."
      ]
    },
    "316": {
      "play": "And some about him have too lavishly",
      "notes": [
        "about] See note on iii.ii.235. lauishly] SCHMIDT (1874): Licentiously, arbitrarily.—ONIONS (1911): Wildly.—Miss WINSTANLEY (ed. 1918): Loosely or carelessly.—COWL (ed. 1923): With too great a latitude."
      ]
    },
    "317": {
      "play": "Wrested his meaning and authority.",
      "notes": [
        "Wrested] N.E.D. (Wrest v. 5): To strain or overstrain the meaning or bearing of (a writing, passage, word, etc.); to deflect or turn from the true or proper signification."
      ]
    },
    "318": {
      "play": "To the Archbishop. My lord, these griefs shall be",
      "notes": [
        "Griefes] See note on iv.i.78.",
        "Grievances] See textual notes.—ABBOTT (1870, §471): The plural ... of nouns in which the singular ends in ce [&c. is] frequently written, and still more frequently pronounced, without the additional syllable."
      ]
    },
    "319": {
      "play": "with speed redressed;",
      "notes": []
    },
    "320": {
      "play": "Upon my soul, they shall. If this may please you,",
      "notes": [
        "Vpon my Life] See note on iii.i.104."
      ]
    },
    "321": {
      "play": "Discharge your powers unto their several counties,",
      "notes": [
        "Powers] See note on i.i.206. 70–91.] Frl. ECKLEBEN (1912, p. 14) points out the unconscious irony in this episode. Westmoreland, of course, is consciously ironical in ll. 79–82."
      ]
    },
    "322": {
      "play": "As we will ours, and here, between the armies,",
      "notes": [
        "ye] See note on I.ii.197."
      ]
    },
    "323": {
      "play": "Let’s drink together friendly and embrace,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "324": {
      "play": "That all their eyes may bear those tokens home",
      "notes": []
    },
    "325": {
      "play": "Of our restorèd love and amity.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "326": {
      "play": "ARCHBISHOP: I take your princely word for these redresses.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "327": {
      "play": "JOHN OF LANCASTER: I give it you, and will maintain my word,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "328": {
      "play": "And thereupon I drink unto your Grace.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "329": {
      "play": "The Leaders of both armies begin to drink together.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "330": {
      "play": "HASTINGS, to an Officer",
      "notes": []
    },
    "331": {
      "play": "Go, captain, and deliver to the army",
      "notes": []
    },
    "332": {
      "play": "This news of peace. Let them have pay, and part.",
      "notes": [
        "part] N.E.D. (Part v. 7): To depart, go away. 78–80.] On the lineation see p. 502. 79–80. paines ... breede] Deighton (ed. 1893): A play on pains in the sense of pains of childbirth.",
        "] COLLINS (ed. 1927): There has not been time to carry out Hastings' injunction to pay the men (1. 74); but Shakespeare is careless of such trifles.—[On the difference between Q and F see p. 501.] 115-6.] Miss SPURGEON (1935, p. 140): [Sh.'s] delight in boy nature is evident ... in the many images [he] draws from it."
      ]
    },
    "333": {
      "play": "I know it will well please them. Hie thee, captain.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "334": {
      "play": "[Officer exits.]",
      "notes": []
    },
    "335": {
      "play": "ARCHBISHOP, toasting Westmoreland",
      "notes": []
    },
    "336": {
      "play": "To you, my noble Lord of Westmoreland.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "337": {
      "play": "WESTMORELAND, returning the toast",
      "notes": []
    },
    "338": {
      "play": "I pledge your Grace, and if you knew what pains",
      "notes": []
    },
    "339": {
      "play": "I have bestowed to breed this present peace,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "340": {
      "play": "You would drink freely. But my love to you",
      "notes": []
    },
    "341": {
      "play": "Shall show itself more openly hereafter.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "342": {
      "play": "ARCHBISHOP: I do not doubt you.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "343": {
      "play": "WESTMORELAND: I am glad of it.—",
      "notes": []
    },
    "344": {
      "play": "Health to my lord and gentle cousin, Mowbray.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "345": {
      "play": "MOWBRAY: You wish me health in very happy season,",
      "notes": [
        "happy] N.E.D. (Happy a. 5b): Appropriate, fitting."
      ]
    },
    "346": {
      "play": "For I am on the sudden something ill.",
      "notes": [
        "on the sodaine] N.E.D. (Sudden quasi-sb. and sb. 1b): Suddenly. arch. something] See note on I.iii.171–2. 88–9.] STEEVENS (Var. ’78): Thus the poet describes Romeo, as feeling an unaccustom’d degree of cheerfulness just before he hears the news of the death of Juliet [v.i.1–5].—DYER (1884, pp. 363 f.) cites also Romeo v.iii.88–90, Richard III iii.ii.85–6 &c."
      ]
    },
    "347": {
      "play": "ARCHBISHOP: Against ill chances men are ever merry,",
      "notes": [
        "Against] N.E.D. (Against prep.): esp. with some idea of preparation: In view of; in anticipation of, in preparation for, in time for.—[See FRANZ (3 ed., 1924) §46o.] Chance] N.E.D. (Chance sb. 2): (With pl.) A matter which falls out or happens; a fortuitous event or occurrence; often, an unfortunate event, mishap, mischance."
      ]
    },
    "348": {
      "play": "But heaviness foreruns the good event.",
      "notes": [
        "heuainesse] SCHMIDT (1874): Sorrow, sadness, melancholy.—[Cf. IV.v.10.] 90–1.] Addressed to Mowbray."
      ]
    },
    "349": {
      "play": "WESTMORELAND: Therefore be merry, coz, since sudden sorrow",
      "notes": [
        "sodaine] ONIONS (1911): Happening or performed immediately, immediate, very early."
      ]
    },
    "350": {
      "play": "Serves to say thus: “Some good thing comes",
      "notes": []
    },
    "351": {
      "play": "tomorrow.”",
      "notes": []
    },
    "352": {
      "play": "ARCHBISHOP: Believe me, I am passing light in spirit.",
      "notes": [
        "passing] SCHMIDT (1875): (Used only before adjectives and adverbs) exceedingly. light] N.E.D. (Light a. 21): Free from the weight of care or sorrow; cheerful, merry. Obs. exc. in light heart."
      ]
    },
    "353": {
      "play": "MOWBRAY: So much the worse if your own rule be true.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "354": {
      "play": "Shout within.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "355": {
      "play": "JOHN OF LANCASTER: The word of peace is rendered. Hark how they",
      "notes": []
    },
    "356": {
      "play": "shout.",
      "notes": [
        "render’d] N.E.D. (Render v. 10b): To declare, state. Obs. rare. [Quotes only Cymbeline II.iv.119, V.v.135, “My boon is that this gentleman may render Of whom he had this ring”.]"
      ]
    },
    "357": {
      "play": "MOWBRAY: This had been cheerful after victory.",
      "notes": [
        "had been] See note on II.ii.5."
      ]
    },
    "358": {
      "play": "ARCHBISHOP: A peace is of the nature of a conquest,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "359": {
      "play": "For then both parties nobly are subdued,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "360": {
      "play": "And neither party loser.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "361": {
      "play": "JOHN OF LANCASTER, to Westmoreland  Go, my lord,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "362": {
      "play": "And let our army be dischargèd too.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "363": {
      "play": "[Westmoreland exits.]",
      "notes": []
    },
    "364": {
      "play": "To the Archbishop. And, good my lord, so please",
      "notes": [
        "so please you] See note on 1.i.9. our] Heath (1765, p. 260): This speech is addressed to the archbishop ... It is evident therefore that we should read, your trains.—Johnson (ed. 1765): That is, our army on each part, that we may both see those that were to have opposed us.—Capell (Notes, 1779, p. 179): The true reason of the Prince's request seems to have been,—that he might know as soon as possible the actual state of those “trains,” which, from the shouts he had heard, he imagin'd might be disbanding already; and when certify'd of the truth of his thought by the return of the Archbishop's messenger, his concerted project breaks out.—Malone (ed. 1790): The prince knew his own strength sufficiently, and only wanted to be acquainted with that of the enemy. The plural, trains, however, seems in favour of the old reading.—Steevens (ed. 1793): The Prince was desirous to see their train, and therefore, under pretext of affording them a similar gratification, proposed that both trains should pass in review.—Clarke (ed. 1865): It is just one of those fair-sounding proposals that this perfidious son of tricking Bolingbroke makes; he proposes to let the forces on each side march by, that each party may see those that were to have contended with them, well knowing that no such thing will take place, having evidently had a secret understanding with Westmoreland as to what was to be really done. Traines] N.E.D. (Train sb.1 11): A body of persons, etc., travelling together in order, esp. in a long line or procession."
      ]
    },
    "365": {
      "play": "you, let our trains",
      "notes": []
    },
    "366": {
      "play": "March by us, that we may peruse the men",
      "notes": [
        "peruse] N.E.D. (Peruse v. 2c): To survey, inspect, examine, or consider in detail. arch.—[Cf. Romeo v.iii.74, “Let me peruse this face”.]"
      ]
    },
    "367": {
      "play": "We should have coped withal.",
      "notes": [
        "withall] See note on 1.ii.117."
      ]
    },
    "368": {
      "play": "ARCHBISHOP: Go, good Lord",
      "notes": []
    },
    "369": {
      "play": "Hastings,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "370": {
      "play": "And ere they be dismissed, let them march by.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "371": {
      "play": "[Hastings exits.]",
      "notes": []
    },
    "372": {
      "play": "JOHN OF LANCASTER: I trust, lords, we shall lie tonight together.",
      "notes": [
        "lye] See note on 11. i. 150."
      ]
    },
    "373": {
      "play": "[Enter Westmoreland.]",
      "notes": []
    },
    "374": {
      "play": "Now, cousin, wherefore stands our army still?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "375": {
      "play": "WESTMORELAND: The leaders, having charge from you to stand,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "376": {
      "play": "Will not go off until they hear you speak.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "377": {
      "play": "JOHN OF LANCASTER: They know their duties.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "378": {
      "play": "[Enter Hastings.]",
      "notes": []
    },
    "379": {
      "play": "HASTINGS, to the Archbishop",
      "notes": []
    },
    "380": {
      "play": "My lord, our army is dispersed already.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "381": {
      "play": "Like youthful steers unyoked, they take their",
      "notes": []
    },
    "382": {
      "play": "courses",
      "notes": []
    },
    "383": {
      "play": "East, west, north, south, or, like a school broke up,",
      "notes": [
        "broke] See note on 1. i. 16."
      ]
    },
    "384": {
      "play": "Each hurries toward his home and sporting-place.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "385": {
      "play": "WESTMORELAND: Good tidings, my Lord Hastings, for the which",
      "notes": []
    },
    "386": {
      "play": "I do arrest thee, traitor, of high treason.—",
      "notes": [
        "] Ax (1912, p. 76): The conspirators’ fate which is intimated in this and the following scene is reported more in detail in Holinshed [iii. 530; p. 536 below].—HEATH (1765, p. 261): This whole proceeding, as it is represented by the poet, is founded in strict historical truth, and therefore, in an historical play like this, he is undoubtedly justifiable in giving it us as he found it. It hath however a very unhappy and disagreeable effect on the reader or spectator, as instead of acquiescence, at least in the punishment of the rebels, it cannot fail of exciting in him compassion towards them when so treacherously ensnared, as well as a very high degree of indignation against Prince John, who is on all other occasions represented as a Prince of great gallantry, and magnanimity, for prostituting his character by so deliberate and odious a piece of perfidy. I believe there are few readers who do not wish Shakespear’s plan had permitted him to follow Horace’s rule, ‘et quae Desperat tractata nitescere posse relinquit” [Ars Poetica 150].—JOHNSON (ed. 1765): It cannot but raise some indignation to find this horrible violation of faith passed over thus slightly by the poet, without any note of censure or detestation.—CAPELL (Notes, 1779, p. 179): Blameable as this behaviour will seem at this time of day, no disapprobation is shewn of it by the historians that Shakespeare follow’d, which historians (it should be noted) were his contemporaries; the passive-obedience doctrine running so high with them, that all proceedings with rebels were reckon’d justifiable.—MALONE (ed. 1790): Shakespeare, here, as in many other places, has merely followed the historians who related this perfidious act without animadversion, and who seem to have adopted the ungenerous sentiment of Coreobus [Aeneid ii. 390]: “—dolos an virtus, quis in hoste requirat?” But this is certainly no excuse; for it is the duty of a poet always to take the side of virtue.—KNIGHT (ed. 1839, pp. 301 f.): Shakspeare has contrived to make us hate the act and the actors with an intensity which is the natural result of his dramatic power. ... To our minds, after this dramatic picture, we can well dispense with any didactic explanations.—COURTENAY (1840, p. 134): It was not Shakspeare’s business to make moral reflections, nor was there a person in the drama to whom he could have assigned them; he might, perhaps, have put a more energetic and indignant remonstrance in the mouth of the injured prelate.—VERPLANCK (ed. 1847): Chief-Justice Marshall is said to have observed to a prolix counsel, who had entered upon a demonstration of some familiar elementary doctrine, that “he ought to presume that the court knew something.” Shakespeare always presumes his readers to have the first principles of morals and human feelings in their hearts, and does not enter into declamatory demonstration to show the baseness or guilt of the deeds he represents in his scenes. Here he portrays"
      ]
    },
    "387": {
      "play": "And you, Lord Archbishop, and you, Lord Mowbray,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "388": {
      "play": "Of capital treason I attach you both.",
      "notes": [
        "attach] N.E.D. (Attach v. 1a): Law. To secure for legal jurisdiction and disposal; to arrest or seize. Const. for, of."
      ]
    },
    "389": {
      "play": "MOWBRAY: Is this proceeding just and honorable?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "390": {
      "play": "WESTMORELAND: Is your assembly so?",
      "notes": [
        "Assembly] COWL (ed. 1923): The word is probably used in its legal sense with reference to the offence known as unlawful assembly. [An exposition of certaine ... Termes of the Lawes, 1598, f. 120ᵣ]: “Vnlawfull assemble, is where people assemble themselues together to do some vnlawfull thing against the peace”."
      ]
    },
    "391": {
      "play": "ARCHBISHOP: Will you thus break your faith?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "392": {
      "play": "JOHN OF LANCASTER: I pawned thee none.",
      "notes": [
        "thee] WALKER (Crit. Exam., 1860, iii. 137): Note the transition from you, which runs through the preceding part of the scene, to the opprobrious thou.",
        "pawn’d] SCHMIDT (1875): Pledge[d]."
      ]
    },
    "393": {
      "play": "I promised you redress of these same grievances",
      "notes": []
    },
    "394": {
      "play": "Whereof you did complain, which, by mine honor,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "395": {
      "play": "I will perform with a most Christian care.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "396": {
      "play": "But for you rebels, look to taste the due",
      "notes": [
        "looke to] See note on I.iii.42. taste] ONIONS (1911): Experience, feel."
      ]
    },
    "397": {
      "play": "Meet for rebellion and such acts as yours.",
      "notes": [
        "and ... yours] On the omission of this phrase from Q see p. 495."
      ]
    },
    "398": {
      "play": "Most shallowly did you these arms commence,",
      "notes": [
        "shallowly] ONIONS (1911): Without consideration. Armes] See note on I.iii.8."
      ]
    },
    "399": {
      "play": "Fondly brought here, and foolishly sent hence.—",
      "notes": [
        "Fondly] STEEVENS (Var. ’78): Foolishly. brought] COLLINS (ed. 1927): Agreeing with “armies,” to be understood from arms."
      ]
    },
    "400": {
      "play": "Strike up our drums; pursue the scattered stray.",
      "notes": [
        "stray] SCHMIDT (1875): Collectively, = stragglers.—[N.E.D. quotes no earlier example.]"
      ]
    },
    "401": {
      "play": "God, and not we, hath safely fought today.—",
      "notes": []
    },
    "402": {
      "play": "Some guard these traitors to the block of death,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "403": {
      "play": "Treason’s true bed and yielder-up of breath.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "404": {
      "play": "[They exit.]",
      "notes": []
    }
  },
  "Act 4, SCENE 2": {
    "1": {
      "play": "[Alarum. Excursions. Enter Falstaff and Colevile.]",
      "notes": []
    },
    "2": {
      "play": "FALSTAFF: What’s your name, sir? Of what condition are",
      "notes": [
        "condition] N.E.D. (Condition sb. 10): Social position, estate, rank."
      ]
    },
    "3": {
      "play": "you, and of what place, I pray?",
      "notes": [
        "I pray] On the omission of these words from Q see p. 505."
      ]
    },
    "4": {
      "play": "COLEVILE: I am a knight, sir, and my name is Colevile of",
      "notes": []
    },
    "5": {
      "play": "the Dale.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "6": {
      "play": "FALSTAFF: Well then, Colevile is your name, a knight is",
      "notes": [
        "degree] SCHMIDT (1874): Rank."
      ]
    },
    "7": {
      "play": "your degree, and your place the Dale. Colevile shall",
      "notes": []
    },
    "8": {
      "play": "be still your name, a traitor your degree, and the",
      "notes": []
    },
    "9": {
      "play": "dungeon your place, a place deep enough so shall",
      "notes": [
        "a place] TYRWHITT (1766, p. 42): But where is the wit, or the logic of this"
      ]
    },
    "10": {
      "play": "you be still Colevile of the Dale.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "11": {
      "play": "COLEVILE: Are not you Sir John Falstaff?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "12": {
      "play": "FALSTAFF: As good a man as he, sir, whoe’er I am. Do",
      "notes": [
        "you] See note on I.ii.197."
      ]
    },
    "13": {
      "play": "you yield, sir, or shall I sweat for you? If I do sweat,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "14": {
      "play": "they are the drops of thy lovers and they weep for",
      "notes": [
        "they] The drops I sweat.",
        "drops] N.E.D. (Drop sb. 2): =Tear-drop; also drop of sweat, blood, [&c.] according to context.—[Cf. Caesar vi.48–9, \"if arguing make us sweat, The proof of it will turn to redder drops.\"]",
        "lovers] N.E.D. (Lover1 1): A friend or well-wisher. Now rare."
      ]
    },
    "15": {
      "play": "thy death. Therefore rouse up fear and trembling,",
      "notes": [
        "fear and trembling] Noble (1935, p. 181) quotes Ephesians vi. 5: ‘Servantes obey them that are (your) bodily maisters with feare & trembling”."
      ]
    },
    "16": {
      "play": "and do observance to my mercy.",
      "notes": [
        "observance] N.E.D. (Observance 3): Respectful or courteous attention, dutiful service. arch."
      ]
    },
    "17": {
      "play": "COLEVILE: I think you are Sir John Falstaff, and in that",
      "notes": []
    },
    "18": {
      "play": "thought yield me.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "19": {
      "play": "FALSTAFF: I have a whole school of tongues in this belly",
      "notes": [
        "school] Onions (1911): Fig. large number, ‘crowd.’"
      ]
    },
    "20": {
      "play": "of mine, and not a tongue of them all speaks any",
      "notes": []
    },
    "21": {
      "play": "other word but my name. An I had but a belly of any",
      "notes": []
    },
    "22": {
      "play": "indifferency, I were simply the most active fellow in",
      "notes": [
        "indifferency] Schmidt (1874): Moderate measure."
      ]
    },
    "23": {
      "play": "Europe. My womb, my womb, my womb undoes",
      "notes": [
        "] On the difference between the Q and F stage-directions see pp. 512 ff.",
        "womb] N.E.D. (Womb sb. 1a): The abdomen. Obs. [Quotes this line.]—DELIUS (ed. 1857): Falstaff jokingly calls his paunch his womb because it is as fat as a belly carrying a child.",
        "] On the F stage-direction see pp. 512 ff."
      ]
    },
    "24": {
      "play": "me. Here comes our general.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "25": {
      "play": "[Enter John, Westmoreland, and the rest.]",
      "notes": []
    },
    "26": {
      "play": "JOHN OF LANCASTER: The heat is past. Follow no further now.",
      "notes": [
        "heat] JOHNSON (ed. 1765): That is, the violence of resentment, the eagerness of revenge.—BECKET (1815, ii. 66): The heat is said in allusion to racing. The meaning is, \"the race is over\". [Adopted by others.]—SCHMIDT (1874): Haste, pressure, urgency.—N.E.D. (Heat sb. 12): The intense or violent stage of any action; height, stress (e.g. of conflict, debate, etc.)."
      ]
    },
    "27": {
      "play": "Call in the powers, good cousin Westmoreland.",
      "notes": [
        "Follow] N.E.D. (Follow v. 5): To go in pursuit of; to pursue, chase.",
        "powers] See note on I.i.206."
      ]
    },
    "28": {
      "play": "Westmoreland exits. Retreat is sounded.",
      "notes": [
        "Retreat] N.E.D. (Retreat sb. 2b): Mil. The recall of a pursuing force. Obs. – [Quotes this line only.]"
      ]
    },
    "29": {
      "play": "Now, Falstaff, where have you been all this while?",
      "notes": [
        "] RITSON (apud Steevens, ed. 1793, viii. 595): \"Oldcastle, where have you been all this while?\" [See note on II.iv.365.]"
      ]
    },
    "30": {
      "play": "When everything is ended, then you come.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "31": {
      "play": "These tardy tricks of yours will, on my life,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "32": {
      "play": "One time or other break some gallows’ back.",
      "notes": [
        "break ... back] DELIUS (ed. 1857) quotes 1 Henry IV II.iv.235, “horse-back-breaker”."
      ]
    },
    "33": {
      "play": "FALSTAFF: I would be sorry, my lord, but it should be",
      "notes": []
    },
    "34": {
      "play": "thus. I never knew yet but rebuke and check was the",
      "notes": [
        "I ... but] PINK (ed. 1935): I always knew that.—[See note on II.iv.57.]",
        "check] SCHMIDT (1874): Rebuke, reproof."
      ]
    },
    "35": {
      "play": "reward of valor. Do you think me a swallow, an",
      "notes": [
        "] AX (1912, p. 78): Lancaster’s words ... may be backed by Holinshed’s account iii. 530 [p. 536 below]: \"Wherevpon their troops scaled and fled their"
      ]
    },
    "36": {
      "play": "arrow, or a bullet? Have I in my poor and old",
      "notes": []
    },
    "37": {
      "play": "motion the expedition of thought? I have speeded",
      "notes": []
    },
    "38": {
      "play": "hither with the very extremest inch of possibility. I",
      "notes": [
        "with ... possibility] WARBURTON (ed. 1747): I.e. it was not possible, in the nature of things, to have got one inch further in the space of time allowed me.—DELIUS (ed. 1857): I have hurried here as fast as it is possible to hurry in an extremity. Inch is here the emphatically designated measure of movement.—RUSHTON (Sh. an Archer, 1897, p. 56): Falstaff ... [compares] the effect produced by his own exertion on his poor and old motion, to the effect produced by the exertion of the archer when he draws the arrow up to the extremest inch of its length, thereby causing its greatest possible speed.—HERFORD (ed. 1899): [With] the utmost possible speed.—ONIONS (1911): [With] the very utmost [of possibility].—COWL (ed. 1923): With the very last inch of possible speed.—COLLINS (ed. 1927): Extremest inch is used loosely; it is transformed from “the greatest distance” to mean “the greatest speed in covering a given distance.”"
      ]
    },
    "39": {
      "play": "have foundered ninescore and odd posts, and here,",
      "notes": [
        "foundered] N.E.D. (Founder v. 5): To cause to break down or go lame.",
        "ninescore and odd] MORGANN (1777, pp. 54 f.): It is probable that Falstaff was singularly adroit at his exercises [see III.ii.33] ... Even at the age at which he is exhibited to us, we find him foundering, as he calls it, nine score and odd miles [sic], with wonderful expedition, to join the army of Prince John of Lancaster.—CLARKE (ed. 1865): It is not that he for a moment means Prince John to believe in his having foundered more than a hundred and eighty horses, but he has a relish of defending himself with such exuberance of re-"
      ]
    },
    "40": {
      "play": "travel-tainted as I am, have in my pure and immaculate",
      "notes": []
    },
    "41": {
      "play": "valor taken Sir John Colevile of the Dale, a most",
      "notes": []
    },
    "42": {
      "play": "furious knight and valorous enemy. But what of",
      "notes": []
    },
    "43": {
      "play": "that? He saw me and yielded, that I may justly say,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "44": {
      "play": "with the hook-nosed fellow of Rome, “There, cousin,",
      "notes": [
        "the ... Rome] RANN (ed. 1789): Julius Caesar.—HUDSON (ed. 1880): I cannot tell whence the Poet got his hint for this epithet hook-nosed; perhaps from some of the Dictator's coins, engravings of which were doubtless printed in his time.—[H. N. PAUL, Esq., calls my attention to the medallion-portrait of Caesar in North's translation of Plutarch, which shows, in profile, a nose with a hook.—STOKES (1924, p. 51) collects Sh.'s many references to Julius Caesar.—RIDLEY's statement (ed. 1934) that Q reads nosoe (actually nosde) is a mistake.—ED.]",
        "Rome] Q Rome, there (their) cousin, (see textual notes).—CAPELL (Notes, 1779, p. 179) attributes the omission of these words from F to SH.—COLLIER (ed. 1842): The quarto adds unintelligibly \"their cousin\" ... Possibly Falstaff meant to claim relationship, in point of valour, with Julius Caesar, and called him \"my cousin\".—DELIUS (ed. 1857): Perhaps the MS. read your cousin, so that Julius Caesar was jokingly designated the prince's cousin.—COWL (ed. 1923): The words ... may have been a part of the sentence, as first drafted, which the author rejected but omitted to cancel. The \"hook-nosed fellow of Rome\" was perhaps an afterthought.—IDEM (Sources, 1928, pp. 50 f.) [pursuing the same idea]: This is suggested by the corruption of the text of Q, which would seem to indicate a reading their or the cozening (I came, saw, and overcame), and by the echoes of the text, which would lead us to expect something like \"the conquering Caesar.\" It is significant that three of the four parallel passages [Jonson, Every Man in his Humour (1616) II.ii; Fletcher & Massinger, The Beggar's Bush (1622) v.ii; Massinger, The Maid of Honour (1622) iii; Hon. James Howard, The Mad Couple (1672) IV.v] refer to Caesar by name, and that three of them describe Cæsar as a conqueror.—RIDLEY (ed. 1934): The words as they stand seem quite irrelevant; nevertheless there they are. (Is there possibly underlying it 'thrasonic,' cf. As You Like It [v.ii.29, \"Caesar's thrasonical brag of 'I came, saw, and overcame'\"].)—[I cannot see that these words are altogether unintelligible. \"There, cousin; I came, saw, and overcame\" hardly defies explanation. Cousin is properly used by a prince to an equal or to a noble; it is sometimes used between equals of noble rank, as by Westmoreland in addressing Mowbray at iv.iii.85. Falstaff, of course, has no business using it in speaking to the prince, but he never lacks effrontery. Indeed, the very point of the joke may lie in his giving himself the airs of a second Caesar. Cf. 1 Henry IV v.v.141, \"I look to be either earl or duke, I assure you\". It is hardly one of Falstaff's best jokes, and I am not altogether convinced that the text is sound and that Cowl may not be right in thinking that the passage has been revised, but thus, I think, we may put the best face on the matter at this late day. In any case, their for there in the catchword on the preceding page is a not uncommon kind of typographical error. If the omission of the phrase from F is not due to correct reading of what the Q compositor read wrongly, it may be one of those inadvertent omissions of which there are a good many in F.—ED.] I ... ouer-came] SANDYS (Sh.'s England, 1916, i. 270): The sentence in North's Plutarch (Life of Julius Caesar, c. 50), 'veni, vidi, vici: to wit, \"I came, I saw, I overcame\"', is the source of the quotation and of the rendering of these three words."
      ]
    },
