        "commences] CAPELL (Notes, 1779, p. 180): I.e. makes a beginning in’t; taps it, as is the vulgar expression, and sets it a running.—TYRWHITT (Var. ’78): It seems probable to me, that Shakespeare in these words alludes to the Cambridge Commencement; and in what follows to the Oxford Act: for by those different names our two universities have long distinguished the season, at which each of them gives to her respective students a complete authority to use those hoards of learning, which have entitled them to their several degrees in arts, law, physic, and divinity.—N.E.D. (Commence v. 4c) bears Tyrwhitt out."
