  "ACT 4, SCENE 3": {
    "1": {
      "play": "[Enter the King in a chair, Warwick, Thomas Duke of",
      "notes": []
    },
    "2": {
      "play": "Clarence, Humphrey Duke of Gloucester, and",
      "notes": [
        "Clarence] Ax (1912, pp. 87 f.): As to the persons who attend on the King ..., none is explicitly named by the chronicler except the Prince of Wales. But it is possible that all may have been present, especially his sons, save Thomas, Duke of Clarence, whom the King, in the play, advises how to treat his eldest brother. Thomas, as Sh. could have seen in the chronicle, was at that time in France; for we read in iii. 541: \"The duke of Clarence immediatlie vpon knowledge had of his father king Henrie the fourth his death, returned out of Guien into England.\""
      ]
    },
    "3": {
      "play": "Attendants.]",
      "notes": []
    },
    "4": {
      "play": "KING: Now, lords, if God doth give successful end",
      "notes": [
        "debate] Schmidt (1874): Contest, quarrel."
      ]
    },
    "5": {
      "play": "To this debate that bleedeth at our doors,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "6": {
      "play": "We will our youth lead on to higher fields",
      "notes": []
    },
    "7": {
      "play": "And draw no swords but what are sanctified.",
      "notes": [
        "sanctified] Miss WINSTANLEY (ed. 1918): For service against the infidel."
      ]
    },
    "8": {
      "play": "Our navy is addressed, our power collected,",
      "notes": [
        "addressed] STEEVENS (Var. '73): Ready, prepar’d.",
        "power] See note on I.i.149."
      ]
    },
    "9": {
      "play": "Our substitutes in absence well invested,",
      "notes": [
        "substitutes] See note on IV.ii.29.",
        "invested] N.E.D. (Invest v. 5): To establish (a person) in the possession of any office, position, property etc.—[Cf. IV.v.84.]"
      ]
    },
    "10": {
      "play": "And everything lies level to our wish.",
      "notes": [
        "level to] N.E.D. (Level a. 3): Lying in the same horizontal plane as something else; on a level with. Also fig., on an equality with; readily accessible or intelligible to [quoting this line]."
      ]
    },
    "11": {
      "play": "Only we want a little personal strength;",
      "notes": [
        "Only] DELIUS (ed. 1857): Simply, without further ceremony."
      ]
    },
    "12": {
      "play": "And pause us till these rebels now afoot",
      "notes": [
        "pause us] On the reflexive use of this verb and on the personal for the reflexive pronoun see FRANZ (3 ed., 1924) §§628, 307."
      ]
    },
    "13": {
      "play": "Come underneath the yoke of government.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "14": {
      "play": "WARWICK: Both which we doubt not but your Majesty",
      "notes": [
        "weeps] N.E.D. (Weep v. 4b): To issue in drops; to trickle or fall as tears [quoting this line as its earliest example].—COWL (ed. 1923): An allusion to the belief that every sigh draws a drop of blood from the heart."
      ]
    },
    "15": {
      "play": "Shall soon enjoy.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "16": {
      "play": "KING: Humphrey, my son of Gloucester, where is the",
      "notes": []
    },
    "17": {
      "play": "Prince your brother?",
      "notes": [
        "he is] From the metrical point of view, Q he is is tolerable only if pronounced in a way scarcely distinguishable from he’s. The expansion of a contraction is a possible error in typesetting.—Ed."
      ]
    },
    "18": {
      "play": "HUMPHREY OF GLOUCESTER: I think he’s gone to hunt, my lord, at Windsor.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "19": {
      "play": "KING: And how accompanied?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "20": {
      "play": "HUMPHREY OF GLOUCESTER: I do not know, my lord.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "21": {
      "play": "KING: Is not his brother Thomas of Clarence with him?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "22": {
      "play": "HUMPHREY OF GLOUCESTER: No, my good lord, he is in presence here.",
      "notes": [
        "in presence] SCHMIDT (1875): Present."
      ]
    },
    "23": {
      "play": "THOMAS OF CLARENCE, coming forward  What would",
      "notes": []
    },
    "24": {
      "play": "my lord and father?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "25": {
      "play": "KING: Nothing but well to thee, Thomas of Clarence.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "26": {
      "play": "How chance thou art not with the Prince thy",
      "notes": [
        "How chance] N.E.D. (Chance v. 5): How chance was formerly used in questions for ‘how chances it that’, ‘how is (was) it that’. Here chance takes no inflexion, and almost assumes the character of an adverb.—[See ABBOTT (1870) §37, FRANZ (3 ed., 1924) §437. Cf. II.i.12.]"
      ]
    },
    "27": {
      "play": "brother?",
      "notes": [
        "by] In consequence of. See Abbott (1870) §146; Franz (3 ed., 1924) §475. Cf. 1. 224 below."
      ]
    },
    "28": {
      "play": "He loves thee, and thou dost neglect him, Thomas.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "29": {
      "play": "Thou hast a better place in his affection",
      "notes": [
        "] AX (1912, p. 88): That [Clarence] was Prince Henry’s favourite brother, we could not find in the chronicle."
      ]
    },
    "30": {
      "play": "Than all thy brothers. Cherish it, my boy,",
      "notes": [
        "] QUILLER-COUCH (Tales, 1900, p. 240): Clarence ... cherished little love but no little contempt for his elder brother."
      ]
    },
    "31": {
      "play": "And noble offices thou mayst effect",
      "notes": [
        "] On the Q stage-direction, see p. 490. On the F stage-direction see pp. 512 ff.—Q Kent. Edmund Holland, 4th earl of Kent, is mentioned several times in Holinshed's account of the reign of Henry IV. Under the year 1406, e.g., Holinshed remarks on the high esteem in which the king held him and records his marriage; under 1405 \"the lord Thomas of Lancaster, and the earle of Kent\" burn some French ships at Sluys and lead an English fleet along the French coast; under 1408 he is charged with clearing the coast of pirates and is mortally wounded in an assault on Briac (D.N.B.: Briant). His brother Thomas, the 3d earl, who was killed at Cirencester in 1400 in consequence of his rising against King Henry, is of course mentioned by Holinshed (iii. 515). Kent would seem to be another background figure like Sir John Blunt (see note on i.i.24)."
      ]
    },
    "32": {
      "play": "Of mediation, after I am dead,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "33": {
      "play": "Between his greatness and thy other brethren.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "34": {
      "play": "Therefore omit him not, blunt not his love,",
      "notes": [
        "omit] SCHMIDT (1875): To neglect, to leave unregarded.—N.E.D. quotes only 2 Henry VI III.ii.382, this line, and Measure IV.iii.69."
      ]
    },
    "35": {
      "play": "Nor lose the good advantage of his grace",
      "notes": []
    },
    "36": {
      "play": "By seeming cold or careless of his will.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "37": {
      "play": "For he is gracious if he be observed;",
      "notes": []
    },
    "38": {
      "play": "He hath a tear for pity, and a hand",
      "notes": []
    },
    "39": {
      "play": "Open as day for melting charity;",
      "notes": []
    },
    "40": {
      "play": "Yet notwithstanding, being incensed he is flint,",
      "notes": [
        "] MALONE (2 App., 1783) quotes A Lover’s Complaint 99-103: “His qualities were beauteous as his form, For maiden-tongued he was, and thereof free; Yet, if men moved him, was he such a storm As oft ’twixt May and April is to see, When winds breathe sweet, unruly though they be”.",
        "he is flint] VAUGHAN (1878, i. 552 f.): He breaks out in angry and transient sparks like a flint.—ROLFE (ed. 1880) quotes Caesar IV. iii. 110, “That carries anger as the flint bears fire”.—Miss WINSTANLEY (ed. 1918): He is very hard and stern."
      ]
    },
    "41": {
      "play": "As humorous as winter, and as sudden",
      "notes": [
        "As humorous as winter] JOHNSON (ed. 1765): That is, changeable as the weather of a winter’s day.—MALONE (Suppl., 1780): He abounds in capricious fancies, as winter abounds in moisture.—[A quibble on humorous = capricious (N.E.D., Humorous a. 3) and humorous = moist, damp (Humorous a. 1).]",
        "sudden] N.E.D. (Sudden a. 2b): Of persons: hasty, impetuous, rash. Obs. or arch."
      ]
    },
    "42": {
      "play": "As flaws congealèd in the spring of day.",
      "notes": [
        "flaws] WARBURTON (ed. 1747): Alluding to the opinion of some philosophers, that the vapours being congealed in the air by cold, (which is most intense towards morning) and being afterwards rarified and let loose by the warmth of the sun, occasion those sudden and impetuous gusts of wind which are called Flaws.—EDWARDS (7 ed., 1765, p. 124): The meaning ... seems to be the small blades of ice, which are struck on the edges of the water in winter mornings; and which I have heard called by that name.—MALONE",
        "rage] N.E.D. (Rage sb. 6): A violent feeling, passion, or appetite."
      ]
    },
    "43": {
      "play": "His temper therefore must be well observed.",
      "notes": [
        "temper] See note on II.i.71."
      ]
    },
    "44": {
      "play": "Chide him for faults, and do it reverently,",
      "notes": [
        "as] N.E.D. (As B9): Introducing a supposition, expressed by the subjunctive mood: As if, as though. arch.—[See Abbott (1870) §107, FRANZ (3 ed., 1924) §582.]"
      ]
    },
    "45": {
      "play": "When you perceive his blood inclined to mirth;",
      "notes": []
    },
    "46": {
      "play": "But, being moody, give him time and scope",
      "notes": [
        "being moody] Modifies an he to be inferred from him. See note on I.i.154.",
        "moody] N.E.D. (Moody a. 3): Angry, given to anger, wrathful. Obs.",
        "give ... scope] Q time is also intelligible, and it is odd that more editors have not adopted it. It is as likely that time would be misread line as that line would be misread time. See p. 506.—N.E.D. (Line sb.2 2b): To give line: to allow full play, scope, or latitude [quoting this line].—N.E.D. thus seems to dispose of the notion put forward by VAUGHAN (1878, i. 554) and by FURNIVALL (Old Sp. ed., 1909) that while line would apply to a harpooned whale, it cannot apply to a stranded whale.—SCHULZE (1908, p. 26): [Give him] scope on the line [hendiadys]."
      ]
    },
    "47": {
      "play": "Till that his passions, like a whale on ground,",
      "notes": [
        "whale on ground] BOSWELL-STONE (1896, p. 156) finds the source of this simile in Holinshed’s account of the stranding of a whale in Kent in 1574; see p. 542 below.",
        "ground] SCHMIDT (1874): The land, the earth as distinguished from water."
      ]
    },
    "48": {
      "play": "Confound themselves with working. Learn this,",
      "notes": [
        "Confound] N.E.D. (Confound v. 1e): To waste, consume, spend. Obs. [Quotes as its earliest example 1 Henry IV 1.iii.100, “He did confound the best part of an hour.”]"
      ]
    },
    "49": {
      "play": "Thomas,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "50": {
      "play": "And thou shalt prove a shelter to thy friends,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "51": {
      "play": "A hoop of gold to bind thy brothers in,",
      "notes": [
        "hoop] DEIGHTON (ed. 1893): The figure is that of hooping together the several staves of a cask so as to form one compact whole.",
        "hath] Q hands is almost certainly a misreading, though FURNIVALL (Old Sp. ed., 1909) explains it as=Sickness’s hands. RIDLEY’s have (haue) may be closer graphically to hands than hath is, but in view of the fact that F derives ultimately from Sh.’s MS. I do not know why we may not be content to assume that it preserves what Sh. wrote.—ED."
      ]
    },
    "52": {
      "play": "That the united vessel of their blood,",
      "notes": [
        "united] DELIUS (ed. 1857): According to the thought, united belongs to blood."
      ]
    },
    "53": {
      "play": "Mingled with venom of suggestion",
      "notes": [
        "venom of suggestion] CAPELL (Notes, 1779, p. 180): The poisonous insinuations of false friends, aiming at division.—MALONE (ed. 1790): The temptations to which youth is peculiarly subject.—VAUGHAN (1878, i. 555): The whole tenor of the king’s address ... is that of an exhortation ... to keep the brotherhood of princes free from fatal dissension. Youthful temptations"
      ]
    },
    "54": {
      "play": "(As, force perforce, the age will pour it in),",
      "notes": [
        "force perforce] See note on iv.i.125."
      ]
    },
    "55": {
      "play": "Shall never leak, though it do work as strong",
      "notes": [
        "Shall never leak] DEIGHTON (ed. 1893): An allusion to the belief that poison dropped into a vessel will cause it to break.—COWL (ed. 1923): An allusion to the belief that aconite is so powerful in its action that it will ooze through the walls even of a stone vessel.",
        "it] The vessel of blood, with the venom mingled in it; not, as Miss WINSTANLEY (ed. 1918) says, the poisonous suggestions.—ED."
      ]
    },
    "56": {
      "play": "As aconitum or rash gunpowder.",
      "notes": [
        "grace] Favor.",
        "aconitum] BEISLY (1864, p. 103): Aconitum Napellus (common monkshood, or wolf’s bane), ... the whole of which, particularly the root, is very poisonous. ... The ancients considered the aconite the most violent of all poisons, and fabled it the invention of Hecate, and to have sprung from the foam of Cerberus.—B. R. FIELD (Shakespeariana vi, 1889, p. 13): Then thought to act only as a poison; its medicinal properties not having been discovered until 1762.—BUCKNILL (1860, pp. 162 f.) quotes Romeo v.i.59-65: “let me have A dram of poison; such soon-spreading gear As will disperse itself through all the veins, That the life-weary taker may fall dead, And that the trunk may be discharged of breath As violently as hasty powder fired Doth hurry from the fatal cannon’s womb”.",
        "rash] N.E.D. (Rash a. 2b): Of things: Operating quickly and strongly. Obs. rare. [Quotes only this line and Winter’s Tale i.ii.319, “with no rash potion But with a lingering dram”.]"
      ]
    },
    "57": {
      "play": "THOMAS OF CLARENCE: I shall observe him with all care and love.",
      "notes": [
        "observe] See note on l. 36 above."
      ]
    },
    "58": {
      "play": "KING: Why art thou not at Windsor with him, Thomas?",
      "notes": [
        "blood] N.E.D. (Blood sb. 5): The supposed seat of emotion, passion; whence, Passion, temper, mood, disposition [quoting this line].—[Cf. II.iii.33, V.ii.137.]",
        "blood] SCHMIDT (1874): The fleshly nature of man.—DEIGHTON (ed. 1893): Nature.—Miss WINSTANLEY (ed. 1918): Heart.—COWL (ed. 1923): Natural feeling."
      ]
    },
    "59": {
      "play": "THOMAS OF CLARENCE: He is not there today; he dines in London.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "60": {
      "play": "KING: And how accompanied? Canst thou tell that?",
      "notes": [
        "Canst ... that?] On the omission of this phrase from Q see p. 495."
      ]
    },
    "61": {
      "play": "THOMAS OF CLARENCE: With Poins and other his continual followers.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "62": {
      "play": "KING: Most subject is the fattest soil to weeds,",
      "notes": [
        "] Proverbial. See JENTE (1926), No. 339.—Miss SPURGEON (1935, p. 164): Evil as a weed is a natural outcome of the running imagery of the untended garden throughout the historical plays, where it occurs constantly, and much penetrating thought is conveyed in theses plays and elsewhere through this image.—CLEMEN (1936, p. 253): Such a characterization directly comprehends the organic law of the prince’s development. This image has nothing to do with the arabesques of sententious maxims so often encountered in earlier works. Its position in the whole philosophy of the play disproves this. Here the royal father reveals a very deep understanding of his son’s way of life; moreover, in this passage there is an indication from Sh. of how we are to understand this way of life: the intrinsically rich and gifted man is at the same time in the greatest danger and must attain equilibrium by a roundabout course. It throws a light on Sh.’s idiosyncrasy in the use of such images in that in Lyly, from whom Sh. perhaps borrowed the outward form of this idea, the image is found thus: “The fattest grounde bringeth foorth nothing but weedes” (ed. Bond, 1902, i. 251). Sh. alters “nothing but” to “most subject,” thus giving the image a different meaning, the meaning which he used here. And what was in Euphues merely one of those countless examples from natural history which are ranked together without organic relation here becomes an organic characteristic of a principal character at a critical juncture."
      ]
    },
    "63": {
      "play": "And he, the noble image of my youth,",
      "notes": [
        "the ... youth] COWL (ed. 1923): Perhaps an echo of Kyd, The Spanish Tragedy [III.xiii, Works, ed. Boas, 1901, p. 74]: “Hier. I, now I know thee, now thou namest thy Sonne: Thou art the liuely image of my griefe”."
      ]
    },
    "64": {
      "play": "Is overspread with them; therefore my grief",
      "notes": []
    },
    "65": {
      "play": "Stretches itself beyond the hour of death.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "66": {
      "play": "The blood weeps from my heart when I do shape,",
      "notes": [
        "shape] ONIONS (1911): To form a mental image of, conceive, imagine."
      ]
    },
    "67": {
      "play": "In forms imaginary, th’ unguided days",
      "notes": []
    },
    "68": {
      "play": "And rotten times that you shall look upon",
      "notes": []
    },
    "69": {
      "play": "When I am sleeping with my ancestors.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "70": {
      "play": "For when his headstrong riot hath no curb,",
      "notes": [
        "] MADDEN (1897, p. 266): Prince Hal’s coltish humours suggest to his father the ragery of an uncurbed and unhandled colt."
      ]
    },
    "71": {
      "play": "When rage and hot blood are his counsellors,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "72": {
      "play": "When means and lavish manners meet together,",
      "notes": [
        "lavish] SCHMIDT (1874): Unrestrained, licentious. [N.E.D. quotes this line as its earliest example.]"
      ]
    },
    "73": {
      "play": "O, with what wings shall his affections fly",
      "notes": [
        "affections] JOHNSON (ed. 1765): His passions; his inordinate desires. [So also SCHMIDT.]—CLARKE (ed. 1865): ‘Natural propensities,’ ‘native inclinations.’ [So also ROLFE (ed. 1880) and COWL (ed. 1923).]—[Cf. vi.ii.132.]"
      ]
    },
    "74": {
      "play": "Towards fronting peril and opposed decay!",
      "notes": [
        "decay] N.E.D. (Decay sb. 1b): Formerly sometimes = Downfall, destruction, ruin; poet. fall, death. Obs. [Quotes John iv.iii.154, “and vast confusion waits, As doth a raven on a sick-fallen beast, The imminent decay of wrested pomp”.]"
      ]
    },
    "75": {
      "play": "WARWICK: My gracious lord, you look beyond him quite.",
      "notes": [
        "look beyond] N.E.D. (Beyond prep. 3): Misconstrue, misunderstand.—[Apparently unique.]"
      ]
    },
    "76": {
      "play": "The Prince but studies his companions",
      "notes": [
        "companions] G. KÖNIG (1888, p. 43) notes that the word has four syllables here."
      ]
    },
    "77": {
      "play": "Like a strange tongue, wherein, to gain the",
      "notes": [
        "strange] SCHMIDT (1875): Foreign."
      ]
    },
    "78": {
      "play": "language,",
      "notes": [
        "heavy] N.E.D. (Heavy a. 13): Grave, severe, deep, profound, intense."
      ]
    },
    "79": {
      "play": "’Tis needful that the most immodest word",
      "notes": []
    },
    "80": {
      "play": "Be looked upon and learned; which, once attained,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "81": {
      "play": "Your Highness knows, comes to no further use",
      "notes": []
    },
    "82": {
      "play": "But to be known and hated. So, like gross terms,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "83": {
      "play": "The Prince will, in the perfectness of time,",
      "notes": [
        "perfectness] N.E.D.: Perfection."
      ]
    },
    "84": {
      "play": "Cast off his followers, and their memory",
      "notes": []
    },
    "85": {
      "play": "Shall as a pattern or a measure live,",
      "notes": [
        "gain] SCHMIDT (1874): Learn."
      ]
    },
    "86": {
      "play": "By which his Grace must mete the lives of others,",
      "notes": [
        "mete] N.E.D. (Mete v.¹ 4): To estimate the greatness or value of; to appraise [quoting this line]."
      ]
    },
    "87": {
      "play": "Turning past evils to advantages.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "88": {
      "play": "KING: ’Tis seldom when the bee doth leave her comb",
      "notes": [
        "seldom when] ONIONS (1911): Seldom that."
      ]
    },
    "89": {
      "play": "In the dead carrion.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "90": {
      "play": "[Enter Westmoreland.]",
      "notes": []
    },
    "91": {
      "play": "Who’s here? Westmoreland?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "92": {
      "play": "WESTMORELAND: Health to my sovereign, and new happiness",
      "notes": [
        "Health] See note on iv.i.35."
      ]
    },
    "93": {
      "play": "Added to that that I am to deliver.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "94": {
      "play": "Prince John your son doth kiss your Grace’s hand.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "95": {
      "play": "Mowbray, the Bishop Scroop, Hastings, and all",
      "notes": [
        "the Bishop Scroop] The comma, uniformly omitted by modern editors, is no doubt misleading in the context, but hardly wrong by either 16th- or 20th-century standards.—ED."
      ]
    },
    "96": {
      "play": "Are brought to the correction of your law.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "97": {
      "play": "There is not now a rebel’s sword unsheathed,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "98": {
      "play": "But peace puts forth her olive everywhere.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "99": {
      "play": "The manner how this action hath been borne",
      "notes": [
        "action] See note on ii.ii.194.",
        "borne] N.E.D. (Bear vb.¹ 15b): To suffer without succumbing, to sustain without giving way, to endure. Formerly with away, out.—[Cf. iv.v.232.]"
      ]
    },
    "100": {
      "play": "Here at more leisure may your Highness read",
      "notes": []
    },
    "101": {
      "play": "With every course in his particular.",
      "notes": [
        "] HERFORD (ed. 1899): With every movement in detail."
      ]
    },
    "102": {
      "play": "He gives the King a paper.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "103": {
      "play": "KING: O Westmoreland, thou art a summer bird,",
      "notes": [
        "summer] SCHMIDT (1875): Implying the idea of all that is pleasant and gratifying.—[Some ornithophilous commentators have concerned themselves to identify this summer bird. YARDLEY (10 N. & Q. viii, 1907, p. 304) votes for the blackbird, with the thrush as second choice; COWL (ed. 1923), for the cuckoo.]"
      ]
    },
    "104": {
      "play": "Which ever in the haunch of winter sings",
      "notes": [
        "haunch] N.E.D. (Haunch sb.¹ 1d): fig. The hinder part, the latter end [quoting this line only].—[Sh. uses a similar metaphor in two other places—Love’s Labour’s Lost v.i.76, “the posteriors of this day”, and Coriolanus ii.i.47–8, “the buttock of the night”. Both of the other contexts are humorous.—ED.]"
      ]
    },
    "105": {
      "play": "The lifting up of day.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "106": {
      "play": "[Enter Harcourt.]",
      "notes": []
    },
    "107": {
      "play": "Look, here’s more news.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "108": {
      "play": "HARCOURT: From enemies heavens keep your Majesty,",
      "notes": [
        "heavens] In setting aside Q heavens the editors must assume that Enemies has attracted heaven to the plural.—Ed.",
        "part] Schmidt (1875): Characteristic action.—N.E.D. (Part sb. 11): A piece of conduct, an act (usually with qualification expressing praise or blame). Obs."
      ]
    },
    "109": {
      "play": "And when they stand against you, may they fall",
      "notes": []
    },
    "110": {
      "play": "As those that I am come to tell you of.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "111": {
      "play": "The Earl Northumberland and the Lord Bardolph,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "112": {
      "play": "With a great power of English and of Scots,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "113": {
      "play": "Are by the shrieve of Yorkshire overthrown.",
      "notes": [
        "shrieve] FRENCH (1869, pp. 92 f.): He was Sir Thomas Rokeby, descended from an old and knightly family, long seated at Rokeby, co. York, a place rendered familiar by Sir Walter Scott’s poem of the same name.—[Q shrieue, which the meter demands, is a form of the word current, according to N.E.D., from the 15th to the 19th century.—Ed.]"
      ]
    },
    "114": {
      "play": "The manner and true order of the fight",
      "notes": [
        "order] N.E.D. (Order sb. 12): Succession of acts or events; the mode in which this occurs, course or method of occurrence or action."
      ]
    },
    "115": {
      "play": "This packet, please it you, contains at large.",
      "notes": [
        "please it you] See note on i.i.9."
      ]
    },
    "116": {
      "play": "He gives the King papers.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "117": {
      "play": "KING: And wherefore should these good news make me",
      "notes": [
        "these ... news] See note on i.i.36."
      ]
    },
    "118": {
      "play": "sick?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "119": {
      "play": "Will Fortune never come with both hands full,",
      "notes": [
        "Fortune] ROOT (1903, p. 62): Classical art represented Fortuna most commonly as a woman standing, in the left hand holding a cornucopia, in the right a ship’s rudder resting on a globe—the cornucopia representing her favors, the rudder her directing power, and the globe her changeableness. [This line] is suggestive of the cornucopia in one hand only.",
        "write ... letters] Q wet ... termes. A very odd misprint indeed. It is"
      ]
    },
    "120": {
      "play": "But write her fair words still in foulest letters?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "121": {
      "play": "She either gives a stomach and no food—",
      "notes": [
        "stomach] SCHMIDT (1875): Appetite."
      ]
    },
    "122": {
      "play": "Such are the poor, in health—or else a feast",
      "notes": [
        "the poor, in health] DEIGHTON (ed. 1893): The poor who have the health and appetite to enjoy."
      ]
    },
    "123": {
      "play": "And takes away the stomach—such are the rich,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "124": {
      "play": "That have abundance and enjoy it not.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "125": {
      "play": "I should rejoice now at this happy news,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "126": {
      "play": "And now my sight fails, and my brain is giddy.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "127": {
      "play": "O, me! Come near me, now I am much ill.",
      "notes": [
        "much] SCHMIDT (1875): Qualifying adjectives and adverbs, = very.—[See ABBOTT (1870) §51, FRANZ (3 ed., 1924) §386.]"
      ]
    },
    "128": {
      "play": "HUMPHREY OF GLOUCESTER: Comfort, your Majesty.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "129": {
      "play": "THOMAS OF CLARENCE: O, my royal father!",
      "notes": []
    },
    "130": {
      "play": "WESTMORELAND: My sovereign lord, cheer up yourself, look up.",
      "notes": [
        "look up] N.E.D. (Look v. 45c): Look up. To cheer up, take courage, be cheerful [quoting Shn. examples only, including this line]."
      ]
    },
    "131": {
      "play": "WARWICK: Be patient, princes. You do know these fits",
      "notes": []
    },
    "132": {
      "play": "Are with his Highness very ordinary.",
      "notes": [
        "ordinary] N.E.D. (Ordinary a. 4): Of common or everyday occurrence; frequent; abundant. Obs. [Quotes this line as its earliest example.]"
      ]
    },
    "133": {
      "play": "Stand from him, give him air. He’ll straight be",
      "notes": []
    },
    "134": {
      "play": "well.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "135": {
      "play": "THOMAS OF CLARENCE: No, no, he cannot long hold out these pangs.",
      "notes": [
        "hold out] N.E.D. (Hold v. 418): Hold out. To bear or sustain to the end. Obs."
      ]
    },
    "136": {
      "play": "Th’ incessant care and labor of his mind",
      "notes": []
    },
    "137": {
      "play": "Hath wrought the mure that should confine it in",
      "notes": [
        "Hath wrought] See note on iv.i.93 and FRANZ (3 ed., 1924) §673.",
        "wrought] N.E.D. (Work v. 7): With complemental word or phrase: To cause to be, make, render. Obs.—[Wrought is, of course, the regular form of the participle of work in Sh.]",
        "mure] POPE (ed. 1723): Wall."
      ]
    },
    "138": {
      "play": "So thin that life looks through and will break out.",
      "notes": [
        "looks through] N.E.D. (Look v. 43c): Look through. To become visible or obvious. Obs. [Quotes this line only.]",
        "and ... out] On the omission of this phrase from Q see p. 495."
      ]
    },
    "139": {
      "play": "HUMPHREY OF GLOUCESTER: The people fear me, for they do observe",
      "notes": [
        "fear me] WARBURTON (ed. 1747): I.e. make me afraid."
      ]
    },
    "140": {
      "play": "Unfathered heirs and loathly births of nature.",
      "notes": [
        "Unfathered heirs] JOHNSON (ed. 1765): That is, equivocal births; animals that had no animal progenitors; productions not brought forth according to the stated laws of generation.—STAUNTON (ed. 1858): Certain so-called prophets, who pretended to have been conceived by miracle, like Merlin —\"And sooth, men say that he was not the sonne of mortall Syre, or other liuing wight, But wondrously begotten, and begonne By false illusion of a guilefull Spright, On a faire Ladie Nonne ...\" Faerie Queene III.iii.13. … And Montaigne refers to such supposed miraculous conceptions in his Essay entitled the Apology of Raymond Sebond, \"In Mahomets religion, by the easie beliefe of that people are many Merlins found; That is to say fatherles children: Spirituall children, conceived and borne divinely in the wombs of virgins, and that in their language beare names, importing as much.\"—\"Florio's Montaigne,\" folio 1603, p. 308 [ed. Saints bury, 1893, ii. 243].—SCHMIDT (1875): Unfathered, fatherless; and hence produced contrary to the course of nature (=unnatural procreations).—DELIUS (ed. 1857): Of nature modifies Unfather’d Heires as well as loathly Births; both are explained by what follows."
      ]
    },
    "141": {
      "play": "The seasons change their manners, as the year",
      "notes": []
    },
    "142": {
      "play": "Had found some months asleep and leapt them",
      "notes": []
    },
    "143": {
      "play": "over.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "144": {
      "play": "THOMAS OF CLARENCE: The river hath thrice flowed, no ebb between,",
      "notes": [
        "] AX (1912, p. 89): Clarence’s words ... correspond to a passage in Holinshed iii. 540 [p. 540 below] ... The conformity of the words is here interesting, Sh. having “no ebb between”, and Holinshed “no ebbing between”."
      ]
    },
    "145": {
      "play": "And the old folk, time’s doting chronicles,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "146": {
      "play": "Say it did so a little time before",
      "notes": []
    },
    "147": {
      "play": "That our great-grandsire, Edward, sicked and died.",
      "notes": [
        "sicked] SCHMIDT (1875): Sick vb. to sicken, to fall ill.—ROLFE (ed. 1880): The only instance of the verb in Sh."
      ]
    },
    "148": {
      "play": "WARWICK: Speak lower, princes, for the King recovers.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "149": {
      "play": "HUMPHREY OF GLOUCESTER: This apoplexy will certain be his end.",
      "notes": [
        "apoplexy] Apoplex (see textual notes) is a common contemporary form of the word. G. KÖNIG (1888, p. 39) calls for the elision of the last syllable with will, but does not explain how to do it. VAUGHAN (1878, ii. 558) recommends “ap’plexy”.—BUCKNILL (1860, pp. 163 f.): [Apoplexy] might be rightly applied to a sudden affection of the brain, caused by “the incessant care and labour of his mind;” but failing sight and giddiness of the brain might equally arise from failure of the heart’s action; defective supply of blood to the brain, being attended with the same symptoms of its failing function, as interference with its due nutrition from congestion or pressure. The suspension of the respiratory movements so that the ‘downy feather’ stirred not, though it lay at the gates of breath [IV.v.36], would indicate that the sudden illness, supervening on the shock of good news, was faintness and not apoplexy. The quick recovery of intellectual powers shews that Prince Humphrey miscalled his father’s illness in naming it an apoplexy. The whole scene describes the illness as faintness from exhaustion.—SIGISMUND (Jahrbuch xvi, 1881, p. 87) takes the apoplexy as a hemorrhage."
      ]
    },
    "150": {
      "play": "KING: I pray you take me up and bear me hence",
      "notes": []
    },
    "151": {
      "play": "Into some other chamber. Softly, pray.",
      "notes": [
        "Softly, pray] On the omission of this phrase from Q see p. 495.",
        "[no breaking of the scene.]] CAPELL (Notes, 1779, p. 180): Here is no breaking of the scene.—DYCE (ed. 1857): Here the old copies have no stage-direction. In fact, the audience of Shakespeare’s time were to suppose that a change of scene took place as soon as the King was laid on the bed.—CAMBRIDGE EDITORS (1864): Although neither the Folios nor any more recent editors make a change of scene after [iv.iv.151], we have ventured to do so [for the reason given by Dyce, as above]. ... Capell’s stage direction is not satisfactory, for it implies a change of scene, though none is indicated in the text.—KOPPEL (Jahrbuch ix, 1874, p. 292): The actors betake themselves to the inner room. Of a clearing of the stage and the consequently necessary division of scene it is not a question.—ROLFE (ed. 1880): To our mind it is perfectly clear that the king is now carried to another room. At the close of the scene he asks what was the name of the chamber in which he “first did swoon” (see iv.iv.126), and, being told that it is the Jerusalem Chamber, he asks to be borne to it; but if there is no change of scene here he is already in the Jerusalem Chamber. ... The Jerusalem Chamber is not a bedroom. The king is holding a council there when he swoons; and when he asks to be taken to “some other chamber” [iv.iv.151] (that is, to a bedroom), he is of course obeyed, and the scene shifts to that chamber, where he remains until he asks to be borne back to the Jerusalem Chamber, on account of the prophecy concerning his death.—W. A. WRIGHT (Academy xvii, 1880, p. 271): It seems ... very probable that in the present instance the scene, which in the early copies is not divided, was supposed to take place on two sides of a partition, which represented the division between the Jerusalem Chamber and a room adjoining, so that none of the actors would leave the stage. [See also Romeo II.i, Henry VIII v.ii, iii.]—FLEAY (Biog. Chron., 1891, ii. 200): The change of chamber ... was indicated by the traverse being drawn and the King being disclosed on a bed behind. The actors did not leave the stage, and no new scene should be marked.—CHAMBERS (Eliz. Stage, 1923, iii. 65 fn.): [This is] a continuous scene divided, with unanimity in ill-doing, by modern editors in the middle of a speech.—RHODES (Sh.’s First Folio, 1923, p. 136): Actus Quartus, Scena [Secunda] is one continuous scena, which has been divided in modern editions into ‘Scene 4: Westminster—The Jerusalem Chamber,’ and ‘Scene 5: Another Chamber.’ As a later passage shows, these apartments were ‘supposed’ as at a distance, and not as antechamber to chamber. In the Folio there was no division, because there was no ‘clear stage,’ the King remaining on the stage, but moving with his Lords from the forestage to the bedchamber, which was approached by drawing ‘the curtains.’—Sir M. HUNTER (R.E.S. ii, 1926, p. 297): The editors ... begin a new scene at line 151 in the middle of a speech, though interrupted sense and mutilated rhythm cry out in protest against them. [There has been a good deal of discussion of the manner in which this scene, i.e. iv.iv and iv.v, was managed on the Elizabethan stage, for, whatever the editors, with their casuistical minds, may say about a change of place, there"
      ]
    },
    "152": {
      "play": "The King is carried to a bed on another",
      "notes": []
    },
    "153": {
      "play": "part of the stage.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "154": {
      "play": "Let there be no noise made, my gentle friends,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "155": {
      "play": "Unless some dull and favorable hand",
      "notes": [
        "dull] JOHNSON (ed. 1765): Melancholy, gentle, soothing.—MALONE (ed. 1790): I believe it rather means producing fullness or heaviness; and consequently sleep.—SCHMIDT (1874): Disposing to sleep with a drowsy music.—ONIONS (1911): Soft, soothing.—[N.E.D. defines dull as “drowsy” (Dull a. 3) but not as “drowsy-making”. This would seem, therefore, to be a nonce use of the word extending, as HERFORD (ed. 1928) says, its meaning from the cause to the effect. See note on III.i.17.—ED.]",
        "favorable] N.E.D. (Favourable a. 2b): Gracious (said of a superior); kindly, obliging. Obs. exc. arch. [Quotes this line.]"
      ]
    },
    "156": {
      "play": "Will whisper music to my weary spirit.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "157": {
      "play": "WARWICK, to an Attendant",
      "notes": []
    },
    "158": {
      "play": "Call for the music in the other room.",
      "notes": [
        "] LAWRENCE (Physical Conditions, 1927, p. 89): [This] surely means that the music was to play somewhere behind curtains, either on the rear or the upper stage."
      ]
    },
    "159": {
      "play": "KING: Set me the crown upon my pillow here.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "160": {
      "play": "The crown is placed on the bed.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "161": {
      "play": "THOMAS OF CLARENCE, aside to the others",
      "notes": []
    },
    "162": {
      "play": "His eye is hollow, and he changes much.",
      "notes": [
        "changes] N.E.D. (Change v. 7e): To change countenance; to turn pale, blush, etc. Obs. [Quotes no examples outside Sh.]"
      ]
    },
    "163": {
      "play": "WARWICK: Less noise, less noise.",
      "notes": [
        "] QUILLER-COUCH (Tales, 1900, p. 242): Prince Harry came in noisy high spirits along the corridor, eager to tell the good news ... Warwick met him at the door, entreating, ‘Less noise, less noise!’—HERFORD (ed. 1928): Prince Hal enters, a breezy presence, his cheery humour, contrasted with the gloomy"
      ]
    },
    "164": {
      "play": "[Enter Prince Harry.]",
      "notes": []
    },
    "165": {
      "play": "PRINCE: Who saw the Duke of Clarence?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "166": {
      "play": "THOMAS OF CLARENCE, weeping",
      "notes": []
    },
    "167": {
      "play": "I am here, brother, full of heaviness.",
      "notes": [
        "full of heaviness] CARTER (1905, p. 283) quotes Phil. ii. 26, “For he longed after you al, and was ful of heauinesse”, and Ps. lxix. 20, “I an ful of heauinesse”.—On heauinesse, see note on IV.ii.89."
      ]
    },
    "168": {
      "play": "PRINCE: How now, rain within doors, and none abroad?",
      "notes": [
        "rain] DELIUS (ed. 1857): He means the tears which he observes in the eyes of those present.",
        "abroad] See note on I.ii.92."
      ]
    },
    "169": {
      "play": "How doth the King?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "170": {
      "play": "HUMPHREY OF GLOUCESTER: Exceeding ill.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "171": {
      "play": "PRINCE: Heard he the good news yet? Tell it him.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "172": {
      "play": "HUMPHREY OF GLOUCESTER: He altered much upon the hearing it.",
      "notes": [
        "altered] WILSON (Sh.’s Hand, 1923, p. 118) explains Q (some copies) vttred as an a:minim misreading."
      ]
    },
    "173": {
      "play": "PRINCE: If he be sick with joy, he’ll recover without",
      "notes": [
        "physic] See note on I.i.153."
      ]
    },
    "174": {
      "play": "physic.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "175": {
      "play": "WARWICK: Not so much noise, my lords.—Sweet prince, speak",
      "notes": []
    },
    "176": {
      "play": "low.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "177": {
      "play": "The King your father is disposed to sleep.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "178": {
      "play": "THOMAS OF CLARENCE: Let us withdraw into the other room.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "179": {
      "play": "WARWICK: Will ’t please your Grace to go along with us?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "180": {
      "play": "PRINCE: No, I will sit and watch here by the King.",
      "notes": [
        "sit and watch] COWL (ed. 1923): An office of love."
      ]
    },
    "181": {
      "play": "[All but Prince and King exit.]",
      "notes": []
    },
    "182": {
      "play": "Why doth the crown lie there upon his pillow,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "183": {
      "play": "Being so troublesome a bedfellow?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "184": {
      "play": "O polished perturbation, golden care,",
      "notes": [
        "perturbation] N.E.D. (Perturbation 3): A cause or factor of disturbance or agitation [quoting this line as its earliest example]."
      ]
    },
    "185": {
      "play": "That keep’st the ports of slumber open wide",
      "notes": [
        "ports] STEEVENS (Var. '78): Gates."
      ]
    },
    "186": {
      "play": "To many a watchful night! Sleep with it now;",
      "notes": []
    },
    "187": {
      "play": "Yet not so sound and half so deeply sweet",
      "notes": [
        "deeply] Schmidt (1874): Intensely, very much."
      ]
    },
    "188": {
      "play": "As he whose brow with homely biggen bound",
      "notes": [
        "he whose] Keightley's conjecture expresses the sense, but nobody has been able to rationalize the construction; indeed, few have tried. Though a singular and drastic compression, it seems to me intelligible enough.—Ed.",
        "biggen] N.E.D. (Biggin1 2): A cap or hood for the head, a night-cap [quoting this line]."
      ]
    },
    "189": {
      "play": "Snores out the watch of night. O majesty,",
      "notes": [
        "To ... night] DEIGHTON (ed. 1893): So that many a wakeful night may enter.",
        "watch of night] N.E.D. (Watch sb. 4): Each of the (three, four, or five) periods into which the night was anciently divided. Now often in collective plural, the watches of the night, used rhetorically for ‘the night-time’."
      ]
    },
    "190": {
      "play": "When thou dost pinch thy bearer, thou dost sit",
      "notes": [
        "pinch] See note on I.ii.212.",
        "bearer] N.E.D. (Bearer 5): The holder of rank or office [quoting this line as its earliest example].—[Cf. I. 179 below.]"
      ]
    },
    "191": {
      "play": "Like a rich armor worn in heat of day,",
      "notes": [
        "scald'st] I think Sh. may have written this, though strict logic undoubtedly requires scalds. It would be natural for a poet speaking metaphorically of the crown as a suit of armor to apply to the armor a verb in the same person as that of the last two verbs he has used with the crown. Indeed, I am not quite sure that he is certainly wrong in doing so. See p. 509.—Ed. —N.E.D. (Scald v. 6b): intr. for pass. To be scorched or burnt [quoting this line].",
        "with safety] Rolfe (ed. 1880): That is, while it gives safety or protects from danger."
      ]
    },
    "192": {
      "play": "That scald’st with safety. By his gates of breath",
      "notes": [
        "gates of breath] RANN (ed. 1789): Lips."
      ]
    },
    "193": {
      "play": "There lies a downy feather which stirs not;",
      "notes": [
        "feather] Cf. Lear v.iii.265.",
        "stirs not] SIGISMUND (Jahrbuch xvi, 1881, p. 88): The symptom here described ... is known as the Cheyne-Stokes respiration phenomenon. Instead of the regular cycle of respiration, repeated according to a fixed rhythm, the breathing stops after an expiration and often for a very long time. Such a delusion as Prince Henry here experiences is easily possible for an inexperienced observer so long as he does not wait for a new inhalation."
      ]
    },
    "194": {
      "play": "Did he suspire, that light and weightless down",
      "notes": [
        "suspire] N.E.D. (Suspire v. 3): To breathe. [Quotes no examples earlier than Mrs. Browning except John iii.iv.80 and this line.]"
      ]
    },
    "195": {
      "play": "Perforce must move. My gracious lord, my father,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "196": {
      "play": "This sleep is sound indeed. This is a sleep",
      "notes": []
    },
    "197": {
      "play": "That from this golden rigol hath divorced",
      "notes": [
        "rigol] GILDON (1710, p. lxxi): A Clavicord, or what makes Merry, or diverts, &c.—POPE (ed. 1723): Circle; meaning the crown.—THEOBALD (ed. 1733): I.e. Ring, or Circle. In Macbeth [I.v.25], he has express'd it; \"All that impedes thee from the golden round.\" But We once more meet with the Word Rigol in our Author's Works; \"About the mourning and congealed face Of that black blood a watery rigol goes,\" &c. Tarquin and Lucrece .—N.E.D. (Rigol sb. 1): A ring or circle. Obs. rare. App. derived from the application of the word to a groove running round a thing. [Quotes this line and Lucrece 1745 only.]"
      ]
    },
    "198": {
      "play": "So many English kings. Thy due from me",
      "notes": [
        "kings] There is certainly a distinct pause after this word, probably to be"
      ]
    },
    "199": {
      "play": "Is tears and heavy sorrows of the blood,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "200": {
      "play": "Which nature, love, and filial tenderness",
      "notes": [
        "nature] N.E.D. (Nature sb. 9e): Natural feeling or affection. Now dial. [Quotes Macbeth I.v.42 as its earliest example.]—[Cf. I. 77 below.]"
      ]
    },
    "201": {
      "play": "Shall, O dear father, pay thee plenteously.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "202": {
      "play": "My due from thee is this imperial crown,",
      "notes": [
        "imperial] N.E.D. (Imperial a. 2): Of or pertaining to a sovereign state."
      ]
    },
    "203": {
      "play": "Which, as immediate from thy place and blood,",
      "notes": [
        "immediate] N.E.D. (Immediate a.): Standing or coming nearest or next [quoting Hamlet I.ii.109, “You are the most immediate to our throne”, as its earliest example].—[Cf. V.ii.79.]—DELIUS (ed. 1857): Belongs with the following to me.",
        "Derives] SCHMIDT (1874): Reflectively, = to be inherited, to descend."
      ]
    },
    "204": {
      "play": "Derives itself to me. He puts on the crown. Lo,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "205": {
      "play": "where it sits,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "206": {
      "play": "Which God shall guard. And, put the world’s whole",
      "notes": []
    },
    "207": {
      "play": "strength",
      "notes": []
    },
    "208": {
      "play": "Into one giant arm, it shall not force",
      "notes": []
    },
    "209": {
      "play": "This lineal honor from me. This from thee",
      "notes": []
    },
    "210": {
      "play": "Will I to mine leave, as ’tis left to me.",
      "notes": [
        "Were] On the use of the subjunctive see FRANZ (3 ed., 1924) §648. Cf. v.iv.16."
      ]
    },
    "211": {
      "play": "He exits with the crown.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "212": {
      "play": "KING, rising up in his bed  Warwick! Gloucester!",
      "notes": []
    },
    "213": {
      "play": "Clarence!",
      "notes": []
    },
    "214": {
      "play": "[Enter Warwick, Gloucester, Clarence, and others.]",
      "notes": []
    },
    "215": {
      "play": "THOMAS OF CLARENCE: Doth the King call?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "216": {
      "play": "WARWICK: What would your Majesty? How fares your Grace?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "217": {
      "play": "KING: Why did you leave me here alone, my lords?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "218": {
      "play": "THOMAS OF CLARENCE: We left the Prince my brother here, my liege,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "219": {
      "play": "Who undertook to sit and watch by you.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "220": {
      "play": "KING: The Prince of Wales? Where is he? Let me see him.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "221": {
      "play": "He is not here.",
      "notes": [
        "He is not here.] Q he is not here, in the opinion of CAPELL (Notes, 1779, p. 180) and of WHITE (ed. 1859), was omitted from F by accident. A. E. MORGAN (1924, p. 22), who regards the phrase as “a fragment” indicating abridgement (see p. 496), implies that the omission was deliberate. Either explanation is possible, though the former involves the coincidence that the accident reduced the speech to a normal verse. Whether the F reviser was capable of going so far as to omit a few words to improve the meter is a question I find very difficult to answer.—ED."
      ]
    },
    "222": {
      "play": "WARWICK: This door is open. He is gone this way.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "223": {
      "play": "HUMPHREY OF GLOUCESTER: He came not through the chamber where we",
      "notes": []
    },
    "224": {
      "play": "stayed.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "225": {
      "play": "KING: Where is the crown? Who took it from my pillow?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "226": {
      "play": "WARWICK: When we withdrew, my liege, we left it here.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "227": {
      "play": "KING: The Prince hath ta’en it hence. Go seek him out.",
      "notes": [
        "That] So that. See note on I.i.198."
      ]
    },
    "228": {
      "play": "Is he so hasty that he doth suppose my sleep my",
      "notes": [
        "hasty] N.E.D. (Hasty a. 2): Eager to get something done quickly; in a hurry. Obs. [Quotes this line.]"
      ]
    },
    "229": {
      "play": "death?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "230": {
      "play": "Find him, my Lord of Warwick. Chide him hither.",
      "notes": [
        "Chide] N.E.D. (Chide v. 4): With adv. or advb. compl.: To drive, impel, or compel by chiding."
      ]
    },
    "231": {
      "play": "[Warwick exits.]",
      "notes": []
    },
    "232": {
      "play": "This part of his conjoins with my disease",
      "notes": []
    },
    "233": {
      "play": "And helps to end me. See, sons, what things you",
      "notes": []
    },
    "234": {
      "play": "are,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "235": {
      "play": "How quickly nature falls into revolt",
      "notes": [
        "power] See note on i.i.149.",
        "things] According to N.E.D. (Thing sb. 10), this word was formerly applied to persons without the contemptuous connotations which it now has. Surely, however, there is some reproach in it here, though none of the scorn which it expresses in v.iv.35.—Ed."
      ]
    },
    "236": {
      "play": "When gold becomes her object!",
      "notes": [
        "nature] See note on I. 43 above.",
        "gold] The king is thinking of the crown. Clemen (Jahrbuch lxviii, 1932, p. 71) points out the frequent association of crown and gold in Sh.’s mind.—Ed."
      ]
    },
    "237": {
      "play": "For this the foolish overcareful fathers",
      "notes": [
        "For this] RANN (ed. 1789): For such a return as this."
      ]
    },
    "238": {
      "play": "Have broke their sleep with thoughts,",
      "notes": [
        "thoughts] ONIONS (1911): Care[s], anxiet[ies].—[Cf. thoughtful, l. 84.]"
      ]
    },
    "239": {
      "play": "Their brains with care, their bones with industry.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "240": {
      "play": "For this they have engrossèd and piled up",
      "notes": [
        "broke] See note on i.i.16.",
        "engrossèd] N.E.D. (Engross v. 4a): To get together, collect from all quarters; also to engross up (obs.)."
      ]
    },
    "241": {
      "play": "The cankered heaps of strange-achievèd gold.",
      "notes": [
        "cankered] N.E.D. (Cankered ppl.a. 2): Rusted, corroded; tarnished. Obs. exc. dial. [Quotes this line.]",
        "strange-achievèd] SCHMIDT (1875): Gained and yet not enjoyed; acquired not for one’s own self, but for the benefit of others.—ROLFE (ed. 1880): May be=gained in foreign lands.—DEIGHTON (ed. 1893): [Amassed by] crooked means.—Miss WINSTANLEY (ed. 1918): Got by strange means.—ONIONS (1911): Gained (a) in foreign lands, (b) by wrong means, (c) for the enjoyment of others [marking the sense disputed].—COWL (ed. 1923): Strangely won, whether (1) in distant lands, (2) in extraordinary ways, or (3) by arts or means beyond the reach of ordinary men.—KITTRIDGE (ed. 1936, glossary): Acquired by extraordinary efforts or in foreign lands."
      ]
    },
    "242": {
      "play": "For this they have been thoughtful to invest",
      "notes": [
        "thoughtful] N.E.D. (Thoughtful a. 1c): With inf., dependent cl., or of: Careful, heedful [quoting this line].—[Cf. thoughts, l. 80.]"
      ]
    },
    "243": {
      "play": "Their sons with arts and martial exercises—",
      "notes": [
        "invest] See note on iv.iv.8."
      ]
    },
    "244": {
      "play": "When, like the bee, tolling from every flower",
      "notes": [
        "arts ... exercises] COWL (ed. 1923): Arts and arms, the two branches of a polite education in the sixteenth century.",
        "tolling] SCHMIDT (1874): Cull, to pick out, to select from many.—Q toling. ONIONS (1911): Toll, to take as toll, collect.—VERPLANCK (ed. 1847) thinks that Sh. first wrote this passage as it is printed in Q (without The vertuous Sweetes) and afterwards revised and expanded it.—COLLIER (ed. 1842) thinks that by the change to culling the image of the bee taking toll from each flower is lost.—HUDSON (ed. 1852) notes that The vertuous Sweetes would not suit toling and so agrees with Verplanck.—COWL (ed. 1923) and RIDLEY (ed. 1934) also think that the change of toling to culling and the addition of The vertuous Sweetes go together.—See note on I.i.119 and p. 507."
      ]
    },
    "245": {
      "play": "The virtuous sweets,",
      "notes": [
        "virtuous] N.E.D. (Virtuous a. 6): Endowed with, or possessed of, inherent or natural virtue or power."
      ]
    },
    "246": {
      "play": "Our thighs packed with wax, our mouths with",
      "notes": [
        "our ... wax] Difficult to read rhythmically, whether the line begins with The vertuous and ends with Wax, as in F, or begins with our Thighes and ends with Honey, as in Q and most modern editions. HERFORD (ed. 1899) and VAN DAM (1900, p. 346) would read Thighes as a dissyllable; ABBOTT (1870, §510) would read packed for packt; and COLLINS (ed. 1927) suggests a pause equivalent to a syllable after packt."
      ]
    },
    "247": {
      "play": "honey,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "248": {
      "play": "We bring it to the hive and, like the bees,",
      "notes": [
        "murdered] COLLINS (ed. 1927): As the bees are by those who want to get the honey; not by the other bees, for, as Shakespeare knew, it is not the working bees, but the “lazy yawning drone” (Henry V I.ii.204) who is delivered “o’er to executors pale” and killed."
      ]
    },
    "249": {
      "play": "Are murdered for our pains. This bitter taste",
      "notes": []
    },
    "250": {
      "play": "Yields his engrossments to the ending father.",
      "notes": [
        "Yields] CLARKE (ed. 1865): The construction is—‘his engrossments yield to the father this bitter taste’.—[See note on I.iii.114.]",
        "engrossments] JOHNSON (ed. 1765): Accumulations.—N.E.D. quotes this line as its earliest example.",
        "ending] N.E.D. (Ending ppl.a. 2): In intr. sense: Dying, near one’s end. Obs. [Quotes this line only.]"
      ]
    },
    "251": {
      "play": "[Enter Warwick.]",
      "notes": []
    },
    "252": {
      "play": "Now where is he that will not stay so long",
      "notes": []
    },
    "253": {
      "play": "Till his friend sickness hath determined me?",
      "notes": [
        "determined] SCHMIDT (1874): Put an end to."
      ]
    },
    "254": {
      "play": "WARWICK: My lord, I found the Prince in the next room,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "255": {
      "play": "Washing with kindly tears his gentle cheeks,",
      "notes": [
        "kindly] SCHMIDT (1874): In keeping with the quality of a person or thing, natural (not feigned).—HUDSON (ed. 1880): “Kindly tears” are tears of natural affection.—ONIONS (1911): (a) Natural, not forced, (b) naturally shed for a father [disputed]."
      ]
    },
    "256": {
      "play": "With such a deep demeanor in great sorrow",
      "notes": []
    },
    "257": {
      "play": "That tyranny, which never quaffed but blood,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "258": {
      "play": "Would, by beholding him, have washed his knife",
      "notes": []
    },
    "259": {
      "play": "With gentle eyedrops. He is coming hither.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "260": {
      "play": "KING: But wherefore did he take away the crown?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "261": {
      "play": "[Enter Prince Harry with the crown.]",
      "notes": []
    },
    "262": {
      "play": "Lo where he comes.—Come hither to me, Harry.—",
      "notes": [
        "Lo where] See note on l. 47 above."
      ]
    },
    "263": {
      "play": "Depart the chamber. Leave us here alone.",
      "notes": [
        "] Cf. The Famous Victories, sc. viii (p. 524 below)."
      ]
    },
    "264": {
      "play": "[Gloucester, Clarence, Warwick, and others exit.]",
      "notes": [
        "Depart] N.E.D. (Depart v. 8): trans. To go away from, leave, quit, forsake. Now rare.",
        "] Mitford (Gentleman’s Magazine xxii, 1844, p. 455) compares Quintilian, Institutio Oratoria VI. ii. \"sed id quod volunt credunt quoque\" [“what they wish, they will also believe” (tr. Butler, 1921)]."
      ]
    },
    "265": {
      "play": "PRINCE: I never thought to hear you speak again.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "266": {
      "play": "KING: Thy wish was father, Harry, to that thought.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "267": {
      "play": "I stay too long by thee; I weary thee.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "268": {
      "play": "Dost thou so hunger for mine empty chair",
      "notes": [
        "by thee] Delius (ed. 1857): In your opinion, the French selon toi. [So also Schmidt (1874), Rolfe (ed. 1880), Herford (ed. 1899).]—Rolfe: But by may be = near or with.—Cowl (ed. 1923): With [thee].",
        "empty chair] DEIGHTON (ed. 1893): Proleptic, the chair that will be emptied by my death.—MISS PORTER (ed. 1911): The Throne."
      ]
    },
    "269": {
      "play": "That thou wilt needs invest thee with my honors",
      "notes": []
    },
    "270": {
      "play": "Before thy hour be ripe? O foolish youth,",
      "notes": [
        "wilt needs] See note on i.iii.198.",
        "honors] N.E.D. (Honour sb. 5): (Usually in pl.) A position or title of rank, a degree of nobility, a dignity."
      ]
    },
    "271": {
      "play": "Thou seek’st the greatness that will overwhelm",
      "notes": []
    },
    "272": {
      "play": "thee.",
      "notes": [
        "deep] SCHMIDT (1874): Coming from, or dwelling in the inmost heart, heartfelt; and therefore intense. —[Cf. 1.155 below.]",
        "be] See note on i.iii.25."
      ]
    },
    "273": {
      "play": "Stay but a little, for my cloud of dignity",
      "notes": []
    },
    "274": {
      "play": "Is held from falling with so weak a wind",
      "notes": [
        "with] By. See note on ii.i.22."
      ]
    },
    "275": {
      "play": "That it will quickly drop. My day is dim.",
      "notes": [
        "is dim] DEIGHTON (ed. 1893): Begins to set in darkness."
      ]
    },
    "276": {
      "play": "Thou hast stol’n that which after some few hours",
      "notes": []
    },
    "277": {
      "play": "Were thine without offense, and at my death",
      "notes": []
    },
    "278": {
      "play": "Thou hast sealed up my expectation.",
      "notes": [
        "sealed ... expectation] JOHNSON (ed. 1765): Confirmed my opinion.—ROLFE (ed. 1880): Up has an intensive force.—[Expectation has five syllables.]"
      ]
    },
    "279": {
      "play": "Thy life did manifest thou loved’st me not,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "280": {
      "play": "And thou wilt have me die assured of it.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "281": {
      "play": "Thou hid’st a thousand daggers in thy thoughts,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "282": {
      "play": "Whom thou hast whetted on thy stony heart",
      "notes": [
        "whetted on thy stony heart] Cf. Richard III iv.iv.227: “No doubt the murderous knife was dull and blunt, Till it was whetted on thy stone-hard heart”.—ED.—ROLFE (ed. 1880) quotes Merchant iv.i.123: “Not on thy sole, but on thy soul, harsh Jew, Thou makest thy knife keen”.—Miss PORTER (ed. 1911): Perhaps suggested by an earlier incident, unused otherwise by Shakespeare, and told by Holinshed [p. 539 below]."
      ]
    },
    "283": {
      "play": "To stab at half an hour of my life.",
      "notes": [
        "hour] STEEVENS (Var. ’73) notes that the word is dissyllabic. He also calls attention to the spelling of Q, hower, which also occurs in the next line, where the word may again be pronounced in two syllables. At ll. 110 and 115 the spelling of Q is howre and houres."
      ]
    },
    "284": {
      "play": "What, canst thou not forbear me half an hour?",
      "notes": [
        "forbear ... hour] It is uncertain whether halfe an howre is the object of forbeare or an adverbial phrase. If it is the object, forbeare means to spare; if it is adverbial, forbeare means to let alone."
      ]
    },
    "285": {
      "play": "Then get thee gone, and dig my grave thyself,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "286": {
      "play": "And bid the merry bells ring to thine ear",
      "notes": []
    },
    "287": {
      "play": "That thou art crownèd, not that I am dead.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "288": {
      "play": "Let all the tears that should bedew my hearse",
      "notes": [
        "hearse] SCHMIDT (1874): A coffin on a bier."
      ]
    },
    "289": {
      "play": "Be drops of balm to sanctify thy head;",
      "notes": [
        "balm] SCHMIDT (1874): Ointment serving to anoint kings.",
        "sanctify] N.E.D. (Sanctify v. 1): To consecrate (a king, etc.). Obs. [Quotes this line.]",
        "is] See note on I.i.8."
      ]
    },
    "290": {
      "play": "Only compound me with forgotten dust.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "291": {
      "play": "Give that which gave thee life unto the worms.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "292": {
      "play": "Pluck down my officers, break my decrees,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "293": {
      "play": "For now a time is come to mock at form.",
      "notes": [
        "form] N.E.D. (Form sb. 15): Behaviour according to prescribed or customary rules; observance of etiquette, ceremony, or decorum."
      ]
    },
    "294": {
      "play": "Harry the Fifth is crowned. Up, vanity,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "295": {
      "play": "Down, royal state, all you sage councillors,",
      "notes": [
        "state] SCHMIDT (1875): High place; power; greatness; majesty.—COWL (ed. 1923): Dignified ceremonial, pomp."
      ]
    },
    "296": {
      "play": "hence,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "297": {
      "play": "And to the English court assemble now,",
      "notes": [
        "to] See ABBOTT (1870) §187, FRANZ (3 ed., 1924) §522."
      ]
    },
    "298": {
      "play": "From every region, apes of idleness.",
      "notes": [
        "idleness] SCHMIDT (1874): Frivolousness, want of gravity, vanity."
      ]
    },
    "299": {
      "play": "Now, neighbor confines, purge you of your scum.",
      "notes": [
        "confines] N.E.D. (Confine sb.² 2): Region, territory. Rarely in sing. Obs."
      ]
    },
    "300": {
      "play": "Have you a ruffian that will swear, drink, dance,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "301": {
      "play": "Revel the night, rob, murder, and commit",
      "notes": []
    },
    "302": {
      "play": "The oldest sins the newest kind of ways?",
      "notes": [
        "the newest ... ways] See note on II.ii.23."
      ]
    },
    "303": {
      "play": "Be happy, he will trouble you no more.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "304": {
      "play": "England shall double gild his treble guilt.",
      "notes": [
        "] This quibble deeply disturbed the 18th-century editors and critics;"
      ]
    },
    "305": {
      "play": "England shall give him office, honor, might,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "306": {
      "play": "For the fifth Harry from curbed license plucks",
      "notes": [
        "Fifth] This old form of fifth occurs also at 1.144 below, v.iii.108, v.v.44, D.P.6, and in the head-title of the play. In Q it is also on the title-page."
      ]
    },
    "307": {
      "play": "The muzzle of restraint, and the wild dog",
      "notes": [
        "the wild dog] DELIUS (ed. 1857): What was just called curbd License."
      ]
    },
    "308": {
      "play": "Shall flesh his tooth on every innocent.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "309": {
      "play": "O my poor kingdom, sick with civil blows!",
      "notes": []
    },
    "310": {
      "play": "When that my care could not withhold thy riots,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "311": {
      "play": "What wilt thou do when riot is thy care?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "312": {
      "play": "O, thou wilt be a wilderness again,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "313": {
      "play": "Peopled with wolves, thy old inhabitants.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "314": {
      "play": "PRINCE, placing the crown on the pillow",
      "notes": []
    },
    "315": {
      "play": "O pardon me, my liege! But for my tears,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "316": {
      "play": "The moist impediments unto my speech,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "317": {
      "play": "I had forestalled this dear and deep rebuke",
      "notes": []
    },
    "318": {
      "play": "Ere you with grief had spoke and I had heard",
      "notes": []
    },
    "319": {
      "play": "The course of it so far. There is your crown,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "320": {
      "play": "And He that wears the crown immortally",
      "notes": []
    },
    "321": {
      "play": "Long guard it yours. He kneels. If I affect it",
      "notes": []
    },
    "322": {
      "play": "more",
      "notes": []
    },
    "323": {
      "play": "Than as your honor and as your renown,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "324": {
      "play": "Let me no more from this obedience rise,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "325": {
      "play": "Which my most inward true and duteous spirit",
      "notes": []
    },
    "326": {
      "play": "Teacheth this prostrate and exterior bending.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "327": {
      "play": "God witness with me, when I here came in",
      "notes": []
    },
    "328": {
      "play": "And found no course of breath within your Majesty,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "329": {
      "play": "How cold it struck my heart! If I do feign,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "330": {
      "play": "O, let me in my present wildness die",
      "notes": []
    },
    "331": {
      "play": "And never live to show th’ incredulous world",
      "notes": []
    },
    "332": {
      "play": "The noble change that I have purposèd.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "333": {
      "play": "Coming to look on you, thinking you dead,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "334": {
      "play": "And dead almost, my liege, to think you were,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "335": {
      "play": "I spake unto this crown as having sense,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "336": {
      "play": "And thus upbraided it: “The care on thee",
      "notes": []
    },
    "337": {
      "play": "depending",
      "notes": []
    },
    "338": {
      "play": "Hath fed upon the body of my father;",
      "notes": []
    },
    "339": {
      "play": "Therefore thou best of gold art worst of gold.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "340": {
      "play": "Other, less fine in carat, is more precious,",
      "notes": [
        "other] See note on iii.ii.125, and FRANZ (3 ed., 1924) §329."
      ]
    },
    "341": {
      "play": "Preserving life in med’cine potable;",
      "notes": []
    },
    "342": {
      "play": "But thou, most fine, most honored, most renowned,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "343": {
      "play": "Hast eat thy bearer up.” Thus, my most royal liege,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "344": {
      "play": "Accusing it, I put it on my head",
      "notes": []
    },
    "345": {
      "play": "To try with it, as with an enemy",
      "notes": []
    },
    "346": {
      "play": "That had before my face murdered my father,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "347": {
      "play": "The quarrel of a true inheritor.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "348": {
      "play": "But if it did infect my blood with joy",
      "notes": []
    },
    "349": {
      "play": "Or swell my thoughts to any strain of pride,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "350": {
      "play": "If any rebel or vain spirit of mine",
      "notes": []
    },
    "351": {
      "play": "Did with the least affection of a welcome",
      "notes": []
    },
    "352": {
      "play": "Give entertainment to the might of it,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "353": {
      "play": "Let God forever keep it from my head",
      "notes": []
    },
    "354": {
      "play": "And make me as the poorest vassal is",
      "notes": []
    },
    "355": {
      "play": "That doth with awe and terror kneel to it.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "356": {
      "play": "KING: O my son,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "357": {
      "play": "God put it in thy mind to take it hence",
      "notes": []
    },
    "358": {
      "play": "That thou mightst win the more thy father’s love,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "359": {
      "play": "Pleading so wisely in excuse of it.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "360": {
      "play": "Come hither, Harry, sit thou by my bed",
      "notes": []
    },
    "361": {
      "play": "And hear, I think, the very latest counsel",
      "notes": []
    },
    "362": {
      "play": "That ever I shall breathe.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "363": {
      "play": "The Prince rises from his knees and sits",
      "notes": []
    },
    "364": {
      "play": "near the bed.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "365": {
      "play": "God knows, my son,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "366": {
      "play": "By what bypaths and indirect crook’d ways",
      "notes": []
    },
    "367": {
      "play": "I met this crown, and I myself know well",
      "notes": []
    },
    "368": {
      "play": "How troublesome it sat upon my head.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "369": {
      "play": "To thee it shall descend with better quiet,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "370": {
      "play": "Better opinion, better confirmation,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "371": {
      "play": "For all the soil of the achievement goes",
      "notes": []
    },
    "372": {
      "play": "With me into the earth. It seemed in me",
      "notes": []
    },
    "373": {
      "play": "But as an honor snatched with boist’rous hand,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "374": {
      "play": "And I had many living to upbraid",
      "notes": []
    },
    "375": {
      "play": "My gain of it by their assistances,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "376": {
      "play": "Which daily grew to quarrel and to bloodshed,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "377": {
      "play": "Wounding supposèd peace. All these bold fears",
      "notes": []
    },
    "378": {
      "play": "Thou seest with peril I have answerèd,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "379": {
      "play": "For all my reign hath been but as a scene",
      "notes": []
    },
    "380": {
      "play": "Acting that argument. And now my death",
      "notes": []
    },
    "381": {
      "play": "Changes the mood, for what in me was purchased",
      "notes": []
    },
    "382": {
      "play": "Falls upon thee in a more fairer sort.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "383": {
      "play": "So thou the garland wear’st successively.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "384": {
      "play": "Yet though thou stand’st more sure than I could do,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "385": {
      "play": "Thou art not firm enough, since griefs are green,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "386": {
      "play": "And all my friends, which thou must make thy",
      "notes": []
    },
    "387": {
      "play": "friends,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "388": {
      "play": "Have but their stings and teeth newly ta’en out,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "389": {
      "play": "By whose fell working I was first advanced",
      "notes": []
    },
    "390": {
      "play": "And by whose power I well might lodge a fear",
      "notes": []
    },
    "391": {
      "play": "To be again displaced; which to avoid,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "392": {
      "play": "I cut them off and had a purpose now",
      "notes": []
    },
    "393": {
      "play": "To lead out many to the Holy Land,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "394": {
      "play": "Lest rest and lying still might make them look",
      "notes": []
    },
    "395": {
      "play": "Too near unto my state. Therefore, my Harry,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "396": {
      "play": "Be it thy course to busy giddy minds",
      "notes": []
    },
    "397": {
      "play": "With foreign quarrels, that action, hence borne",
      "notes": []
    },
    "398": {
      "play": "out,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "399": {
      "play": "May waste the memory of the former days.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "400": {
      "play": "More would I, but my lungs are wasted so",
      "notes": []
    },
    "401": {
      "play": "That strength of speech is utterly denied me.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "402": {
      "play": "How I came by the crown, O God forgive,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "403": {
      "play": "And grant it may with thee in true peace live.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "404": {
      "play": "PRINCE: My gracious liege,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "405": {
      "play": "You won it, wore it, kept it, gave it me.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "406": {
      "play": "Then plain and right must my possession be,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "407": {
      "play": "Which I with more than with a common pain",
      "notes": []
    },
    "408": {
      "play": "’Gainst all the world will rightfully maintain.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "409": {
      "play": "[Enter John of Lancaster and others.]",
      "notes": []
    },
    "410": {
      "play": "KING: Look, look, here comes my John of Lancaster.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "411": {
      "play": "JOHN OF LANCASTER: Health, peace, and happiness to my royal father.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "412": {
      "play": "KING: Thou bring’st me happiness and peace, son John,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "413": {
      "play": "But health, alack, with youthful wings is flown",
      "notes": []
    },
    "414": {
      "play": "From this bare withered trunk. Upon thy sight",
      "notes": []
    },
    "415": {
      "play": "My worldly business makes a period.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "416": {
      "play": "Where is my Lord of Warwick?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "417": {
      "play": "PRINCE: My Lord of Warwick.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "418": {
      "play": "[Enter Warwick.]",
      "notes": []
    },
    "419": {
      "play": "KING: Doth any name particular belong",
      "notes": []
    },
    "420": {
      "play": "Unto the lodging where I first did swoon?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "421": {
      "play": "WARWICK: ’Tis called Jerusalem, my noble lord.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "422": {
      "play": "KING: Laud be to God! Even there my life must end.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "423": {
      "play": "It hath been prophesied to me many years,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "424": {
      "play": "I should not die but in Jerusalem,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "425": {
      "play": "Which vainly I supposed the Holy Land.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "426": {
      "play": "But bear me to that chamber; there I’ll lie.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "427": {
      "play": "In that Jerusalem shall Harry die.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "428": {
      "play": "[They exit.]",
      "notes": []
    }
