    "80": {
      "play": "that either wise bearing or ignorant carriage is",
      "notes": [
        "Carriage] N.E.D. (Carriage 14): Manner of conducting oneself socially; demeanour; deportment, behaviour. (Referring to manners.) arch. [Quotes Errors iii.ii.14, “Teach sin the carriage of a holy saint”.] take] N.E.D. (Take v. 44b): To contract (disease, infection, etc.) [quoting this line].—Moyes (1896, pp. 22 f.) quotes the following further allusions to infection and contagion: Dream i.i.186, Henry VIII i.iii.36–7, Coriolanus i.iv.33, Much Ado i.i.70–4. 83–6. I ... Interuallums] C. F. T. Brooke (Yale Review vii, 1918, p. 356): Falstaff’s life is a series of desperate escapes from boredom ... It is for this that he so carefully husbands Shallow.—Richardson (1789; 5 ed., 1797,"
      ]
    },
    "81": {
      "play": "caught, as men take diseases, one of another. Therefore",
      "notes": []
    },
    "82": {
      "play": "let men take heed of their company. I will",
      "notes": []
    },
    "83": {
      "play": "devise matter enough out of this Shallow to keep",
      "notes": []
    },
    "84": {
      "play": "Prince Harry in continual laughter the wearing out",
      "notes": []
    },
    "85": {
      "play": "of six fashions, which is four terms, or two actions,",
      "notes": [
        "Tearmes] CAMPBELL (1859, p. 88): As there are four terms in the legal year,—Michaelmas Term, Hilary Term, Easter Term, and Trinity Term—this is a legal circumlocution for a twelvemonth. 85-6. Actions] See note on II.i.3.—JOHNSON (ed. 1765): There is something humorous in making a spendthrift compute time by the operation of an action for debt."
      ]
    },
    "86": {
      "play": "and he shall laugh without intervallums. O, it is",
      "notes": [
        "Intervallums] DELIUS (ed. 1857): The intervals between the various terms and actions are to be understood. Hence the Latin expression. 87-8. a Lye ... brow] CLARKE (ed. 1865): We may gather from this that Falstaff enhanced the effect of some of his jokes by staid utterance and a quiet, dry manner; but others, be sure, he accompanied by a broad roar; and all with a twinkle of his eye that spoke volumes."
      ]
    },
    "87": {
      "play": "much that a lie with a slight oath and a jest with a",
      "notes": []
    },
    "88": {
      "play": "sad brow will do with a fellow that never had the",
      "notes": [
        "sadde] SCHMIDT (1875): Grave, serious. 88-9. a Fellow ... shoulders] JOHNSON (ed. 1765): That is, a young fellow, one whose disposition to merriment, time and pain have not yet impaired.—C.F.T. BROOKE (Yale Review vii, 1918, p. 356): Falstaff thinks with rueful envy of the capacity of romantic youth for sensation."
      ]
    },
    "89": {
      "play": "ache in his shoulders. O, you shall see him laugh till",
      "notes": [
        "you shall see] CLARKE (Sh. Key, 1879, p. 708): One form [of soliloquy] is as if the speaker were addressing an imaginary auditor."
      ]
    },
    "90": {
      "play": "his face be like a wet cloak ill laid up.",
      "notes": [
        "be] See note on I.iii.25. ill laid vp] RANN (ed. 1789): Full of wrinkles."
      ]
    },
    "91": {
      "play": "SHALLOW, within  Sir John.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "92": {
      "play": "FALSTAFF: I come, Master Shallow, I come, Master",
      "notes": []
    },
    "93": {
      "play": "Shallow.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "94": {
      "play": "[He exits.]",
      "notes": []
    }
  },
  "ACT 5, SCENE 2": {
    "1": {
      "play": "[Enter Warwick and Lord Chief Justice.]",
      "notes": []
    },
    "2": {
      "play": "WARWICK: How now, my Lord Chief Justice, whither away?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "3": {
      "play": "CHIEF JUSTICE: How doth the King?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "4": {
      "play": "WARWICK: Exceeding well. His cares are now all ended.",
      "notes": [
        "well] Schmidt (1875): Used of the dead, = at rest, free from the cares of the world.—Cf. Romeo IV.v.76, quoted by Rolfe (ed. 1880); Winter's Tale v.i.30, quoted by Clarke (ed. 1865); Antony II.v.33, quoted by Deighton (ed. 1893). Noble (1935, p. 150) quotes 2 Kings iv. 26, where the Shunamite woman, going to Elisha to implore his help in restoring her son's life, says, \"Al is wel\"."
      ]
    },
    "5": {
      "play": "CHIEF JUSTICE: I hope, not dead.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "6": {
      "play": "WARWICK: He’s walked the way of nature,",
      "notes": [
        "way of nature] N.E.D. (Way sb.1 7c): In the Bible phrase to go the way",
        "] This verse seems to lack a syllable, which G. KÖNIG (1888, p. 61) would compensate for by lengthening Warwick."
      ]
    },
    "7": {
      "play": "And to our purposes he lives no more.",
      "notes": [
        "to our purposes] DEIGHTON (ed. 1893): So far as we are concerned.—See FRANZ (3 ed., 1924) §525, who quotes Sonnet cxxvi. 7, “She keeps thee to this purpose”, Merry Wives II.ii.198, “To what purpose have you unfolded this to me?”"
      ]
    },
    "8": {
      "play": "CHIEF JUSTICE: I would his Majesty had called me with him.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "9": {
      "play": "The service that I truly did his life",
      "notes": [
        "truly] See note on V.i.52.",
        "] On the Q stage-direction see p. 490. On the F stage-direction see pp. 512 ff."
      ]
    },
    "10": {
      "play": "Hath left me open to all injuries.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "11": {
      "play": "WARWICK: Indeed, I think the young king loves you not.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "12": {
      "play": "CHIEF JUSTICE: I know he doth not, and do arm myself",
      "notes": []
    },
    "13": {
      "play": "To welcome the condition of the time,",
      "notes": [
        "condition of the time] See note on III.i.81."
      ]
    },
    "14": {
      "play": "Which cannot look more hideously upon me",
      "notes": []
    },
    "15": {
      "play": "Than I have drawn it in my fantasy.",
      "notes": [
        "fantasy] SCHMIDT (1874): Imagination, the power of imagining."
      ]
    },
    "16": {
      "play": "[Enter John, Thomas, and Humphrey.]",
      "notes": []
    },
    "17": {
      "play": "WARWICK: Here come the heavy issue of dead Harry.",
      "notes": [
        "heavy] See note on I.ii.137, and cf. ll. 22, 32, 33, 34."
      ]
    },
    "18": {
      "play": "O, that the living Harry had the temper",
      "notes": [
        "temper] See note on I.ii.171."
      ]
    },
    "19": {
      "play": "Of he the worst of these three gentlemen!",
      "notes": [
        "he] RIDLEY (ed. 1934): Q Of he, which may be a mishearing of Of e’en, which would be more pointed.—[Perhaps Q he is not an error: cf. Tempest I.ii.27, “Which, of he or Adrian, for a good wager, first begins to crow?”—Ed.]"
      ]
    },
    "20": {
      "play": "How many nobles then should hold their places",
      "notes": []
    },
    "21": {
      "play": "That must strike sail to spirits of vile sort!",
      "notes": [
        "strike sail] ONIONS (1911): To lower (sail), only fig.—LAUGHTON (Sh.’s England, 1916, i. 162): A sail may be struck ... in ... submission.",
        "spirits] N.E.D. (Spirit sb. 9): A person considered in relation to his character or disposition; one who has a spirit of a specified nature.",
        "vile] N.E.D. (Vile a. 2): Of persons: Of a low, base, or despicable character; morally depraved or degraded."
      ]
    },
    "22": {
      "play": "CHIEF JUSTICE: O God, I fear all will be overturned.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "23": {
      "play": "JOHN OF LANCASTER: Good morrow, cousin Warwick, good morrow.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "24": {
      "play": "HUMPHREY OF GLOUCESTER, THOMAS OF CLARENCE  Good morrow, cousin.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "25": {
      "play": "JOHN OF LANCASTER: We meet like men that had forgot to speak.",
      "notes": [
        "forgot] N.E.D. (Forget v. 3c): To forget to do = to forget how to do (something). Obs."
      ]
    },
    "26": {
      "play": "WARWICK: We do remember, but our argument",
      "notes": [
        "argument] See note on IV.v.215."
      ]
    },
    "27": {
      "play": "Is all too heavy to admit much talk.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "28": {
      "play": "JOHN OF LANCASTER: Well, peace be with him that hath made us heavy.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "29": {
      "play": "CHIEF JUSTICE: Peace be with us, lest we be heavier.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "30": {
      "play": "HUMPHREY OF GLOUCESTER: O, good my lord, you have lost a friend indeed,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "31": {
      "play": "And I dare swear you borrow not that face",
      "notes": []
    },
    "32": {
      "play": "Of seeming sorrow; it is sure your own.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "33": {
      "play": "JOHN OF LANCASTER, to the Chief Justice",
      "notes": []
    },
    "34": {
      "play": "Though no man be assured what grace to find,",
      "notes": [
        "grace] See note on I.ii.28."
      ]
    },
    "35": {
      "play": "You stand in coldest expectation.",
      "notes": [
        "coldest] N.E.D. (Cold a. 9): fig. Gloomy, dispiriting, deadening."
      ]
    },
    "36": {
      "play": "I am the sorrier; would ’twere otherwise.",
      "notes": [
        "'twere] Subjunctive after a verb of wishing. See FRANZ (3 ed., 1924) §647."
      ]
    },
    "37": {
      "play": "THOMAS OF CLARENCE: Well, you must now speak Sir John Falstaff fair,",
      "notes": [
        "] RITSON (apud Steevens, ed. 1793, viii. 595): \"You must now speak Sir John Oldcastle fair\"—[See note on II.iv.365.]",
        "speak fair] N.E.D. (Speak v. 33): To speak (one) fair, to address (a person) courteously or kindly."
      ]
    },
    "38": {
      "play": "Which swims against your stream of quality.",
      "notes": [
        "] ROLFE (ed. 1880): A metaphor equivalent to \"[which] goes against your grain.\"—[Quality = character (N.E.D., Quality sb. 1). Your refers to Quality; see ABBOTT (1870) §423.]"
      ]
    },
    "39": {
      "play": "CHIEF JUSTICE: Sweet princes, what I did I did in honor,",
      "notes": [
        "in honor] N.E.D. (Honour sb. 9b): In honour: in allegiance to the moral principles which are imperative in one's position; as a moral bounden duty."
      ]
    },
    "40": {
      "play": "Led by th’ impartial conduct of my soul;",
      "notes": [
        "impartial] In the sense imperious, this is intelligible, but it is probably a misreading of Q impartiall. Perhaps the fact that impartial was a new word (N.E.D. quotes no example earlier than Sh.) fostered the mistake. See p. 507.",
        "conduct] N.E.D. (Conduct sb.1 3): A guide, leader, conductor (figuratively). Obs."
      ]
    },
    "41": {
      "play": "And never shall you see that I will beg",
      "notes": []
    },
    "42": {
      "play": "A ragged and forestalled remission.",
      "notes": [
        "ragged] HEATH (1765, p. 264): It means a remission which hath a mean and scandalous appearance.—JOHNSON (ed. 1765): Ragged, in our author's licentious diction, may easily signify beggarly, mean, base, ignominious.—VERPLANCK (ed. 1847): Contemptible.—CLARKE (ed. 1865): 'Base,' 'worth-",
        "forestalled remission] Q forestald.—JOHNSON (ed. 1765): Perhaps ... he may mean a pardon begged by a voluntary confession of offence, and anticipation of the charge.—MASON (1785, pp. 195 f.): The same expression occurs in two different passages in Massinger. In the Duke of Milan [ed. T. W. Baldwin, 1918, III.i.152], Sforza says to the Emperor, “Nor come I as a Slaue, Falling before thy Feet, kneeling and howling, For a forestal’d remission.” And in the Bond Man [ed. B. T. Spencer, 1932, III.iii.169], Pisander says, “better expose Our naked breasts to their keene Swords, and sell Our liues with the most advantage, then to trust In a forestal’d remission, or yeeld vp Our bodies to the furnace of their furie.” In all these passages, a forestal’d remission seems to mean, a remission that it is pre-determined, shall not be granted, or will be rendered nugatory.—MALONE (ed. 1790): I believe, forestall’d only means asked before it is granted. If he will grant me a pardon unasked, so; if not, I will not condescend to solicit it.—COLLIER (ed. 1842): Perhaps means [a pardon] anticipated by the king before it is asked.—FIELD (Sh. Soc.’s Papers iii, 1847, pp. 140 f.): I believe that it was a custom in those times for courtiers to beg of the King a pardon for an offence, political or moral, before the offender should be impeached or arraigned; and this may very well be called “a forestall’d remission.”—KEIGHTLEY (Sh.-Expositor, 1867, p. 244): [A pardon] prevented by the efforts of his enemies.—SCHMIDT (1874): [A pardon] judge[d] beforehand, regard[ed] with prejudice.—J. HUNTER (quoted by Rolfe, ed. 1880): One which is precluded from being absolute, by the refusal of the offender to accuse or alter his conduct.—CROSBY (apud Hudson, ed. 1880): A remission for a deed that of itself forestalled any remission.—O. F. ADAMS (Irving ed., 1888): Perhaps ... “a pardon the terms of which have been settled before my defence has been heard.”—DEIGHTON (ed. 1893): Possibly the sense is “a pardon on conditions which I am prevented by honour from accepting”.—Mcilwraith (T.L.S. 19 Jany. 1933, p. 40): It is noteworthy that both times Massinger spells the word in the same way, forestal’d, with a single l, as does Q. This is a perfectly possible seventeenth-century spelling of forestalled, but I venture to suggest that we create unnecessary difficulties if we treat it as such, and that the word is in fact in modern spelling forestalled. The “New English Dictionary” has no example of the word forestale, but it comments on the frequency of stale in Shakespeare, and nonce-formations with the prefix fore- in the sense of “beforehand,” “previously,” are common. If this is the origin of Shakespeare’s coinage, the Lord Chief Justice’s expression will mean “a pardon rendered stale (or distasteful) before it is received, by the ignominy of begging it,” and this is just the sense required by the three passages in which it occurs.—[Other editors are about equally divided between Mason’s and Malone’s explanations. McIlwraith’s idea is very attractive.—ED.]",
        "remission] WHITE (ed. 1883): Four syllables."
      ]
    },
    "43": {
      "play": "If truth and upright innocency fail me,",
      "notes": [
        "truth] SCHMIDT (1875): Faith, honesty."
      ]
    },
    "44": {
      "play": "I’ll to the king my master that is dead",
      "notes": []
    },
    "45": {
      "play": "And tell him who hath sent me after him.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "46": {
      "play": "[Enter the Prince, as Henry V, and Blunt.]",
      "notes": []
    },
    "47": {
      "play": "WARWICK: Here comes the Prince.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "48": {
      "play": "CHIEF JUSTICE: Good morrow, and God save your Majesty.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "49": {
      "play": "PRINCE: This new and gorgeous garment majesty",
      "notes": []
    },
    "50": {
      "play": "Sits not so easy on me as you think.—",
      "notes": [
        "easy] See note on iii.1.33."
      ]
    },
    "51": {
      "play": "Brothers, you mix your sadness with some fear.",
      "notes": [
        "mix] Q mixt. If it is not possible for e to be misread as t, it is certainly possible for the compositor to read mixe as mixt and then, in setting up the word, to spell it phonetically mixt.—ED."
      ]
    },
    "52": {
      "play": "This is the English, not the Turkish court;",
      "notes": []
    },
    "53": {
      "play": "Not Amurath an Amurath succeeds,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "54": {
      "play": "But Harry Harry. Yet be sad, good brothers,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "55": {
      "play": "For, by my faith, it very well becomes you.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "56": {
      "play": "Sorrow so royally in you appears",
      "notes": []
    },
    "57": {
      "play": "That I will deeply put the fashion on",
      "notes": [
        "deeply] N.E.D. (Deeply adv. 3): With deep seriousness, solemnly. Obs."
      ]
    },
    "58": {
      "play": "And wear it in my heart. Why then, be sad.",
      "notes": [
        "wear] N.E.D. (Wear v.1 8): To carry about with one in one’s heart, mind, or memory. [Quotes Hamlet III.ii.71, “Give me that man That is not passion’s slave, and I will wear him In my heart’s core”.]"
      ]
    },
    "59": {
      "play": "But entertain no more of it, good brothers,",
      "notes": [
        "entertain] N.E.D. (Entertain v. 14c): To harbour; to cherish; in weaker sense, to experience (a sentiment). [Obs.]"
      ]
    },
    "60": {
      "play": "Than a joint burden laid upon us all.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "61": {
      "play": "For me, by heaven, I bid you be assured,",
      "notes": [
        "For me] N.E.D. (For conj. 26): The parenthetic use, as in for me = as for me, for my part, is now obsolete."
      ]
    },
    "62": {
      "play": "I’ll be your father and your brother too.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "63": {
      "play": "Let me but bear your love, I’ll bear your cares.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "64": {
      "play": "Yet weep that Harry’s dead, and so will I,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "65": {
      "play": "But Harry lives that shall convert those tears",
      "notes": []
    },
    "66": {
      "play": "By number into hours of happiness.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "67": {
      "play": "BROTHERS: We hope no otherwise from your Majesty.",
      "notes": [
        "hope] Hope for (N.E.D., Hope v. 3a).",
        "no otherwise] N.E.D. (Other pron. 7): no(ne) other, nothing else. Obs. or arch.—[Cf. I.ii.83.—With Q no otherwise cf. 1 Henry VI I.iii.10, “We do no otherwise than we are will’d”.]"
      ]
    },
    "68": {
      "play": "PRINCE: You all look strangely on me. To the Chief Justice.",
      "notes": [
        "strangely] N.E.D. (Strangely adv. 2): In an unfriendly or unfavourable manner; with cold or distant bearing. Obs."
      ]
    },
    "69": {
      "play": "And you most.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "70": {
      "play": "You are, I think, assured I love you not.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "71": {
      "play": "CHIEF JUSTICE: I am assured, if I be measured rightly,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "72": {
      "play": "Your Majesty hath no just cause to hate me.",
      "notes": [
        "hath] On the tense see note on I.iii.84."
      ]
    },
    "73": {
      "play": "PRINCE: No? How might a prince of my great hopes forget",
      "notes": [
        "No?] On the lineation see p. 510."
      ]
    },
    "74": {
      "play": "So great indignities you laid upon me?",
      "notes": [
        "] DEIGHTON (ed. 1893): Perhaps a confusion between ‘so great indignities laid upon me,’ and ‘the great indignities you laid upon me.’"
      ]
    },
    "75": {
      "play": "What, rate, rebuke, and roughly send to prison",
      "notes": [
        "rate] See note on iii.i.71."
      ]
    },
    "76": {
      "play": "Th’ immediate heir of England? Was this easy?",
      "notes": [
        "immediate] See note on iv.v.46.",
        "easy] N.E.D. (Easy a. 15): Of small ‘weight’ or importance, insignificance, slight. [Obs.]"
      ]
    },
    "77": {
      "play": "May this be washed in Lethe and forgotten?",
      "notes": [
        "washed in Lethe] Root (1903, p. 67): The allusions in Richard III [iv.iv.250-1] and 2 Henry IV would indicate that Shakespeare thinks of Lethe as ‘washing’ away or ‘drowning’ memory. In Vergil it is by drinking of the water that the souls win oblivion. But in the Divine Comedy, Purg. 31. 101, Beatrice submerges Dante in Lethe up to the head so that he may in that way swallow some of the water. The immersion is made more prominent than the drinking.—[Sh. is similarly wrong about Lethe at Twelfth Night iv.i.61.—ED.]"
      ]
    },
    "78": {
      "play": "CHIEF JUSTICE: I then did use the person of your father;",
      "notes": [
        "person] N.E.D. (Person sb. 1): A character sustained or assumed; hence, function, office, capacity. [Quotes Dream iii.i.54, “he comes to disfigure, or to present, the person of moonshine”.]"
      ]
    },
    "79": {
      "play": "The image of his power lay then in me.",
      "notes": [
        "image] N.E.D. (Image sb. 4b): A symbol, emblem, representation.—[Cf. l. 87 below.]"
      ]
    },
    "80": {
      "play": "And in th’ administration of his law,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "81": {
      "play": "Whiles I was busy for the commonwealth,",
      "notes": [
        "Whiles] See note on Ind. 16."
      ]
    },
    "82": {
      "play": "Your Highness pleasèd to forget my place,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "83": {
      "play": "The majesty and power of law and justice,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "84": {
      "play": "The image of the King whom I presented,",
      "notes": [
        "presented] N.E.D. (Present v. 7): To represent, to be the representative of."
      ]
    },
    "85": {
      "play": "And struck me in my very seat of judgment,",
      "notes": [
        "] RUSHTON (Sh. Illustrated by Old Authors, 1867, p. 4): Injuria illata judici, seu locum tenenti regis, videtur ipsi regi illata, maxime si fiat in exercitium officii.—COKE, 3 Inst. I. ... According to this maxim, an injury offered to a judge, or one holding the place of the king, is considered to be offered to the king himself, especially if done during the exercise of the office of a judge."
      ]
    },
    "86": {
      "play": "Whereon, as an offender to your father,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "87": {
      "play": "I gave bold way to my authority",
      "notes": [
        "gave ... way] N.E.D. (Give v. 49d): Give way. To allow free scope, opportunity, or liberty of action to [quoting this line].",
        "bold] DELIUS (ed. 1872): Exactly construed, this would modify gave way adverbially."
      ]
    },
    "88": {
      "play": "And did commit you. If the deed were ill,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "89": {
      "play": "Be you contented, wearing now the garland,",
      "notes": [
        "garland] See note on IV.v.218."
      ]
    },
    "90": {
      "play": "To have a son set your decrees at nought?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "91": {
      "play": "To pluck down justice from your awful bench?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "92": {
      "play": "To trip the course of law and blunt the sword",
      "notes": [
        "To trip the course of law] JOHNSON (ed. 1765): To defeat the process of justice, a metaphor taken from the act of tripping a runner."
      ]
    },
    "93": {
      "play": "That guards the peace and safety of your person?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "94": {
      "play": "Nay more, to spurn at your most royal image",
      "notes": []
    },
    "95": {
      "play": "And mock your workings in a second body?",
      "notes": [
        "workings] See note on IV.v.223.",
        "second] SCHMIDT (1874), CLARKE (Sh. Key, 1879, p. 588), and ONIONS (1911) explain this as = secondary, subordinate, but N.E.D. does not specifically bear them out.",
        "body] N.E.D. (Body sb. 13): Formerly exactly equivalent to the current ‘person’."
      ]
    },
    "96": {
      "play": "Question your royal thoughts, make the case yours;",
      "notes": []
    },
    "97": {
      "play": "Be now the father and propose a son,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "98": {
      "play": "Hear your own dignity so much profaned,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "99": {
      "play": "See your most dreadful laws so loosely slighted,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "100": {
      "play": "Behold yourself so by a son disdained,",
      "notes": [
        "propose] N.E.D. (Propose v. 2d): To contemplate as a supposition; to imagine, fancy: = Propound v. 5b. Obs. rare. [Quotes this line only.]",
        "disdained] Doubtfully erroneous: Sh. may have intended a feminine ending. See textual notes. —Ed."
      ]
    },
    "101": {
      "play": "And then imagine me taking your part",
      "notes": []
    },
    "102": {
      "play": "And in your power soft silencing your son.",
      "notes": [
        "soft] N.E.D. (Soft adv. 2b): Lightly, gently.",
        "silencing] N.E.D. (Silence v. 2): To reduce (a person, etc.) to silence by restraint or prohibition [quoting this line as its earliest example]."
      ]
    },
    "103": {
      "play": "After this cold considerance, sentence me,",
      "notes": [
        "cold] SCHMIDT (1874): Cool, deliberate.",
        "considerance] SCHMIDT (1874): Consideration, sober reflection. —[N.E.D. quotes this line as its last example.]"
      ]
    },
    "104": {
      "play": "And, as you are a king, speak in your state",
      "notes": [
        "state] N.E.D. (State sb. 16): A high rank or exalted position; an office of power or importance. Obs."
      ]
    },
    "105": {
      "play": "What I have done that misbecame my place,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "106": {
      "play": "My person, or my liege’s sovereignty.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "107": {
      "play": "PRINCE: You are right, justice, and you weigh this well.",
      "notes": [
        "right] MOUNT (9 N. & Q. iii, 1899, pp. 282 f.) argues in favor of omitting the comma after this word and understanding it as “the right, the true, the ideal”."
      ]
    },
    "108": {
      "play": "Therefore still bear the balance and the sword.",
      "notes": [
        "] J. M. RIGG (D.N.B., vii. 925): [The reappointment of the chief justice] is not only unfounded in, but is inconsistent with, historical fact. Gascoigne was indeed summoned as lord chief justice to the first parliament of",
        "balance] N.E.D. (Balance sb. 8): The metaphorical balance [scales] of justice."
      ]
    },
    "109": {
      "play": "And I do wish your honors may increase",
      "notes": []
    },
    "110": {
      "play": "Till you do live to see a son of mine",
      "notes": []
    },
    "111": {
      "play": "Offend you and obey you as I did.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "112": {
      "play": "So shall I live to speak my father’s words:",
      "notes": []
    },
    "113": {
      "play": "“Happy am I that have a man so bold",
      "notes": []
    },
    "114": {
      "play": "That dares do justice on my proper son;",
      "notes": [
        "proper] SCHMIDT (1875): (One’s) own.—[See FRANZ (3 ed., 1924) §704.]"
      ]
    },
    "115": {
      "play": "And not less happy, having such a son",
      "notes": []
    },
    "116": {
      "play": "That would deliver up his greatness so",
      "notes": []
    },
    "117": {
      "play": "Into the hands of justice.” You did commit me,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "118": {
      "play": "For which I do commit into your hand",
      "notes": []
    },
    "119": {
      "play": "Th’ unstainèd sword that you have used to bear,",
      "notes": [
        "used] Onions (1911): Use: to be accustomed to.—[See Franz (3 ed., 1924) §620.]"
      ]
    },
    "120": {
      "play": "With this remembrance: that you use the same",
      "notes": [
        "remembrance] N.E.D. (Remembrance sb. 8b): A reminder given by one person to another [quoting this line as its earliest example]."
      ]
    },
    "121": {
      "play": "With the like bold, just, and impartial spirit",
      "notes": []
    },
    "122": {
      "play": "As you have done ’gainst me. There is my hand.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "123": {
      "play": "They clasp hands.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "124": {
      "play": "You shall be as a father to my youth,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "125": {
      "play": "My voice shall sound as you do prompt mine ear,",
      "notes": [
        "sound] N.E.D. (Sound v.1 2b): To utter vocal sounds; to speak. Obs."
      ]
    },
    "126": {
      "play": "And I will stoop and humble my intents",
      "notes": [
        "stoop] Schmidt (1875): To humiliate, to subdue to."
      ]
    },
    "127": {
      "play": "To your well-practiced wise directions.—",
      "notes": []
    },
    "128": {
      "play": "And, princes all, believe me, I beseech you:",
      "notes": []
    },
    "129": {
      "play": "My father is gone wild into his grave,",
      "notes": [
        "] Theobald (ed. 1733): \"My Father, says the Prince, is gone wild into his Grave, for now all my wild Affections lye intomb’d with him\". [Cf. Henry V I.i.25–7, \"The breath no sooner left his father's body, But that his wildness, mortified in him, Seem’d to die too\".]—Malone (Var. '78): The meaning seems to be —My wild dispositions having ceased on my father's death, and being now as it were buried in his tomb, he and wildness are interred in the same grave. ... So, in Henry VIII [iii.i.94]: \"And when old time shall lead him to his end, Goodness and he fill up one monument!\""
      ]
    },
    "130": {
      "play": "For in his tomb lie my affections,",
      "notes": [
        "affections] See note on IV.iv.75."
      ]
    },
    "131": {
      "play": "And with his spirits sadly I survive",
      "notes": [
        "spirits] WALKER (Crit. Exam., 1860, i. 236) calls the final s an interpolation, and beyond doubt, with the preceding word ending in s and the following word beginning with s and the whole line hissing with sibilants, it may well be. Nevertheless, there is nothing unintelligible about spirits, and the plural is similarly used in Hamlet III.ii.56 and Antony V.ii.172.—Ed.",
        "sadly] JOHNSON (ed. 1765): Sadly is the same as soberly, seriously, gravely. Sad is opposed to wild."
      ]
    },
    "132": {
      "play": "To mock the expectation of the world,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "133": {
      "play": "To frustrate prophecies, and to raze out",
      "notes": [
        "raze] N.E.D. (Race v.3 3): To scrape out, erase. Obs. (Now written Rase or Raze.)"
      ]
    },
    "134": {
      "play": "Rotten opinion, who hath writ me down",
      "notes": [
        "opinion] See note on IV.v.204.—COWL (ed. 1923): Generally used by Elizabethan writers in a depreciatory sense, and as opposed to “reason” and “truth”.",
        "who] See note on III.i.24.",
        "writ] See note on I.i.16."
      ]
    },
    "135": {
      "play": "After my seeming. The tide of blood in me",
      "notes": [
        "After] ABBOTT (1870, §141): “Following,” Latin “secundum,” hence “according to”.",
        "blood] See note on IV.iv.44."
      ]
    },
    "136": {
      "play": "Hath proudly flowed in vanity till now.",
      "notes": [
        "proudly] N.E.D. (Proudly adv. 2): Grandly, magnificently, splendidly; with vigour or force [quoting this line]."
      ]
    },
    "137": {
      "play": "Now doth it turn and ebb back to the sea,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "138": {
      "play": "Where it shall mingle with the state of floods",
      "notes": [
        "the state of floods] WARBURTON (ed. 1747): I.e. the assembly, or general meeting of the floods.—MASON (1785, p. 196): State means dignity; and ... to mingle with the state of floods, is to partake of the dignity of floods.—SCHMIDT (1875): The majestic dignity of the ocean. [So also ONIONS.]"
      ]
    },
    "139": {
      "play": "And flow henceforth in formal majesty.",
      "notes": [
        "henceforth] G. KÖNIG (1888, p. 68) notes that the accent is on the second syllable."
      ]
    },
    "140": {
      "play": "Now call we our high court of parliament,",
      "notes": [
        "court] N.E.D. (Court sb.1): Applied to Parliament."
      ]
    },
    "141": {
      "play": "And let us choose such limbs of noble counsel",
      "notes": [
        "limbs] N.E.D. (Limb sb1 3a): A member. Obs. exc. in nonce-uses.—COWL (ed. 1923): The choice of the word in the text has been obviously influenced by the conception of a body politic (cf. the metaphor in the next line)."
      ]
    },
    "142": {
      "play": "That the great body of our state may go",
      "notes": [
        "body ... state] See note on III.i.41.",
        "go] Walk, carrying out the metaphor of Limbes."
      ]
    },
    "143": {
      "play": "In equal rank with the best-governed nation;",
      "notes": []
    },
    "144": {
      "play": "That war, or peace, or both at once, may be",
      "notes": [
        "That] So that, unless That goes back to such in l. 143. See note on I.i.198."
      ]
    },
    "145": {
      "play": "As things acquainted and familiar to us,",
      "notes": [
        "acquainted] N.E.D. (Acquainted ppl.a.): Familiar, through being known. arch. of things. [Quotes this line.]"
      ]
    },
    "146": {
      "play": "To the Chief Justice. In which you, father, shall",
      "notes": []
    },
    "147": {
      "play": "have foremost hand.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "148": {
      "play": "Our coronation done, we will accite,",
      "notes": [
        "accite] HAMMER (ed. 1743, glossary): To call, to summon."
      ]
    },
    "149": {
      "play": "As I before remembered, all our state.",
      "notes": [
        "remembered] N.E.D. (Remember v. 3): To record, mention, make mention of. Obs.",
        "state] N.E.D. (State sb. 26a): collect. sing. The rulers, nobles, or great men of a realm; the government, ruling body, or court. Obs. [Quotes this line.]"
      ]
    },
    "150": {
      "play": "And, God consigning to my good intents,",
      "notes": [
        "consigning] N.E.D. (Consign v. 5): To set one’s seal, subscribe, agree to anything. Obs. [Quotes only this line and Henry V v.ii.90, “And take with you free power to ratify, ... And we’ll consign thereto”.]"
      ]
    },
    "151": {
      "play": "No prince nor peer shall have just cause to say",
      "notes": []
    },
    "152": {
      "play": "God shorten Harry’s happy life one day.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "153": {
      "play": "[They exit.]",
      "notes": []
    }
  },
  "ACT 5, SCENE 3": {
    "1": {
      "play": "[Enter Sir John Falstaff, Shallow, Silence, Davy,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "2": {
      "play": "Bardolph, and Page.]",
      "notes": []
    },
    "3": {
      "play": "SHALLOW: Nay, you shall see my orchard, where, in an",
      "notes": [
        "orchard] SCHMIDT (1875): Garden."
      ]
    },
    "4": {
      "play": "arbor, we will eat a last year’s pippin of mine own",
      "notes": [
        "last year's pippin] CAPELL (Notes, 1779, p. 182): A pippin gather’d last autumn.—SCHMIDT (1875): Pippin, a kind of apple.",
        "graffing] N.E.D. (Graff v. 1): arch. To insert (a scion of one tree) into a different stock."
      ]
    },
    "5": {
      "play": "graffing, with a dish of caraways, and so forth.—",
      "notes": [
        "caraways] WARBURTON (ed. 1747): A comfit or confection [containing caraway seeds] so called in our author’s time.—GOLDSMITH (Var. ’73): The dish of carraways here mentioned was a dish of apples of that name.—[Most editors and commentators explain as sweetmeats or confections, but JACKSON"
      ]
    },
    "6": {
      "play": "Come, cousin Silence.—And then to bed.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "7": {
      "play": "FALSTAFF: Fore God, you have here a goodly dwelling,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "8": {
      "play": "and a rich.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "9": {
      "play": "SHALLOW: Barren, barren, barren, beggars all, beggars",
      "notes": [
        "] On the omission of the Q stage-direction from F see pp. 512 ff."
      ]
    },
    "10": {
      "play": "all, Sir John. Marry, good air.—Spread, Davy,",
      "notes": [
        "good air] HOLT WHITE (apud Steevens, ed. 1793): Justice Shallow alludes to a witticism frequent among rustics, who when talking of a healthy country pleasantly observe: “Yes, it is a good air, more run away than die.”—SCHMIDT (1874, s.v. Air): Proverbial: build there, carpenter, the air is sweet.",
        "Spread] N.E.D. (Spread v. 8b): To lay (a table) for a meal or other purpose."
      ]
    },
    "11": {
      "play": "spread, Davy. Well said, Davy.",
      "notes": [
        "Well said] See note on III.ii.277."
      ]
    },
    "12": {
      "play": "FALSTAFF: This Davy serves you for good uses. He is",
      "notes": []
    },
    "13": {
      "play": "your servingman and your husband.",
      "notes": [
        "husband] N.E.D. (Husband sb. 4): The manager of a household or establishment; a steward.—[It is unnecessary to suppose, as MALONE (ed. 1790) and DELIUS (ed. 1857) do, that -man is to be understood from Serving-man.—ED.]"
      ]
    },
    "14": {
      "play": "SHALLOW: A good varlet, a good varlet, a very good",
      "notes": [
        "varlet] COWL (ed. 1923): Servant.—[Used depreciatingly.—ED.]"
      ]
    },
    "15": {
      "play": "varlet, Sir John. By the Mass, I have drunk too",
      "notes": []
    },
    "16": {
      "play": "much sack at supper. A good varlet. Now sit down,",
      "notes": [
        "And] Q And.—DYCE (ed. 1857): The person who made the transcript of this play used for the folio, being accustomed to alter “and” (i.e. an) to “if,” misunderstood the force of the word in the present passage: here the “And” of the 4to is not equivalent to An (if),—it is the copulative conjunction."
      ]
    },
    "17": {
      "play": "now sit down.—Come, cousin.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "18": {
      "play": "SILENCE: Ah, sirrah, quoth he, we shall",
      "notes": [
        "Ah, sirrah] SCHMIDT (1875): Sometimes forming part of a soliloquy and addressed ... to the speaker himself.—[Cf. Romeo I.v.27, 124, As You Like It IV.iii.164.]",
        "quoth he] COWL (ed. 1923): Said he."
      ]
    },
    "19": {
      "play": "[Sings. Do nothing but eat and make good cheer,]",
      "notes": [
        "make good cheer] N.E.D. (Cheer sb. 6): To make good (etc.) cheer: to feast and make merry."
      ]
    },
    "20": {
      "play": "And praise God for the merry year,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "21": {
      "play": "When flesh is cheap and females dear,",
      "notes": [
        "dear] FARMER (Var. ’73, Appendix II) calls attention to the punning sense of the word in antithesis to cheape."
      ]
    },
    "22": {
      "play": "And lusty lads roam here and there",
      "notes": []
    },
    "23": {
      "play": "So merrily,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "24": {
      "play": "And ever among so merrily.",
      "notes": [
        "ever among] N.E.D. (Among adv. 1): During this (period), meanwhile, all the while, at the same time. Obs. [Quotes this line.]"
      ]
    },
    "25": {
      "play": "FALSTAFF: There’s a merry heart!—Good Master Silence,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "26": {
      "play": "I’ll give you a health for that anon.",
      "notes": [
        "give you a health] COWL (ed. 1923): Toast you, drink your health.—[Cf. Jonson, The Case Is Altered I.i (ed. Herford & Simpson, 1925+, iii. 112): “Ile giue you a health I faith”.]"
      ]
    },
    "27": {
      "play": "SHALLOW: Give Master Bardolph some wine, Davy.",
      "notes": [
        "Master Bardolph] On the difference between Q and F see p. 507."
      ]
    },
    "28": {
      "play": "DAVY, to the guests  Sweet sir, sit. I’ll be with you",
      "notes": []
    },
    "29": {
      "play": "anon. Most sweet sir, sit. Master page, good master",
      "notes": []
    },
    "30": {
      "play": "page, sit. Proface. What you want in meat, we’ll",
      "notes": [
        "Proface] THEOBALD (ed. 1733): I presume it a Contraction from the Italian Phrase, Bon vi profaccia; i.e. Much Good may’t do You.—N.E.D. (Proface int.): Obs. ([from] obs. French prou fasse! in full bon prou vous fasse!) A formula of welcome or good wishes at a dinner or other meal.",
        "meat] N.E.D. (Meat sb. 1): Food in general; usually, solid food; in contradistinction to drink. Now arch. and dial.",
        "tiny] See note on v.i.31."
      ]
    },
    "31": {
      "play": "have in drink, but you must bear. The heart’s all.",
      "notes": [
        "heart] JOHNSON (ed. 1765): That is, the intention with which the entertainment is given.—N.E.D. (Heart sb. 8): Disposition, temperament, character. Obs."
      ]
    },
    "32": {
      "play": "[He exits.]",
      "notes": []
    },
    "33": {
      "play": "SHALLOW: Be merry, Master Bardolph.—And, my little",
      "notes": [
        "in] Q ith is a compositor’s error: thy has attracted in to ith.—ED."
      ]
    },
    "34": {
      "play": "soldier there, be merry.",
      "notes": [
        "] Proverbial. See Jente (1926), No. 410."
      ]
    },
    "35": {
      "play": "SILENCE sings",
      "notes": []
    },
    "36": {
      "play": "Be merry, be merry, my wife has all,",
      "notes": [
        "my wife has all] BOSWELL (Var.): An equally good introduction to what follows [compared with Farmer’s emendation]. It is a proof that she is a shrew."
      ]
    },
    "37": {
      "play": "For women are shrews, both short and tall.",
      "notes": [
        "shrews] Q shrowes is an obsolete form of the word familiar in the 16th and 17th centuries."
      ]
    },
    "38": {
      "play": "’Tis merry in hall when beards wags all,",
      "notes": [
        "hall] SCHMIDT (1874): The largest room of a house.",
        "wags] On Q wags see note on i.iii.114."
      ]
    },
    "39": {
      "play": "And welcome merry Shrovetide.",
      "notes": [
        "merry Shrovetide] T. WARTON (apud Malone, Suppl., 1780): Formerly a season of extraordinary sport and feasting."
      ]
    },
    "40": {
      "play": "Be merry, be merry.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "41": {
      "play": "FALSTAFF: I did not think Master Silence had been a",
      "notes": [
        "had been] SCHMIDT (1874, p. 517): [The past perfect is used instead of the past tense] if the actual state is contrary to expectation.—[See FRANZ (3 ed., 1924) §657.]"
      ]
    },
    "42": {
      "play": "man of this mettle.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "43": {
      "play": "SILENCE: Who, I? I have been merry twice and once ere",
      "notes": [
        "twice and once] COWL (ed. 1923): An adverbial expression humorously denoting the repetition of an action or state in the lowest possible degree of frequency."
      ]
    },
    "44": {
      "play": "now.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "45": {
      "play": "[Enter Davy.]",
      "notes": []
    },
    "46": {
      "play": "DAVY, to the guests  There’s a dish of leather-coats for",
      "notes": [
        "leather-coats] N.E.D. (Leather sb. 6): A name for russet apples, from the roughness of their skin [quoting this line]."
      ]
    },
    "47": {
      "play": "you.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "48": {
      "play": "SHALLOW: Davy!",
      "notes": []
    },
    "49": {
      "play": "DAVY: Your Worship, I’ll be with you straight.—A cup",
      "notes": []
    },
    "50": {
      "play": "of wine, sir.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "51": {
      "play": "SILENCE sings",
      "notes": [
        "bear] SCHMIDT (1874): Have patience, be indulgent.",
        "once] N.E.D. (Once adv. 5): At some future time; one day. Now rare."
      ]
    },
    "52": {
      "play": "A cup of wine that’s brisk and fine,",
      "notes": [
        "brisk] N.E.D. (Brisk a. 4): Of liquors: Agreeably sharp or smarting to the taste [quoting this line].",
        "fine] ONIONS (1911): (Of wine) clear."
      ]
    },
    "53": {
      "play": "And drink unto thee, leman mine,",
      "notes": [
        "leman] HAMNER (ed. 1743, glossary): A sweet-heart, a gallant, or a mistress."
      ]
    },
    "54": {
      "play": "And a merry heart lives long-a.",
      "notes": [
        "merry] N.E.D. (Merry a. 3d): Hilarious from drink; slightly tipsy.",
        "a merry heart lives long-a] Proverbial. See JENTE (1926), No. 176. Cf. Love's Labour's Lost v.ii.18, “a light heart lives long”."
      ]
    },
    "55": {
      "play": "FALSTAFF: Well said, Master Silence.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "56": {
      "play": "SILENCE: And we shall be merry; now comes in the",
      "notes": []
    },
    "57": {
      "play": "sweet o’ th’ night.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "58": {
      "play": "FALSTAFF: Health and long life to you, Master Silence.",
      "notes": [
        "Health] See note on IV.i.35."
      ]
    },
    "59": {
      "play": "SILENCE sings",
      "notes": []
    },
    "60": {
      "play": "Fill the cup, and let it come,",
      "notes": [
        "let it come] COWL (ed. 1923): Pass on the cup, “drink and pass on.” So in 2 Henry VI II.iii.66: “Let it come, i’ faith, and I’ll pledge you all”; Sir John Oldcastle II.i [ed. Simpson, M.S.R., 1908, I. 676]: “Harp. Fill sweete Doll, Ile drinke to thee. Doll I pledge you sir, ... and I pray you let it come”; Heywood, I Fair Maid of the West (ed. Pearson, 1874, ii. 267): “Sp. ... Captaine, this health. Goodl. Let it come”; Massinger, The Great Duke of Florence IV.ii.194; Beaumont & Fletcher, Thierry and Theodoret II.iii (ed. Glover & Waller, 1905-10, x. 281]."
      ]
    },
    "61": {
      "play": "I’ll pledge you a mile to th’ bottom.",
      "notes": [
        "heart] N.E.D. (Heart sb. 15): As a term of appreciation or commendation: Man of courage or spirit.—[Cf. v.v.54.]",
        "a mile to th' bottom] HERFORD (ed. 1899): To the bottom if it were a mile."
      ]
    },
    "62": {
      "play": "SHALLOW: Honest Bardolph, welcome. If thou want’st",
      "notes": [
        "Honest] See note on II.iv.332."
      ]
    },
    "63": {
      "play": "anything and wilt not call, beshrew thy heart.—",
      "notes": [
        "beshrew] See note on II.iii.49."
      ]
    },
    "64": {
      "play": "Welcome, my little tiny thief, and welcome indeed",
      "notes": [
        "thief] ONIONS (1911): Term of reproach = wretch; used affectionately. —Cowt. (ed. 1923): An adaptation of the phrase \"little tiny page\" in the Ballad of Little Musgrave and Lady Barnard [Child, Popular Ballads, ii. 242 ff.]."
      ]
    },
    "65": {
      "play": "too. I’ll drink to Master Bardolph, and to all the",
      "notes": [
        "] Miss WINSTANLEY (ed. 1918): Bardolph is thinking joyfully how he would fleece him."
      ]
    },
    "66": {
      "play": "cabileros about London.",
      "notes": [
        "cabileros] N.E.D. (Cavalier sb. 2): A courtly gentleman, a gallant. (Like gallant, also applied about 1600, to a roistering, swaggering fellow.) [Quotes this line.]"
      ]
    },
    "67": {
      "play": "DAVY: I hope to see London once ere I die.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "68": {
      "play": "BARDOLPH: An I might see you there, Davy!",
      "notes": []
    },
    "69": {
      "play": "SHALLOW: By the Mass, you’ll crack a quart together,",
      "notes": [
        "crack] N.E.D. (Crack v. 10): To get at the contents of (a bottle or other vessel); to empty, drink [quoting this line.]"
      ]
    },
    "70": {
      "play": "ha, will you not, Master Bardolph?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "71": {
      "play": "BARDOLPH: Yea, sir, in a pottle-pot.",
      "notes": [
        "pottle-pot] See note on II.ii.77."
      ]
    },
    "72": {
      "play": "SHALLOW: By God’s liggens, I thank thee. The knave",
      "notes": [
        "By God's liggens, I thank] Q By Gods liggens I thanke. The oath is unique and remains unexplained."
      ]
    },
    "73": {
      "play": "will stick by thee, I can assure thee that. He will not",
      "notes": [
        "out] STAUNTON (ed. 1858): A sportsman’s saying applied to hounds.—ROLFE (ed. 1880): Will not fail you; a sportsman’s expression.—HUDSON (ed. 1880): Used of hounds when they ... pursue the game in concert, and stick by each other.—MADDEN (1891, p. 54): [Expresses] Davy’s powers of sticking to his quarry.—[But the examples adduced by these commentators are of hold in = pursue closely; no one has produced a passage with out, and N.E.D. does not hint at any use of out as a hunting term. Moreover, Antony II.vi.30, “I am not so well as I should be, but I’ll ne’er out”, quoted by ROLFE, makes it seem that the word meant what is called in the colloquial language of to-day to pass out, to become dead drunk. COWL (ed. 1923) quotes Massinger’s Great Duke of Florence IV.ii.209, where Petronella, after promising “I will not out”, falls down dead drunk.—Ed.]"
      ]
    },
    "74": {
      "play": "out, he. ’Tis true bred!",
      "notes": [
        "'Tis] Q a tis. It does not seem altogether likely that a = he in such an emphatic position. Perhaps it represents some exclamation and it in tis is used as at II.i.5.—ED."
      ]
    },
    "75": {
      "play": "BARDOLPH: And I’ll stick by him, sir.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "76": {
      "play": "SHALLOW: Why, there spoke a king. Lack nothing, be",
      "notes": [
        "be] This form of the present indicative singular is used especially after think; see FRANZ (3 ed., 1924) §171."
      ]
    },
    "77": {
      "play": "merry. (One knocks at door.) Look who’s at door",
      "notes": []
    },
    "78": {
      "play": "[there, ho. Who knocks?    Davy exits.]",
      "notes": []
    },
    "79": {
      "play": "FALSTAFF: Why, now you have done me right.",
      "notes": [
        "done me right] ONIONS (1911): Do (one) right, to do him justice, give him satisfaction, with ref[erence] to pledging a person by drinking to him.—COWL"
      ]
    },
    "80": {
      "play": "SILENCE sings",
      "notes": []
    },
    "81": {
      "play": "Do me right,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "82": {
      "play": "And dub me knight,",
      "notes": [
        "dub me knight] MALONE (Var. ’78): It was the custom of the good fellows of Shakespeare’s days to drink a very large draught of wine, and sometimes a less palatable potation, on their knees, to the health of their mistress. He who performed this exploit was dubb’d a knight for the evening. So, in the Yorkshire Tragedy, 1608 [i. 93 ff.]: “they call it knighting in London, when they drink vpon their knees. ... Come, follow me: Ile giue you all the degrees ont in order.”—[As COWL (ed. 1923) notes, this rite is performed in Summer’s Last Will and Testament 1065 ff. to the singing of “God Bacchus doe him right” &c.]"
      ]
    },
    "83": {
      "play": "Samingo.",
      "notes": [
        "Samingo] HANMER (ed. 1743): He means to say San Domingo.—T. WARTON (apud Hanmer, ed. 1770, glossary): But what is the meaning and propriety of the name here, has not yet been shewn. ... I remember a black-letter ballad, in which either a San Domingo, or a signior Domingo, is celebrated for his miraculous feats in drinking.—STEEVENS (Var. ’73): Perhaps Domingo is only the burthen of some old song.—TOLLET (Var. ’78): Of the gluttony and drunkenness of the Dominicans, one of their own order says thus in Weaver’s Funeral Monuments, p. cxxxi: ‘Sanctus Dominicus sit nobis semper amicus, cui canimus—siccat is ante lagenis—fratres qui non curant nisi ventres.’ Hence Domingo might ... become the burden of a drinking song.—CAPELL (Notes, 1779, p. 183): By this explication, we get no insight into the propriety of using it here, unless it could be prov’d—that saint Dominick was as jolly a fellow as some of his followers.—[Before long, “San Domingo” has become “a common burden of drinking-songs” (ROLFE, ed. 1880) and the saint “a drunkard’s patron saint” (Miss PORTER, ed. 1911). From the note above it should be apparent that Samingo is a phonetic spelling—or, as MALONE (ed. 1790) suggests, a drunken mispronunciation—of Sir Mingo, and Mingo or Domingo is simply the name of the hero of the song. In the version printed by Brown the name is Don Mingo.—Ed.]—G.E.P.A. (8 N. & Q. vii, 1895, p. 203): [In the song] there might possibly be an allusion to the Domingo Lomelyn whose nose is mentioned by Skelton (‘Why Come Ye not to Court?’), for whom see Nicolas’s ‘Privy Purse Expences of King Henry VIII,’ p. 315 [f.]."
      ]
    },
    "84": {
      "play": "Is ’t not so?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "85": {
      "play": "FALSTAFF: ’Tis so.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "86": {
      "play": "SILENCE: Is ’t so? Why then, say an old man can do",
      "notes": []
    },
    "87": {
      "play": "somewhat.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "88": {
      "play": "[Enter Davy.]",
      "notes": []
    },
    "89": {
      "play": "DAVY: An ’t please your Worship, there’s one Pistol",
      "notes": []
    },
    "90": {
      "play": "come from the court with news.",
      "notes": []
    },
