      "play": "[Enter Pistol.]",
      "notes": []
    },
    "93": {
      "play": "How now, Pistol?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "94": {
      "play": "PISTOL: Sir John, God save you.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "95": {
      "play": "FALSTAFF: What wind blew you hither, Pistol?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "96": {
      "play": "PISTOL: Not the ill wind which blows no man to good.",
      "notes": [
        "no man] On the difference between Q and F see p. 507."
      ]
    },
    "97": {
      "play": "Sweet knight, thou art now one of the greatest men",
      "notes": []
    },
    "98": {
      "play": "in this realm.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "99": {
      "play": "SILENCE: By ’r Lady, I think he be, but Goodman Puff of",
      "notes": [
        "Goodman] N.E.D. (Goodman 3b): Prefixed to names of persons under the rank of gentlemen, esp. yeomen or farmers. Obs.—[Cf. IV.iv.33.]"
      ]
    },
    "100": {
      "play": "Barson.",
      "notes": [
        "Barson] STEEVENS (Var. '73) [quoting Edwards’s MSS.]: Barton.—PERCY (Var. ’73, appendix): Barston is a village in Warwickshire, lying between Coventry and Solyhull.—SINGER (ed. 1856): As Barston is beyond Coventry, it is possible that Barton on the Heath may be meant, the residence of the Lamberts, which is much nearer to the scene in Gloucestershire.—SUGDEN (1925, p. 48): Barcheston (locally pronounced Barson). Village in Warwickshire, on the Stour, 10 miles south of Stratford.—GOVER (1936, pp. 55, 297) refers to this line under Barston, but gives Barston also as a variant form, apparently uncommon, of Barcheston."
      ]
    },
    "101": {
      "play": "PISTOL: Puff?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "102": {
      "play": "Puff in thy teeth, most recreant coward base!—",
      "notes": [
        "recreant] SCHMIDT (1875): Originally =retracting one’s errors (recredens) and crying for mercy. Hence =cowardly."
      ]
    },
    "103": {
      "play": "Sir John, I am thy Pistol and thy friend,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "104": {
      "play": "And helter-skelter have I rode to thee,",
      "notes": [
        "rode] See note on I.i.147."
      ]
    },
    "105": {
      "play": "And tidings do I bring, and lucky joys,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "106": {
      "play": "And golden times, and happy news of price.",
      "notes": [
        "golden] N.E.D. (Golden a. 7): Of a time or epoch: Characterized by great prosperity and happiness; flourishing, joyous [quoting this line]."
      ]
    },
    "107": {
      "play": "FALSTAFF: I pray thee now, deliver them like a man of",
      "notes": [
        "them] I.e. news, as also in I. 103 below: see note on I.i.36."
      ]
    },
    "108": {
      "play": "this world.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "109": {
      "play": "PISTOL: A foutre for the world and worldlings base!",
      "notes": [
        "foutre] WHITE (ed. 1859): A corruption of an indecent French word not unfrequently used ... as an expression of contempt. [It means copulation: there is an English cognate.—ED.]"
      ]
    },
    "110": {
      "play": "I speak of Africa and golden joys.",
      "notes": [
        "] COWL (T.L.S. 26 March 1925, p. 222): Pistol’s cry of exultation ... would recall the images of wealth and splendour that are associated in Tamburlaine the Great with Fez, Argier, and Morocco (cf. “Not for all Afric” (2 Tamburlaine I.iii.12); “costly cloth of massy gold” (ib. IV.ii.40); and “Afric captains taken in the field, Whose ransom made them {their captors} march in coats of gold, With costly jewels hanging at their ears, And shining stones upon their lofty crests.” (1 Tamburlaine I.ii.142 ff.))."
      ]
    },
    "111": {
      "play": "FALSTAFF: O base Assyrian knight, what is thy news?",
      "notes": [
        "Assyrian] Miss WINSTANLEY (ed. 1918): Often used as a term of abuse and equivalent to “heathen”.—NOBLE (1935, p. 262): In Isa. x. 6, 13 (Bishops’ Bible) the Assyrians were definitely associated with robbery and pillage and hence possibly the significance of Falstaff’s [epithet]."
      ]
    },
    "112": {
      "play": "Let King Cophetua know the truth thereof.",
      "notes": [
        "Cophetua] Q Couetua.—JOHNSON (ed. 1765) refers to his note on Love’s Labour’s Lost IV.i.64, where he alludes to the ballad of The King and the Beggar in Percy’s Reliques, which Percy printed from Richard Johnson’s Crowne Garland of Goulden Roses (1612). It begins: “I read that once in Affrica A princely wight did raine, Who had to name Cophetua.”—RANN (ed. 1789): Pistol’s mention of [Africa] reminds Falstaff [of King Cophetua].—[The ballad is also alluded to in Romeo II.i.14 and Richard II V.iii.80.]"
      ]
    },
    "113": {
      "play": "SILENCE sings",
      "notes": []
    },
    "114": {
      "play": "And Robin Hood, Scarlet, and John.",
      "notes": [
        "] STEEVENS (Var. ’78): This scrap (as Dr. Percy has observed in the first volume of his Reliques of Ancient English Poetry [on Lancelot du Lake]) is taken from a stanza in the old ballad of Robin Hood and the Pindar of Wakefield [Child, Popular Ballads iii. 131].—ANDERS (1904, p. 164): It must be admitted, however, that the names ... are to be found together, in this order, in a later version of R[obin] H[ood] and Queen Katherine 1, 2 (Child iii. 202); compare,"
      ]
    },
    "115": {
      "play": "PISTOL: Shall dunghill curs confront the Helicons,",
      "notes": [
        "Helicons] HUDSON (ed. 1880): For poets ... Pistol has got his memory so stored with scraps of plays and ballads, that he imagines himself a poet, or a Heliconian.—Miss WINSTANLEY (ed. 1918): Pistol evidently mistakes Mount Helicon for the name of some nation or tribe.—COWL (ed. 1923): Pistol probably confounds Mount Helicon, the haunt of the Muses, with the Muses themselves.—F. G. STOKES (1924, p. 141): Used by Pistol for ‘Muses.’ ... It is not necessary to suppose that Pistol meant ‘Heliconides.’—SUGDEN (1925, p. 246): I suppose by Helicons he means true poets, though it is wasted labour to try to discover anything but idle rhodomontade in much that he says."
      ]
    },
    "116": {
      "play": "And shall good news be baffled?",
      "notes": [
        "baffled] N.E.D. (Baffle v. 1): To subject to public disgrace or infamy; spec. to disgrace a perjured knight with infamy‘[by hanging him up by the heels]. Obs."
      ]
    },
    "117": {
      "play": "Then, Pistol, lay thy head in Furies’ lap.",
      "notes": [
        "Furies] ROOT (1903, p. 64): Shakespeare is quite ignorant of the Eumenides of the Greek tragedians, the personified stingings of conscience. ... To Shakespeare they are merely fiends, or devils."
      ]
    },
    "118": {
      "play": "SHALLOW: Honest gentleman, I know not your",
      "notes": [
        "Honest] See note on II.iv.332."
      ]
    },
    "119": {
      "play": "breeding.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "120": {
      "play": "PISTOL: Why then, lament therefor.",
      "notes": [
        "] MALONE (Var.): So, in Marlowe’s Massacre at Paris [xviii. 150]: “The Guise is slain, and I rejoice therefore.” —DEIGHTON quotes Henry V III.vi.51, “Pist. Why then, rejoice therefore”; and II.iii.5-6, “Pist. ... for Falstaff he is dead, And we must yearn therefore”.—COWL (T.L.S. 26 March 1925, p. 222): Shakespeare, moreover, may have wished to ridicule the pedantic use of the pronoun “therefore,” particularly in climaxes. The anti-climax that was, in fact, the result usually achieved may be exemplified from Greene’s Alphonsus King of Arragon III.ii [ed. Collins, 1905, i. 107]:—“Take her ..."
      ]
    },
    "121": {
      "play": "SHALLOW: Give me pardon, sir. If, sir, you come with",
      "notes": []
    },
    "122": {
      "play": "news from the court, I take it there’s but two ways,",
      "notes": [
        "but] ABBOTT (1870, §128): Such instances as this, where but [=except] follows not a negative but a superlative, are rare."
      ]
    },
    "123": {
      "play": "either to utter them, or to conceal them. I am, sir,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "124": {
      "play": "under the King in some authority.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "125": {
      "play": "PISTOL: Under which king, besonian? Speak or die.",
      "notes": [
        "] PRIESTLEY (1925, p. 75): A whole school of drama is being parodied by this ragged grotesque. There is one common type of romantic literature that is summed up to perfection in the single question he addresses to Shallow.",
        "besonian] THEOBALD (letter to Warburton, 17 Jany. 1729): So in 2 Henry VI [iv.i.134]. “Great men oft die by vile bezonians”. ... metaphorically, a base Scoundrel.—J. HUNTER (1845, ii. 56 f.): It was a word used in the army for “a raw souldier, vnexpert in his weapon, and other Military points.” Thus it is explained by Barret in his Explanation of Terms added to his Theorike and Practike of Modern Warres, fol. 1598, [sig. Y4]. [According to N.E.D., this is the Italian sense of the word.]—ANON. (Edinburgh Review cxxx, 1869, p. 108): Pistol could not mean to suggest that Shallow was a beggar, a needy soldier, a knave, or a scoundrel. He uses bezonian simply as a thrasonical phrase of martial contempt for the bucolic mind, an intimation that Shallow ... is after all no better than a peasant.—DEIGHTON (ed. 1893): It seems to me hyper-criticism to credit Pistol with any discerning employment of the term.—N.E.D. (Bezonian b): (as a term of contempt) Needy beggar, base fellow, knave, rascal [quoting this line]."
      ]
    },
    "126": {
      "play": "SHALLOW: Under King Harry.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "127": {
      "play": "PISTOL: Harry the Fourth, or Fifth?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "128": {
      "play": "SHALLOW: Harry the Fourth.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "129": {
      "play": "PISTOL: A foutre for thine office!—",
      "notes": []
    },
    "130": {
      "play": "Sir John, thy tender lambkin now is king.",
      "notes": [
        "lambkin] N.E.D. (Lambkin 2): A young tender person; chiefly used as a term of endearment [quoting this line as its earliest example]."
      ]
    },
    "131": {
      "play": "Harry the Fifth’s the man. I speak the truth.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "132": {
      "play": "When Pistol lies, do this and fig me, like",
      "notes": [
        "do this] Cowl. (ed. 1923) takes this as meaning the same thing as figge-me, but Mr. H. N. Paul suggests to me that, instead of referring twice to the same insulting gesture, Pistol first draws his index finger across his throat, saying \"do this\", and then makes a fig. The order, however, would be anticlimactic.—ED."
      ]
    },
    "133": {
      "play": "The bragging Spaniard.     Pistol makes a fig.",
      "notes": [
        "fig me] Johnson (ed. 1765): To fig, in Spanish, higas dar, is to insult by putting the thumb between the fore and middle finger. From this Spanish custom we yet say in contempt, a fig for you.—[Cf. 2 Henry VI ii. iii. 67, \"a fig for Peter!\"; Henry V iii. vi. 56, \"Pist. ... figo for thy friendship!\", iii. vi. 58, \"Pist. The fig of Spain!\", iv. i. 60, \"Pist. The figo for thee, then!\"; Merry Wives i. iii. 27-8, \"Pist. ... a fico for the phrase!\"]"
      ]
    },
    "134": {
      "play": "FALSTAFF: What, is the old king dead?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "135": {
      "play": "PISTOL: As nail in door. The things I speak are just.",
      "notes": [
        "just] See note on iii. ii. 86."
      ]
    },
    "136": {
      "play": "FALSTAFF: Away, Bardolph.—Saddle my horse.—",
      "notes": []
    },
    "137": {
      "play": "Master Robert Shallow, choose what office thou",
      "notes": []
    },
