    "10": {
      "play": "thee what, thou damned tripe-visaged rascal: an the",
      "notes": []
    },
    "11": {
      "play": "child I now go with do miscarry, thou wert better",
      "notes": []
    },
    "12": {
      "play": "thou hadst struck thy mother, thou paper-faced",
      "notes": []
    },
    "13": {
      "play": "villain.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "14": {
      "play": "HOSTESS: O the Lord, that Sir John were come! I would",
      "notes": []
    },
    "15": {
      "play": "make this a bloody day to somebody. But I pray God",
      "notes": []
    },
    "16": {
      "play": "the fruit of her womb might miscarry.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "17": {
      "play": "BEADLE: If it do, you shall have a dozen of cushions",
      "notes": []
    },
    "18": {
      "play": "again; you have but eleven now. Come, I charge you",
      "notes": []
    },
    "19": {
      "play": "both go with me, for the man is dead that you and",
      "notes": []
    },
    "20": {
      "play": "Pistol beat amongst you.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "21": {
      "play": "DOLL: I’ll tell you what, you thin man in a censer, I will",
      "notes": [
        "thin man in a censer] WARBURTON (apud Theobald, ed. 1733): A Censer ... is ... a Perfume-pan. ... I have seen several antique Censers ... which, being of Brass, were beat out exceeding thin. In the Middle of the Bottom was rais’d up, in emboss’d Work, with the Hammer, the Figure of some Saint in a kind of barbarous hollow Bass-relief, the whole Diameter of the Bottom. ... Now this thin beadle is compar’d, for his Substance, to one of these thin hammer’d Figures, with the same kind of Humour that Pistol in the Merry Wives [i.i.146], calls Slender a laten Bilboe.—CAPELL (Notes, 1779, p. 183): Their ill-shap’d and ill-habited figures furnish Petruchio with a simile for his wife’s gown, in [Shrew iv.iii.91, “‘Here’s a snip and nip and cut and slish and slash, Like to a censer in a barber’s shop’].”—STEEVENS (ed. 1793): Dr. Warburton’s explanation is erroneous. The embossed figure to which Doll refers, was in the middle of the pierced convex lid of the censer. [Censers were commonly burned in houses to sweeten the air.]—WHITE (ed. 1859): The thin officer wore some kind of cap which she likened to a censer.—ROLFE (ed. 1880): [White] is probably right.—GOLLANCZ (ed. 1895, p. 166) agrees with White; other editors follow Steevens.—N.E.D. (Censer sb¹ b): app.=Cassolelte [i.e. incense-burner]. (The commentators are not agreed as to exactly what is referred to.)"
      ]
    },
    "22": {
      "play": "have you as soundly swinged for this, you bluebottle",
      "notes": [
        "bluebottle] Q blewbotle.—JOHNSON (ed. 1765): A name I suppose given to the beadle from the colour of his livery."
      ]
    },
    "23": {
      "play": "rogue, you filthy famished correctioner. If you be",
      "notes": [
        "swinged] ONIONS (1917): Thrash[ed], belabor[ed], belabour[ed].",
        "correctioner] SCHMIDT (1874): One who inflicts chastisement. [N.E.D. quotes no other example.]"
      ]
    },
    "24": {
      "play": "not swinged, I’ll forswear half-kirtles.",
      "notes": [
        "half-kirtles] Miss LINTHICUM (1936, pp. 185 f.): The sixteenth-century kirtle worn by women was used over petticoats and farthingale as an outside dress, but a gown or cloak was worn over it. It consisted of a separate bodice, called ‘a pair of bodies’, and a skirt. ... The skirt of the kirtle was called a ‘half-kirtle’. Doll’s exclamation ... means that she will give up a necessary part of woman’s dress.—[JOHNSON’s notion (ed. 1765) that the half-kirtle was the prostitute’s uniform is a flight of fancy.—ED.]"
      ]
    },
    "25": {
      "play": "BEADLE: Come, come, you she-knight-errant, come.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "26": {
      "play": "HOSTESS: O God, that right should thus overcome",
      "notes": [
        "about] This could mean because of (see note on V.i.27) or in the company of (see note on III.ii.235).",
        "O God, that right should thus overcome might!] TILLEY (S.A.B. v, 1930, p. 106): In these words she manages to say the opposite of what she intends ... by transposing the words of the old proverb, \"Might overcomes right.\"—[On the proverb see JENTE (1926), No. 232.]"
      ]
    },
    "27": {
      "play": "might! Well, of sufferance comes ease.",
      "notes": [
        "of sufferance comes ease] Proverbial. See JENTE (1926), No. 303.",
        "sufferance] SCHMIDT (1875): Distress, misery, suffering.",
        "ease] N.E.D. (Ease sb. 2): Comfort, convenience; formerly also, advantage, profit, and in stronger sense, pleasure, enjoyment."
      ]
    },
    "28": {
      "play": "DOLL: Come, you rogue, come, bring me to a justice.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "29": {
      "play": "HOSTESS: Ay, come, you starved bloodhound.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "30": {
      "play": "DOLL: Goodman Death, Goodman Bones!",
      "notes": [
        "Goodman] See note on v.iii.81."
      ]
    },
    "31": {
      "play": "HOSTESS: Thou atomy, thou!",
      "notes": [
        "atomy] Q Atomy.—N.E.D. (Atomy¹ 2): ({from] Anatomy by aphæresis of an-, due to its being taken for the indef. article) An 'emaciated or withered living body, a walking skeleton [quoting this line as its earliest example; but anatomy is similarly used earlier, e.g. in Errors vi.238].—[See p. 507.]"
      ]
    },
    "32": {
      "play": "DOLL: Come, you thin thing, come, you rascal.",
      "notes": [
        "rascal] See note on ii.iv.43."
